<HEADLINE>Egyptian rulers retain power</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110145</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CAIRO: Egypt's ruling party was headed for an overwhelming victory in
parliamentary elections which opposition parties said were rigged on a massive
scale.
The National Democratic Party won 87 of the first 96 seats decided in
Wednesday's first round of voting, during which at least four people were
killed and about 100 injured. Opposition candidates warned the polls could
create a shift in support of violence by militant Islamist groups seeking to
topple the government.
Libya arms seized
GENOA: Italian police have seized 10 tons of sophisticated combat aircraft
parts which were headed for Libya in contravention of a UN embargo imposed
after the 1988 Lockerbie bombing. Investigators believe British, American, and
Canadian companies supplied the equipment found in two containers, one on a
Libyan-bound ship in the port of Genoa and the other at Turin airport.
Trump reweds
NEW YORK: Ivana Trump, 46, ex-wife of US property mogul Donald Trump who
received a #16m divorce settlement, has married 51-year-old Italian businessman
Riccardo Mazzuchelli after a four-year courtship.
Doctor honoured
LOS ANGELES: Dr Jack Kevorkian, the Michigan-based GP who has helped
terminally-ill people to commit suicide, has been named winner of the 1995
Sovereign Fund award for contributing to individual freedom in the United
States. ``No personal right could be more basic than the legal right to live
and die as one chooses,'' said Kurt Simon, chairman of the private fund.
US backs Solana
WASHINGTON: The United States has signalled support for Spanish Foreign
Minister Javier Solana as Nato's next secretary general. Officials said a broad
consensus was forming to back him in the US and Europe, and the appointment is
expected to be formally made next week, when Nato Foreign Ministers meet in
Brussels.
Shelling kills 17
KABUL: At least 17 people were killed and 26 wounded when rockets slammed into
a busy market district in central Kabul yesterday. The attack followed a
government victory against the rebel Islamic Taleban militia on Tuesday night.
On Sunday, at least 39 people were killed and 140 wounded in an air raid on
Kabul for which the government blamed the Taleban.
`Dwarf' found
NEW YORK: Astronomers have identified a celestial object discovered 19 light
years from Earth as the most convincing image yet of a brown dwarf, a stellar
object that is less than a star but more than a planet.
Walesa son free
WARSAW: A Polish appeal court has ruled one of President Lech Walesa's sons,
convicted of causing a road accident while drunk, will not have to go to jail.
The court suspended and cut a two-year jail sentence on Przemyslaw Walesa, 21,
after hearing psychiatrists' reports that he was not fully in control of his
actions.
Leeson cash-in
SINGAPORE: Former futures trader Nick Leeson is today making his second court
appearance in Singapore to reveal his plea to charges of committing fraud and
forgery in the collapse of Barings Bank. Capitalising on his misfortunes, a
merchandising frenzy in the republic has resulted in a new cocktail called the
``Bank Breaker'', a teeshirt proclaiming ``Barings Learns a Leeson'', and a
board game called ``In the Nick of Time''.
</TEXT>
