<HEADLINE>Former Gunner blasts back</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>41</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975110146</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SACKED Arsenal manager George Graham continues to hit back at his detractors by
insisting that he has been made a scapegoat for some of the wider ills in the
game.
In a magazine interview, the former Highbury manager claimed: ``I was a
high-profile manager, a successful manager, and the FA were determined to make
an example of me. It was as if the rest of football's sleaze would disappear
overnight if they could nail me. But if they think that, then they are just
kidding themselves.''
Graham is still adamant that Arsenal should have backed him. ``They backed me
for four or five months,'' he said. ``Then, when the Premier League inquiry
team unearthed some `new evidence,' which, in my opinion, was questionable
anyway, they took only a couple of minutes to sack me.
``At the very least I expected the club to wait until I was actually charged
with something or until the FA had actually announced a verdict. That is what
is happening at other clubs. There have been numerous other allegations, about
players as well as managers, but the other clubs are standing by their staff.''
Graham admits at being surprised by Radio Five's decision to drop him. ``I was
disappointed,'' he said. ``The BBC hired me after the FA hearing. They knew I
was banned and they knew the reasons I was banned. They knew everything about
me. And they were great to work for. I just felt a bit embarrassed for the
producer who hired me.
``He had to tell me that my contract was being terminated. I felt a bit for
him, because it definitely wasn't his decision. It was people upstairs at the
BBC pulling strings.''
Graham says he still has a deep affection for Arsenal. ``Nothing has changed,''
he said. ``I've had a great love for the club since my days as a player in the
70s. I still have a lot of friends there and in the stands at Highbury. And
they're good friends. It's just that they're not on the board of directors.''
But there is one thing that confounds him about Bruce Rioch's new Highbury
regime. ``The money the club is now spending and the salaries it is paying.
That has shocked me,'' he said.
</TEXT>
