<HEADLINE>Concern is expressed over role of supervisor SFA give Gascoigne and Brown one-match bans</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER CHIEF FOOTBALL WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975110147</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RANGERS' controversial midfield player Paul Gascoigne was handed a one-match
ban yesterday after the much-publicised meeting of the SFA Disciplinary
Committee.
That will be added to a similar punishment which the player must serve after a
booking in the Old Firm game last month carried him over the penalty points'
mark for the season.
The Ibrox reserve-team coach John Brown also was given a single-match
suspension following an incident in the same game, against Aberdeen at Ibrox,
which brought Gascoigne to the SFA headquarters at Park Gardens in Glasgow
yesterday.
Two more players, Alan McLaren, of Rangers, and Aberdeen's Billy Dodds, had
their cases continued because of ongoing inquiries into the game. The players
asked that the matter be dealt with at a later date and this was accepted by
the football authorities.
The explosive nature of the match between Rangers and Aberdeen on November 11
had brought the four players in front of the Disciplinary Committee, and while
television evidence is not yet accepted, the views of the referee supervisors
have become important to the committee.
That was the soccer area yesterday which was most argued as Alan Lawrence, of
Hearts, and Airdrie's Sean Sweeney also were dealt with on what the supervisor
said and received one-match suspensions.
Later, both Rangers and the Players' Union leader Tony Higgins expressed
concern at the growing involvement of the supervisors and the possible
undermining of the authority of the referees.
In a statement issued from Ibrox late yesterday afternoon, Rangers spelled out
their long-term worries over the situation.
They said: ``We accept the SFA Disciplinary Committee's decision today and, in
the circumstances, are of the opinion that, on this occasion, we have received
a fair hearing from the Association.
``We continue to believe, however, that a referee supervisor should not be
utilised as a second referee in the stand and, if this were to become a
practice, we are convinced that this would have a very damaging effect on our
game and would totally undermine the authority of the match officials.
``Whilst accepting the Committee's decision, we believe that certain aspects of
the reporting of disciplinary matters require close scrutiny and we will be
raising this with the Scottish Football Association.''
Higgins repeated the worries of the growing influence of the supervisor and
added: ``We cannot allow the authority of the referee to be undermined. That
would be wrong.
Higgins represented the players yesterday and revealed that the Ibrox men had
been instructed by club director Donald Findlay not to answer direct questions
about the various incidents. Higgins, in fact, answered on behalf of the
players.
SFA chief executive Jim Farry insisted later: ``I hope that this matter is now
at an end. The Disciplinary Committee has dealt with the matter fairly and we
would hope that this is the end of the affair.''
The Rangers-Aberdeen clash, and its various incidents, were highlighted by
television and, while referee John Rowbotham took no action, the players were
summoned to appear because of the report of supervisor Donald McVicar.
Similarly, Alan Lawrence was called up because of an off-the-ball clash with
Rangers' defender Craig Moore, which was also seen by a referee supervisor.
Airdrie defender Sean Sweeney's kick at the grounded Dundee midfield man Morten
Wieghorst in the Coca-Cola Cup semi-final at McDiarmid Park was in the same
category. However, Sweeney will miss a total of six games because this offence
carries him into a points situation which already brings with it a five-game
ban.
Dumbarton goalkeeper Ian McFarlane was suspended for five games after being
red-carded twice in a game against Airdrie on November ll.
Gascoigne will miss matches against Partick Thistle and Motherwell - again, he
had exceeded the points total which counts for automatic disciplinary action.
The rumblings over the role of the superisor will continue but, surely, once
teleision evidence is admitted, that problem will vanish.
</TEXT>
