<HEADLINE>Stock Exchange bows to pressure</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<FLAG>business digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975110148</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Stock Exchange has dealt a blow to traditional market-making by deciding to
launch an order-driven dealing system where investors will post firm prices at
which they are prepared to buy or sell a specific number of shares.
In contrast, market-makers are obliged at all times to quote firm prices at
which they will buy or sell shares, deriving an income from the spread between
the buy and sell prices. Institutions complain that this makes dealing more
expensive, particularly for routine trading.
Market makers fear that an order driven system will take business away from
them and have resisted a move towards away from the present system. The
Exchange has decided to bow to institutional pressure and plans to have an
order-driven system up and running next August.
The move is also expected to help London's competitiveness as a share-dealing
centre in Europe, where order-driven trading methods are the norm.
Matthey setback
JOHNSON Matthey has suffered a setback in its car pollution control business,
it revealed yesterday. Operating profits from converters business slumped by
#5.7m to #12.5m in the six months to September 30. Overall pre-tax profits for
the metals and components group were #47m compared with #45m. The interim
dividend is lifted to 4.4p from 4.2p with earnings at 16.7p against 15.9p.
Enterprise post
GRAMPIAN Enterprise yesterday named Professor Alan Sim as its new chief
executive to take over from the retiring Hance Fullerton in February. Professor
Sim, who defeated 120 applicants for the post, is presently employed in
Aberdeen by both McDermott Marine Construction as division director and The
Robert Gordon University as the BP Professor of Engineering Education.
MEPC warning
MEPC said conditions in the UK property market remained tough, despite
reporting a lift in its own profits yesterday. It made pre-tax profits of
#122.6m in the year to September 30 compared with #105.9m in the previous 12
months. Total dividends stay at 20p on earnings per share increased to 21p from
20.1p.
Camelot capture
RICHARD Brown, deputy director-general of the Association of British Chambers
of Commerce, is leaving to become head of government affairs at National
Lottery operator Camelot.
Sale agreed
JOHNSON Fry Holdings is selling its personal financial planning business,
Johnson Fry Financial Services in a #1.25m deal to a newly-formed company
controlled by its management.
</TEXT>
