<HEADLINE>Five to take a break</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOSEPH DILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110149</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GREAT Britain's success in securing a place in the Atlanta Olympics is having a
disruptive effect on the Scottish indoor season, writes Joseph Dillon.
Rhona Simpson, Susan MacDonald, Diane Renilson, Susan Fraser, and Pauline
Robertson have all been instructed by the British management to take a break
from hockey until the turn of the year.
This will be a blow to Edinburgh Ladies as they start their programme tomorrow
at the Bell's Sports Centre at Perth. They are attempting to win the title for
the fourth successive year, but will be deprived of three of their players.
Also affected is the Scottish squad, currently in training for the finals of
European Nations' Cup in Glasgow's Kelvin Hall from January 26 to 28.
It means coach Andrew Scoular is now in a quandary whether to select his squad
on previous form or to wait until the Great Britain players are free from their
restrictions to stake their claim for places.
Meanwhile Edinburgh Ladies have been recruiting new talent. Their drive has
been so successful that they will be putting out two teams in the league this
season, with Pentland competing in the second division.
Despite the influx of new players, Edinburgh will find it difficult to retain
their title. They play all their main contenders before Christmas.
</TEXT>
