<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Drinking isn't working</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCIS SHENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>98</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110151</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
'TIS the season to be jolly - and that's the trouble. Even the word ``jolly''
is used as a synonym for mildly drunk. This is the month when over-indulging in
drink is not only condoned, it is positively encouraged.
Repeated advertising campaigns have helped to alter public opinion about
drinking and driving but the misuse of alcohol, even at work, still tends to be
either covered up or ignored.
Attitudes, though, are beginning to change. Such surveys as have been carried
out suggest a definite shift toward both management and employees adopting what
are usually described as ``more appropriate'' drinking habits, especially
during the working day. The idea of a drink to ``help'' you through the day or
to unwind at night is seen by more and more people for what it is: a danger
sign of serious problems to come if action is not taken.
There are more serious considerations. Under regulations inspired by the
European Union and introduced two years ago, employers must make an assessment
of health and safety risks to their staff and take preventative measures. An
employer who allows a worker to threaten his own or others' safety through
drink is opening himself up to actions for damages and perhaps prosecution. And
action is increasingly being prompted by employers. More than 60% of the
managers questioned said their company had an alcohol policy.
The most common policies were to ban drink from the premises, to ban any
drinking at all during the working day or to forbid employees to be ``under the
influence''.
Many leading employers participate in awards called A Working Concern, the
first Scotland-wide scheme to recognise alcohol policies at work. It is run by
the Scottish Council on Alcohol (SCA), a charity to promote sensible drinking
and the first agency in Britain to promote the idea of alcohol policies in the
workplace.
The awards are supported by CBI Scotland, the Scottish TUC, Scottish Office,
Scottish Enterprise, the Confederation of Scottish Local Authorities, and local
councils on alcohol.
More surprisingly, they are sponsored by the Portman Group, which is funded by
Britain's eight biggest drink producers including Guinness which includes
United Distillers, Allied Distillers, Scottish &amp; Newcastle, and Seagram.
``It is necessary to get the drinks industry's motives straight,'' says its
director Dr John Rae. ``They are principally commercial. The industry knows
that unless alcohol misuse can be reduced by education and by measures that
target particular problems, governments may impose across-the-board
restrictions.
``We make no secret of the fact that we are funded by the drinks industry and
that we hope to prevent across-the-board restrictions.''
The awards scheme was designed to stimulate further interest by rewarding
employers. There are still many employers who have not yet developed alcohol
policies.
Awards are not made simply for banning drink. Policies should have a clear
procedure to deal with the misuse of alcohol and must promote sensible drinking
throughout the company. There must be a strategy for prevention and to
encourage staff with problems to accept help as soon as possible. One example
is to insist that those who have to be disciplined for an occurrence which
involved drinking in some way have the chance to seek treatment from an
approved source without it appearing on their work record.
If he or she refused to admit there was a drink problem, the disciplinary
procedure would continue as normal.
At what point drink becomes a problem may vary with the individual. Current
health guidelines advise men not to take more than 21 units of alcohol per
week, less for women, and that two or three days a week should be ``dry'' days.
Some experts prefer the term ``drink dependence'' to alcoholism. Relying on a
couple of quick drinks after work and ``social'' drinking which depends on
rounding up anybody available to drink with are unhealthy habits.
``It is important for all companies, no matter how large or small, to establish
policies that encourage a responsible attitude to alcohol and identify and help
individuals who may have problems,'' says Dr Rae.
