<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pickering fails</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110152</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KAREN Pickering, the Commonwealth champion, could finish only seventh in the
final of the 100 metres freestyle at the second World Short Course
Championships in Rio yesterday.
Pickering landed a bronze medal two years ago at the inaugural championships in
a British record time of 54.39 seconds. However, she was never on that pace in
Brazil and finished last in 55.52 - more than two seconds behind winner Le
Jingyi, from China.
``I could not believe it when I turned and saw the scoreboard. I kept waiting
for them to change my time,'' said Pickering.
She felt her first 50m in the morning heats had been slow and explained: ``I
tried to go out faster in the final and perhaps I kicked too hard, which is
something I tend to do when I try to go faster.''
With the start delayed by more than an hour because of a power failure,
Pickering said she had been distracted when European champion Franziska van
Almsick, of Germany, was disqualified for a false start.
The German's long-awaited battle with Le Jingyi never took place as the German,
in an outside lane, was thrown out after the judges decided she had voluntarily
false-started.
It was a good day for Australia, with Scott Miller winning the men's 100m
butterfly, Susan O'Neill the women's 200m butterfly, and Matthew Dunn the men's
400m medley.
</TEXT>
