<DOCID>GH951201-000008</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The most-fancied Fiat - a nice piece of work if you can get it</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROSS FINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>88</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110153</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NOW that November and the Scottish Motor Show are behind us, it may seem an odd
time of year to be hankering after an open two-seater, writes ROSS FINLAY. But
an informal poll of friends and colleagues who attended the show made it clear
that, in retrospect, one car they all fancied was the Fiat Barchetta.
A rather more sophisticated affair than the brute-force Austin-Healey 3000 with
which it shares this page, the Barchetta is the most recent vehicle to show
that the Styling Centre in Turin, which also designed the closed Fiat Coupe, is
being given its head.
Some designers employed by major companies mutter privately that their
employers prefer to play safe. Fiat under Paolo Cantarella is certainly not
like that. The Coupe is a real eye-catcher, with wing ``slashes'' that very few
of Fiat's rivals would have taken a chance with on a full production car. And
the Barchetta combines modernity with real international style.
As the example on the stand at the SECC showed, there is something exactly
right about the side elevation and rear view of the Barchetta. The very
slightly curving seam which runs above the front and rear wheel arches, and
dips a little at the door, jogs the memory of anybody familiar with Fifties
sports-racing cars.
A little like a Cooper-MG, or the Tojeiro-Bristol, or the Tojeiro's
production-car counterpart the AC Ace. All these British designs were virtually
straight copies of the car whose unofficial model name the latest Fiat revives
- the Tipo 166 Ferrari Barchetta by Superleggera Touring of Milan. It won at Le
Mans in 1949, and Ascari raced one the following year at Silverstone, where it
obviously struck a chord with our own sports-racing men.
The present Barchetta comes with a new twin-cam 1747cc engine which peaks at
130bhp. Fiat sees no chance of there being a big enough UK market demand to
justify converting it to right-hand drive, but LHD versions are available to
special order at #13,995.
Left-hand drive can be a real pest in this country, although there were enough
keen types interested in the Lancia Delta Integrale to justify a few sales
here. But the Barchetta looked terrific on the motor show stand. What impact
would it have out on the open road?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
