<DOCNO>GH951201-000009</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000009</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tyson fight moved</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110154</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FORMER world heavyweight champion Mike Tyson will fight Buster Mathis Jr on
December 16 - despite a decision by the New Jersey Casino Control Commission to
bar the fight from taking place in Atlantic City.
The NJCCC ruled that staging the fight in New Jersey would violate a ban on
casinos doing business with Tyson's promoter, Don King. But, hours later, King
announced that the fight was being moved along the east coast to Philadelphia.
King's casino-service licence was suspended by the state last year after he had
been charged with fraud. Earlier this month, a mis-trial was declared in King's
case, but the charges are still pending.
Tyson is due to fight Britain's WBC champion, Frank Bruno, in March.
q MICKEY Duff believes Henry Wharton's clash with Frenchman Frederic Seillier
on January 13 will be ``the most meaningful European title fight in years - if
not ever.''
Yorkshireman Wharton defends his European super-middleweight crown against the
former holder in Halifax, in a bout which Duff is billing as a final eliminator
for a crack at WBC champion Nigel Benn.
Duff has secured the rights to stage Wharton's second defence with a purse-bid
of more than #150,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000010</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000010</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Aiming for Gunners</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>41</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110155</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PETER Beardsley hopes to help Newcastle take a giant step towards their first
Wembley final in 20 years by beating Arsenal in a quarter-final of the
Coca-Cola Cup at Highbury early in the new year.
Reading face a daunting trip to Leeds, while there is a Midlands derby with
Wolves at Aston Villa, while the fourth tie seeks replay untanglement, with
Middlesbrough or Birmingham at Norwich or Bolton.
However, the Highbury clash is the one that will set the pulse racing, pitting
two in-form strike forces against each other - 21-goal Ian Wright and Dennis
Bergkamp versus 24-goal Les Ferdinand and Beardsley.
While #6m Ferdinand has contributed 18 to the Geordie haul, it is Beardsley
that double-winners Arsenal will fear most. He scored twice as Newcastle won
3-2 at Highbury last season, and then hit the St James' Park winner in March.
Reading, 50-1 outsiders, will not travel to Elland Road without hope. It is
more than 22 years since the Yorkshire side made a successful run on Wembley
and they were eliminated from the competition last season at Mansfield and held
at home by Notts County this term.
Wolves, too, are beginning to dream of Wembley, despite their lack of manager
and the woeful start to the season which cost Graham Taylor his job.
They defeated Coventry to set up another intriguing Midlands tie at Villa Park,
with history favouring Villa, the most consistent side in a competition they
have won four times.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
