<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Minister calls on Brussels for more radical shake-up of CAP</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KATHERINE BUTLER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975110157</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN will be pushing its EU partners to make its next shake-up of the CAP
even more radical than outlined, the Minister for Agriculture Douglas Hogg said
yesterday, writes KATHERINE BUTLER.
In Brussels, where farm ministers got their first opportunity to mull over the
long-awaited strategy paper on the future of agriculture policy Mr Hogg
welcomed the move to scale down supports in advance of EU enlargement to
Eastern Europe.
The approach outlined by the European Commission in the document fell short of
radical reform, Mr Hogg said. He added: ``This is a useful strategy, but we
wish to go much further.'' He said Brussels should begin to tackle the next
wave of reforms as a matter of urgency. According to the strategy paper devised
by EU Agriculture Commissioner Franz Fischler, extending the CAP to ten former
Communist states will add #12bn a year on to the EU's farm bill. However, it
says reform is essential irrespective of enlargement because of internal
budgetary pressures and Gatt World Trade Commitments.
Mr Fischler is proposing a deepening of the 1992 MacSharry reforms, which imply
a new round of price and quota cuts. But he also wants to link direct payments
more closely to environment friendly farming and to schemes which make farmers
``the stewards of the countryside.''
The shake-up would involve a radical simplification of the CAP. Mr Fischler
said the policy had become so complex that farmers could not understand it, let
alone the general public.
But he is also suggesting that Brussels devolve responsibility for much of the
day-to-day running of the CAP to national governments, including some of the
handling of direct income supplements. That is seen as a dangerous precedent
which could eventually undermine the foundations of the 30-year-old common
policy.
Irish minister Ivan Yates said to allow governments to boost their farmers
incomes out of national exchequers would in effect mean the beginning of the
end of the CAP. He vowed that Ireland would block the proposal and said he
could rely on France and Germany to block any radical change.
The Fischler paper envisages that eastern European countries will join the bloc
around the turn of the century and gain full admittance to the CAP by the year
2010.
</TEXT>
