<DOCNO>GH951201-000013</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000013</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Selection process is really extraordinary</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HUGH DAN MacLENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110158</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE sport's ability to handle its affairs has been called into question
following the decision to hold an extraordinary meeting of shinty's ruling body
to discuss the handling of the appointment of the new administrator.
The short-leet for the position - shinty's first full-time professional
administrator - will be drawn up today but the meeting to discuss the handling
of the interview selection process is threatening to overshadow what should be
seen as a major step forward for the game.
Monday night's meeting, to be held in Fort William and chaired by the
association's past-president Ken Thomson, has been called following the
decision by current president, Duncan Cameron of Glasgow, to apply for the new
job. Shinty's part-time secretary/treasurer, Alister MacIntyre, of Fort
William, also has confirmed he will be a candidate.
It has transpired that once Cameron informed members of the executive council
that he was to apply for the post, another member of the executive, Douglas
MacKintosh of Newtonmore, vice-chief, contacted executive members to discuss
the handling of the job applications.
The up-shot was a claim that 14 of the 16 members of the executive expressed
``concern'' about the way the job specification had been drawn up, and
presented to a recent meeting of the executive.
Monday night's meeting will therefore centre on Cameron's alleged failure to
declare an interest in the new job, and the handling of the preparations for
the new post. The move is being interpreted in some quarters as an attempt to
influence the outcome of the application process.
Cameron as president, was to have been a member of the six-strong selection
panel, but withdrew on announcing his interest in the post. He is understood to
be convinced of the propriety of his actions and ready to respond to any
allegations to the contrary at Monday night's meeting. He is virtually certain
by then to be on the short-leet for the post.
The original plan announced by the association involved a further meeting to
conduct interviews, and it had been hoped that the new official would be in
place around the New Year. Whether that will now be the sequence of events will
depend on the outcome of Monday's meeting.
The feeling among members of the executive contacted by The Herald this week is
that, while any suggestions of officials being ``underhand'' in their dealings
with the job application may be well off the mark, there is a need to clarify
the handling of the affair.
How the executive hope to do that when the job applications have already been
processed to the short-leet stage is not clear. Nor is it apparent what effect,
if any, the unseemly situation will have on the many aspiring candidates who
now await news of who is to be interviewed and when.
</TEXT>
