<DOCNO>GH951201-000014</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000014</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>WORLD BANK STUDY Australia and Canada emerge as richest countries</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110159</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AUSTRALIA and Canada emerge as the world's richest countries, with wealth
estimated at $835,000 and $704,000 per capita respectively, according to a new
study by the World Bank which includes natural resources, capital assets and
human capital.
These countries emerge on top because of their natural wealth and relatively
low populations. The UK at 22nd with $324,000 per head comes further down the
list than is usual in such comparisons of wealth, just below Finland, which
benefits from its vast forests, and also below Italy. The poorest country,
Ethiopia, is worth just $1400 per capita, so that on this basis Australia is
almost 600 times richer.
The World Bank warns that figures for individual countries can only be rough
estimates but that they give a good idea of regional patterns. The study
attempts to get beyond the usual bald gross domestic product which is the usual
way of assessing relative wealth.
It tries to assess each country's natural capital such as forests and soil
quality, adjusted for degradation caused by human activity; man-made capital,
which gives a country its productive capacity through its manufactured assets
and infrastructure, and human capital, meaning investment in education, health
etc.
This approach produces some surprising findings. Surinam for example has GDP
per head of under $3000 but take account of the other forms of capital and its
wealth jumps to no less than $389,000, which is really a measure of its
potential if its natural wealth was harnessed.
The main finding is the vital role of human capital. This exceeds both natural
and man-made capital combined in importance in the vast majority of cases. Yet
conventional economics take no account of it. Man-made assets represent a fifth
at most of the wealth of most countries studied, yet it is on this that ``the
bulk of current economic policy focuses,'' as the study's author Ismail
Serageldin points out.
It boils down to the simple fact that the most important single parameter for
economic development in the long-term is education. Another important factor is
saving. For most countries these are the first building blocks for prosperity
and development will happen if they are in place. Establishing a basic
infrastructure should not be the first priority, though it will quickly follow.
The East Asian countries have basically followed such an approach and of course
have not looked back. The exact benefits of investment in human capital are
difficult to measure in monetary terms, whereas the advantage of high savings
rates are more obvious in terms of high capital formation. People in the
fast-expanding East Asian economies save a lot partly because they don't have a
western-style social security safety net which forces government spending to be
much higher as a proportion of GDP than in East Asia.
It may seem obvious that education and health are prerequisites for continuing
economic development, though this could be questioned. For example the early
stages of the industrial revolution were not marked by a surge in popular
education and better health, though conditions were improving for the budding
entrepreneurial class.
Human capital cannot develop if there is insufficient social capital, meaning a
stable political and cultural framework. How a society is organised and the
legitimacy of its institutions are clearly important but it is difficult to see
how this can be measured.
There is evidence that societies with a rich matrix of non-governmental
associations between people, meaning anything from choral societies to
parent-teacher associations, rather than those with autocratic vertical
institutions, have better government.
However the latter have certainly not held back the East Asian countries so
there may be cultural bias in this conclusion which was arrived at after
research in Italy. More work is being done on this and on how the
morale-sapping effects of unemployment and underemployment affects well being
and economic success.
It is becoming clearer what makes economies take off, though translating this
knowledge into politically acceptable policies is another matter. Making growth
sustainable in the long-term and compatible with low inflation and without
degradation of the environment is still a question which economists will ponder
for years to come.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
