<DOCNO>GH951201-000015</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000015</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bank chairman warns there is a risk that the softness in UK economic activity will continue Royal cashes in with record results</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110160</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Royal Bank of Scotland has set any potential bidders pondering after
producing record full year results, with pre-tax profits rising 13% to #602m.
However, the more meaningful figure is the 20% rise before the inclusion in the
preceding year of the #52m gain on the bank's stake in the 3i venture capital
group.
There were improvements in all the major activities which is unusual for bank
these days.
The most important factors were the #70m reduction in the bad debt provisions
to #112m and the #3000m increase in UK lending as the headline figures.
But chairman Lord Younger warned that, while there are good reasons to expect
that economic activity in the UK will show some rebound in the coming year,
there is a sigificant risk that the present softness will continue.
He said that despite the speculation, there had been no takeover approaches and
there were no suspicious nominee shareholdings.
The staff will benefit to the extent of a #30m profit-sharing bonus which will
be equivalent to 8.8% on basic salary and worth on average about #1200.
There was a brief flurry of excitment and amazement when a newswire said that
the Royal was in merger talks with the Bank of Ireland. But it soon emerged
that its highly successful Citizens banking group in New England, with assets
of over $10bn, was in preliminary talks to merge with the $4000m asset-based
Bank of Ireland First Holdings, which owns the First New Hampshire Bank.
Talks are at an early stage, but the consideration would seem unlikely to
exceed $400m (#260m).
Citizens itself increased pre-tax profits by 57% to #107m and since its
acquisition for $250m in 1988, has never lost money unlike all other banks in
New England. It is increasingly becoming ever more core to the Royal and, given
the strength of its capital ratios, it may be somewhat flummoxed as to what to
do with any money it did receive from a sale.
The high profile Direct Line insurance division raised profit by #2m to #112m
in a highly competitive trading sector, where premiums have been hit by 10%
over the year.
Founder Peter Wood said that there are now 2.2 million motor-policty holders
with Direct Line, which is the only major insurer making money out of
underwriting. That is partly through cost control, with the expense of each
Direct Line policy having fallen from #61 to #46, compared with an industry
average of around #100.
Household business had been less competitive, with there being 725,000 policy
holders as at the end of September. Mr Wood said he is now determined to attack
the building societies' share of the market. He expects motor rates to increase
sharply, probably in a year's time once weaker competitors are squeezed out of
the market.
The UK branch banking side continued to benefit from the Project Columbus
reorganisation and employee refocussing programme, with the taking of back
office tasks out of the branches. That has also included much better credit
control to the extent that chief executive George Mathewson does not, at
present, expect any cyclical rise in defaults.
He added that, as valuations for property and other assets have remained low,
there has not been any inflated lending. The underlying bad-debt position may,
in fact, be better than it looks as centralised control has removed many of the
``hope'' non-provisioning by individual managers who previously had not
reserved adequately against some loans.
The south of England is still lagging in recovery, with the North East of
England and Scotland the most bouyant as far as the Royal in concerned.
The one third stake in the Newton Investment Group brought in #2m for nine
months and seems set to become a steady earner as a highly successful fund
management associate.
Treasury operations rose a quarter to #104m, although its finding meant some
recourse to the wholesale money markets and reduced interest spreads.
The dividend total has been raised 18% to 16.2p, with an 11.6p final. To
prevent speculation as to future interim payments, it has been decided that
they will be one third of the total for the preceding year, so that the next
one will be 5.4p.
Royal's shares rose 10p to 557p, where they yield 3.6%.
</TEXT>
