<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000016</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000016</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hanson slims  its operations</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110161</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HANSON's days as a sprawling conglomerate appear to be over. The group intends
to concentrate on four strategic sectors and as such expects to realise #2000m
from disposals within the next 12 months.
Around #450m of this will come from the sale of its stake in the National Grid
and the remainder from the disposal of non-core businesses. However it refused
to comment on speculation that its Cavenham forest products business might be
sold.
The disposal programme will go some way to reducing Hanson's hefty debt pile
following its recent #2900m acquisition of Eastern Group, the regional
electricity company (REC). It contributed #7m to group profits. Gearing in the
wake of the Eastern acquisition stands at 130%.
Chief executive Derek Bonham is very enthusiastic about the acquisition which
was made at a price below those seen in subsequent bids, for what he said were
less attractive RECs.
There is thought to be scope for the Peabody coal business and Eastern to
collaborate on international power projects in the Far East and Australia. It
is not unusual for Hanson to have such high debts immediately after a bid.
Interest cover remains healthy at four times.
The tighter operational focus is aimed at maximising future cash flow which
will help to boost dividends. The company decided to hold its dividend at 12p
believing that the money saved is better spent investing in the business.
However, it remains committed to a progressive dividend policy. Mr Bonham added
that following the USI demerger many UK shareholders had in effect had a 9p
payout in addition to the 12p cash dividend. ``Shareholders have had a
tremendous deal,'' he said.
Capital expenditure in the year rose by 70% to #442m with much of the money
spent on projects to increase capacity and improve productivity. Spending on
strategic development projects has also been stepped up.
At an operational level its businesses performed well with a notably strong
performance from its Quantum chemicals business in the US, whose profits rose
nearly fourfold.
It benefited from strong price increases due to a shortage of ethylene.
However, other US businesses turned in record performances. There was a record
group operating profit from continuing operations of #1486m, an increase of 44%.
Within the UK businesses, Imperial Tobacco continued to increase its share of a
stabilising domestic market. Duty free and international sales did well. The
ARC aggregates business did well considering the problems with demand in the
construction industry. Production cut-backs in the industry and stable prices
and margins enabled Hanson Brick to increase its profits by 65% to #38m.
Whilst Quantum's profits are expected to slip from their exceptionally high
level they are expected to remain healthy. Actions throughout the businesses to
improve efficiency should keep group profits on an upward path.
The company will hold its bi-annual strategy presentation in mid-January and
will also give an update on progress within Eastern Group.
Hanson shares gained 3p to 1951/2p.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>We can work it out</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOAN GRADY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>98</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110162</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AT LEAST 175,000,000 days are lost to employers every year through
stress-related illnesses. This is more than a third of the 500m days lost
through sickness absence - while hangovers account for a further 8m to 14m
days. But if employers and staff know how to cope with problems, many such
absences can be avoided. The Employee Counselling Service (ECS) in Glasgow
provides counselling and training to that end.
``The employers we deal with have long recognised that there were problems they
couldn't ignore,'' says Pauline Bryan, director of ECS. ``Even though they
mainly happen in an employee's private life.
``They recognise that people don't always leave their personal problems at the
door, that they do sometimes bring them in to work.''
The service is a charitable body which has offered one-stop access to
professional help and counselling for nearly 20 years. It provides a
confidential, independent service away from the workplace, in an environment
where troubled employees can speak more freely about their problems.
Referrals come about either voluntarily, when the employer asks the employee to
attend, or as the result of disciplinary action where personal problems are a
contributory factor. Occasionally employees refer themselves.
``About 15% of referrals are self-referrals, the rest come through employers,''
says Bryan. ``Problems vary between men and women. The most common problem for
men is alcohol abuse, followed by stress.
``For women it's personal family problems, followed by alcohol, then stress.
Alcohol isn't always the main problem - it could be bereavement or some
traumatic event the person is using alcohol to cope with.''
Stress is a huge contributor to employee absence, and it is now an issue which
employers are being forced into taking seriously. A Northumberland County
Council worker successfully sued his employers after being forced to leave work
due to stress, setting a legal precedent for others.
``Employers are now realising how they suffer from employees' stress - and of
course they've been suffering all the while,'' says Bryan.
``There's nothing worse than an unplanned absence, and if someone has to get a
sick line for stress-related illnesses such as anxiety or depression the
employer could be losing them for months.
``It's important to have a strategy for recognising stress, offering internal
and using external support so people can talk freely about their problems
outside the work environment. We've developed a training strategy to encourage
personnel managers to recognise the symptoms.''
Public training, arranged and conducted at the service's headquarters in
Glasgow's Oswald Street, covers the factors that make people vulnerable to
stress, understanding the duty of care and Health and Safety Executive
guidelines.
Training is also provided in assessing levels of stress and developing a
strategy to deal with it. In-house training concentrates on improving the
skills of management in spotting stress and on finding appropriate staff to act
as volunteer counsellors on a range of subjects.
``If the company has a harassment policy we train the volunteer counsellors in
how to cope with harassment,'' says Bryan.
``Often people at all levels have received some training in counselling skills
so they recognise how far they can help and when to move on. We help equip
people in companies to deal with other people's problems.''
This year has seen a significant rise in the number of referrals being dealt
with by the service. While this shows that more employers are adopting an
understanding approach, it can mean problems for counsellors.
``We've increased our counselling hours, but it's very demanding for our
counsellors.'' says Bryan. ``We have to build in to each day a chance to deal
with the feelings counsellors are experiencing.
``All counsellors who work as a team share information - they don't use names
or details but they learn from each other - it's part of their development and
offers great help and advice.''
As a charity, ECS provides counselling free to employers and employees. There
is a charge for training, however, to supplement the funding donated by
Strathclyde Regional Council, CBI Scotland and STUC, among others.
ECS might be non-profit-making, but lack of money might mean employers have to
contribute more. ``It is becoming harder to depend on donations and training to
supplement our grants,'' says Bryan.
``We hope always to be able to supply a subsidised service, and we've tried to
maintain an open-door, drop-in-any-time service but employers are probably
going to have to start meeting more of the costs.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Taking change in their stride</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HAZEL DUDGEON, CHIEF EXECUTIVE HAMILTON RACECOURSE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>Arena</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975110163</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HAVE you noticed the correlation between the evolution of a particular sport
and the culture in which it exists? The more you appreciate the subtle changes
in your sport, the more apparent this theory becomes.
Take horseracing, for example, the long existence and scale of this sport and
industry is a perfect case in point. You'll have to think about it because a
history lesson, this is not.
For now, consider the changes within the 1990s. The behaviour patterns of the
sport's most ardent followers are on the move again; sociologists need not be
surprised by the news. Before I elaborate, as a racecourse manager the news is
good. If you are an off-course betting shop manager, however, don't completely
give up on the lottery - you may just need Mystic Meg to do you a big favour.
In my opinion, the betting-shop punter is becoming an ageing market. The
habitual visitor who frequented these havens when they first became legalised
is either approaching 60, more than 60, or in the land of constant winners. The
quick success experienced by off-course betting shops 30 years ago    surely
resulted in the benefactors taking the levels of      business for granted.
Meanwhile, social habits have evolved, not to mention the growing competition
for the punter's pound. Our society   now demands value for its leisure spend -
competition insists upon it.
Even with their smarter interiors, quality pictures, and convenient locations,
the betting shop experience cannot provide today's sports fans with that vital
sense of involvement, suspense, and thrill that is sought from the leisure
investment. Here lies the exciting opportunity for racecourse    managers.
Despite the issues of transport to the racecourse, admission prices, catering
choice. If racecourses can satisfy in these respects, the racing fan will still
perceive a trip to the races as a far superior experience and better value for
money. The collective benefits of attending the meetings instead of catching
the 3.30 at Kelso between the 3.28 at Hackney and the 3.42 at Romford, are soon
appreciated by those looking for quality leisure time.
A competitive leisure industry has allowed each of us to become a connoisseur
of our chosen hobby. Sedentary jobs encourage us to be more active in our
leisure pursuits; increasing urbanisation forces us to seek out fresh air,
green grass, and large spaces; either hard work and stress, or the monotony of
unemployment, make us crave for excitement, glamour, and natural beauty. Live
horseracing, fellow Millennium Crusaders provides all of these things.
This behaviour evolution is becoming more widely recognised. With innovations
such as Sunday racing and various promotional activity by racecourse
executives, the customer-mix out on the racecourse is increasingly family-based
and broad-ranging. The solitary flat-capped, wax coated, Morris Minor driver
has become the exception amongst a recent influx of women and children,
corporate executives, and professional colleagues surrounding the paddock
studying the form.
Hamilton Park, located on Glasgow's doorstep, illustrates this mini-evolution
and it is exciting to be part of the metamorphosis. Our mid week evening
meetings are competing strongly for the city pub and wine bar trade-lads, you
may as well eye up a leggy filly whilst you sup your pint (or in our case
girls, check out the best dressed studs) spending an evening with your friends,
instead of succumbing to yet another smoke-filled evening in the west end.
The lottery is also doing its bit for horseracing's social status, if
indirectly. Short-term, the bookmakers are bemoaning the fall-off in betting
turnover. The concept of gambling, however, has experienced a quantum leap in
the credibility stakes. Horseracing is being supported by banks, accountants,
lawyers, and the like to an unprecedented extent. Nobody questions the morality
of a flutter any more, in fact in sheer probability terms let alone
entertainment, it makes infinitely a more sense to stake #1 on a runner in an
eight-horse race than buy a scratch card.
The appeal of a #1 bet on a five-to-one-shot compared to the scratch card for
entertainment value, there is no contest.
So now that gambling is fully accepted by modern society, horseracing stands to
benefit, particularly the tracks.
Racecourses even have a safety net in place should the current level of
betting-shop closures continue. This is in the form of a recently launched
television Racing Channel. Now punters can bet from home using a satellite
channel dedicated solely to horseracing - the first single sport channel of its
kind.
Racecourses earn a substantial income from the provision of pictures of live
horseracing in to betting shops. If this income was to fall significantly it is
anticipated that the Racing Channel will help mop up the lost business.
Furthermore, the Racing Channel has wide horizons, stretching as far as the
gambling-mad Asian continents.
Who knows the limits of this new source of potential revenue with today's
communication technology.
Look out for form guides appearing on the Internet. Information and
communication technology is advancing at such a pace surely the 33-1 winner is
quickly becoming a thing of the past, but then again racing's greatest charm is
to expect the unexpected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000019</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000019</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Peacock lands indoor title</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GORDON DUNWOODIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>41</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975110164</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MIDLOTHIAN'S David Peacock landed the CIS Insurance Scottish Indoor Singles
Championship at Coatbridge last night when he edged out club-mate and defending
champion Paul Conlan 7-4, 6-7, 2-7, 7-3, 7-5 in a 39-end, three-and-a-quarter
hour final.
Peacock, who arrived in Scotland just last week from Australia after having
married his new wife Kim, made a great start in the first final between players
from the same club.
A new ruling introduced by the SIBA that allowed the reigning champion to
defend the title, enabled the two men from the east to set up a final clash,
and Peacock came from having been 1-3 down in the opener to win it 7-4.
The second set turned into a ding-dong battle, and with seven ends played the
scores were tied at 6-6, but it was defending champion Conlan who got the vital
single to tie things up at one set apiece.
``I was disappointed to lose that end. Had I managed to get the shot and gone
2-0 up, I knew it would have been a long way back for Paul - and it was
particularly disappointing when he went on to take the next set,'' said Peacock.
Conlan dominated the third set, restricting his club-mate to just two singles
as he ran out a 7-2 winner.
However, Peacock got a good start in the next with a single and a 3 that took
him 4-0 ahead. The title holder replied with two singles but Peacock went on to
take the set 7-3 in seven ends.
Conlan picked up an opening-end 3 in the deciding set before Peacock replied
with a double to be just one down at 2-3. With five ends completed, Conlan was
still in front at 5-3, but Peacock counted a sixth-end single to put the match
back in the melting pot.
On the next end Peacock picked up a double but was left regretting a missed
opportunity. He failed with an open draw with his last bowl of the end to add a
potential match-winning third shot, but was only delaying the celebrations.
A single on the next enabled him take the set 7-5 and win the title.
``I knew it would be tight and that's the way it turned out,'' said Peacock.
``There was nothing between us and it was just my turn on the day. We know each
other's game so well that it was always going to be a dour battle.''
In the earlier semi-finals, both players had come from behind after having
dropped the opening sets in their best-of-three encounters.
Peacock lost the opener to Cumbernauld's David Miller 1-7, took the second 7-6,
and saved game in the decider before going on to complete a 7-5 win.
``I thought it was all running away from me during the early stages but I stuck
in well in the second and when I won it it gave me a boost for the last,'' said
Peacock.
Conlan also lost his opening set against East Lothian's Angus Blair.
He forged into a 5-2 lead after four ends, but Conlan, who had played on the
same Coatbridge carpet earlier in the week in the CIS Masters, counted three
shots on the fifth end to tie the scores at 5-5. However, Blair got the
set-winning double on the next end.
Conlan then took an early advantage in the second set, opening with a maximum 4
and then went on to complete a 7-4 win.
n DAVID Peacock defeated Paul Conlan 7-4, 6-7, 2-7, 7-3, 7-5 in the final to
take the indoor singles title.
</TEXT>
