<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Menzieshill on top</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOSEPH DILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110165</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SUCCESS breeds success it seems, as far as the Menzieshill club is concerned.
They grabbed pole position after the opening hostilities in the indoor league
last week, and yesterday, they sealed a new sponsorship deal.
They will now have the financial support of the Dundee-based training and
development company Insights, indoors and out.
Andy Lothian, Insights' managing director, confirmed that their interest in the
club was ``an attempt to put something back into the sport.''
Lothian, a former Scotland Under-21 internationalist, continued: ``I gained a
tremendous amount from hockey and I now want to give the youth of Menzieshill
the same opportunity.''
Menzieshill return to league duty at the Bell's Sports Centre, Perth, on Sunday
and, like their nearest challengers MIM, they face two meaningless contests as
they are already assured of their places in the second phase. The pressure,
however, will be on CIBA Kelburne, Insights Inverleith, Torbrex Wanderers, and
Touche Ross Gordonians as they attempt to avoid the two places still to be
decided in the relegation play-offs.
Kelburne's position now looks to be beyond recall. They are still without a
point and their experiment to field such a young side has backfired on them.
JOSEPH DILLON
</TEXT>
