<HEADLINE>BBC finally don't have football say</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>41</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975110167</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TV FOOTBALL
THE decline of prestige sport in public service broadcasting accelerated
yesterday when the BBC surrendered live coverage of the FA Cup final to
commercial rivals ITV.
That is the headline detail in a three-way #130m deal, dominated by satellite
broadcasters Sky, for the rights to the Football Association's major properties
for four years from 1997 onwards. The BBC also loses highlights of England's
international matches, but will keep its Road to Wembley FA Cup highlights in
return for a #15m contribution to the package.
Quite simply, the BBC could not find enough licence payers' money to compete
harder for the game that has been the jewel in its sporting crown since 1937.
``Obviously it will be a wrench to give up live coverage of the FA Cup Final
after so many years, but it is becoming clear that the huge escalation in the
rights fees for live domestic football has put some events beyond the reach of
the BBC's licence fee,'' the Corporation admitted.
Yesterday's developments are another blow for terrestrial television. ITV were
only better placed to bid for the final because on Monday they lost out in a
five-year, #125m Football League deal to Sky, who gained the best of
yesterday's package. They will broadcast live games from every round, plus live
replays, and will continue to show all of England's home internationals live.
ITV will show a live FA Cup match on Sunday afternoons from rounds three to
six, as well as one live semi-final and the final. They will also show
highlights of midweek replays from round three onwards.
</TEXT>
