<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cash boost for Northampton</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110169</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KEITH Barwell has launched a #1m bid to buy Northampton - with the promise of
more money to come. The Courage League Division 2 leaders' 2500 members will be
asked at an extraordinary general meeting on Sunday week to support the move,
writes Derek Douglas.
Former Scotland coach Ian McGeechan is now director of rugby at Northampton and
Scottish internationalists Gregor Townsend and Mike Dods were recruited during
the close season. Barwell already has the support of McGeechan and club captain
Tim Rodber.
``I have given the club certain assurances that they will have the right to buy
back the controlling interest of the club,'' said Barwell. ``In the future I
see additional sums of money being required. They will be available. I believe
this is the final brick in the wall which makes us very, very powerful.''
Northampton are the latest club to be offered financial help in the game's new
professional era. First division Saracens have been boosted by a #2.5m
injection from a local businessman, and Sir John Hall has pumped millions into
second division Newcastle.
Barwell, 51, who made his fortune out of free newspapers, first approached the
club with his offer six months ago.
Northampton now want to change from being a members' club to a private limited
company, Northampton Rugby Football Club Ltd.
There would be 1.4m shares issued. Barwell would invest #1m and be the majority
shareholder and chairman of the company. A further #400,000 - the value of the
club's assets - would be put into a trust on behalf of the members, who would
have a three-strong representation on the board.
Saints president Roger Harwood said: ``The club wants to remain in the top
flight of rugby union and to do that we have to go down the road to
professionalism.''
</TEXT>
