<DOCNO>GH951201-000025</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000025</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Constable `wore bra and pants'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110170</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MALE police constable allegedly wearing only a bra and pants smiled at young
girls from his door, a court was told yesterday.
Mr Brian Murphy is also said to have waved at children while he was completely
naked, the court heard.
When a concerned mother went to a police station and told Mr Murphy where her
children claimed to have seen a flasher, she said he replied: ``It can't be,
that's where I live.''
Mr Murphy, 24, of East Moulin Road, Pitlochry, was in the dock yesterday
accused of exposing himself at his home in an indecent manner in the presence
of four young girls.
He is also charged with alarming the same girls plus another young girl and a
boy while wearing bra and pants.
A 10-year-old girl - who cannot be named for legal reasons - told Perth Sheriff
Court that as she walked past the house ``the door opened and there was a
person standing there in bra and pants.''
She told the court that she noticed stubble on the face and added: ``I called
it an `it' because it had a man head and lady clothes.'' She described two
similar incidents.
The girl, who was with her older sister or friends at the times of the alleged
incidents, identified Mr Murphy in court as the person at the doorway,
explaining, ``I recognise him from the house.''
The mother of another ten-year-old girl said that another parent had been told
about the alleged incidents and her child and her seven-year-old sister had
told her the address on East Moulin Road.
She drove the girls to identify the house and said they both pointed and said
``that's the one'' when they passed it.
The mother then went to report their claims at the police station where Mr
Murphy was behind the desk.
She said that Mr Murphy had later said: ``I live there with my wife'' when told
the address.
Mr Murphy denies the charges alleged to have happened between April 1 and May
18 this year.
The trial, before Sheriff John McInnes, continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000026</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000026</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trapped bridge worker rescued</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975110171</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SPECIAL rescue team was called into action yesterday to save a worker trapped
inside one of the towers that supports the Forth road bridge.
The team from Fife used ropes to manoeuvre themselves from road level down a
150ft shaft in the tower to get to the 56-year-old man, injured after an object
hit him on the shoulder and neck.
The team secured a safety harness round him and, using ropes, guided him the
remaining 50ft to the bottom of the tower. The man, as yet unnamed, was
transferred to a waiting boat and then to hospital, where he was treated for
minor injuries.
q Meanwhile, Labour MP Brian Donohue hit out at Government delays in bringing
out a report on the structural state of the Forth Rail Bridge.
Mr Donohue, the only Scottish member of the Commons Transport Select Committee,
said the timetable for bringing out the report was slipping.
Mr Donohue, MP for Cunninghame South, said: ``We have been waiting for the
Health and Safety Executive report since last March, and now a further delay
has occurred in its publication.
``I am told that the main reason why this report has been delayed is because
Railtrack has not yet carried out the structural investigations as requested by
the HSE to the required standard.
``This further delay must raise more questions about the reluctance of
Railtrack to have their maintenance policy for the Forth Rail Bridge
scrutinised independently.
``This report has already been delayed long enough. It should be published as
soon as possible.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000027</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000027</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Higgins books revenge chance</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975110173</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOMORROW'S second semi-final in the Royal Liver UK Assurance Championship in
Preston will be an all-Scottish affair between defending champion Stephen
Hendry and second favourite John Higgins.
Higgins last night ensured the clash every snooker fan wants to see with a
hard-fought 9-6 win over Mark Williams.
After having trailed 3-0 in Wednesday's first session and struggled for much of
the contest, partly due to a damaged tip, the Sct found his touch to win the
last three frames with breaks of 60, 94, and 79.
Higgins is out for revenge after losing to Hendry in last month's Skoda Grand
Prix final, a meeting that proved an anti-climax after the hype surrounding
their first meeting as professionals.
``I think we showed each other too much respect and I am sure this will be a
cracking match,'' said Higgins, who was relieved that Williams missed a simple
last pink in the tenth frame which could have put the Scot two frames behind.
He added: ``I'm sure Mark's turn will come - he is one of the best potters in
the game.''
Earlier in the day, Hendry had booked his place in the last four when, leading
6-2 from their first session, he went on to complete a 9-3 victory over
Dubliner Ken Doherty.
The world champion did not have a century break in the match and said: ``I have
set myself such high standards that everyone expects me to knock in centuries
all the time.''
The semi-final line-up was completed when left-hander Andy Hicks shocked former
champion Ronnie O'Sullivan by overturning a first-session deficit of 5-3 to win
9-7.
The world No.17 from Devon, who also reached the last four at this year's world
championship, had been written off at the halfway point by the bookmakers - who
made O'Sullivan, winner of the title in 1993, 1-14 to book a meeting with Peter
Ebdon today.
Hicks was on offer at 13-2 - but was still not tempted into a wager. ``I never
bet,'' he said after taking his second major scalp in successive rounds, having
previously seen off James Wattana 9-8 with a brilliant 67 clearance.
Hicks pulled back to 6-6 helped by a run of 64 in the twelfth frame and never
went behind again, eventually finishing off the match with a magnificent black
to take the sixteenth frame 78-64.
O'Sullivan said about that superb pot from Hicks: ``I did not think Andy would
have a go, but it was a great shot. Andy is good under pressure and pots the
important balls you need to win matches.
``Of course I am disappointed, but you cannot cry or sulk. Snooker's only a
game and there are a lot more unfortunate people out there than me.
``Just look at Christopher Reeve - he's really brave and manages to smile, so
I'll not start complaining.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000028</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000028</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sharing the costs</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>41</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110174</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MANCHESTER United supporters have bought their way into today's shareholders'
meeting to demand price cuts at Old Trafford. Members of the club's independent
supporters association have invested on the stock market as a way of gaining
access to the club's annual meeting so they can ask for a drop in admission
prices in the wake of record #20m profits.
``Supporters have been buying shares so that we can confront the board with
questions direct from the terraces,'' says association secretary Andy Walsh.
``The club has refused to meet representatives of our organisation to talk on
matters we have raised with them. By buying shares we hope we can get them to
listen to the fears that fans have for the welfare of the club.''
Chris Robinson, the independent supporters' chairman, says he is worried that
young fans are being driven away from the club by high ticket prices. ``United
has developed a youth policy on the field which is the envy of all others. A
similar policy must be adopted off the field if the club is to attract and
retain supporters.''
The supporters' pleas may not fall on deaf ears. United chairman Martin Edwards
says the club will review admission costs in the New Year. ``We have not fixed
prices for next season and I am sure this is something shareholders are going
to be asking about.
``What I can say is that we are aware that over the last few years prices have
gone up and that is mainly due to developing the ground. When we set prices for
next season we will take that into consideration.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000029</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000029</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Experience still counts</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110175</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TRACEY Craik's decision to invest in an experienced caddie continued to pay off
for the Scot when she extended her lead with a third round of 70 in the
American Express Tour qualifying school tournament at La Manga Club in Spain
yesterday.
It left the former Scottish girl champion at three under par on 213 to take a
four-stroke lead over Tracy Loveys from Dorset into today's final round.
Anne-Marie Knight from Australia lies third on 218, one stroke clear of
American Debbie Doniger.
It was also a good day for Scotland's Myra McKinlay after a disappointing
second round of 80. A 73 yesterday left her sharing eleventh place on 224, and
looking good to earn an exempt place on the 1996 Tour.
Craik usually carries her own clubs, but this week, she enrolled the help of
Julie Forbes' brother, Steve, a one-handicap member of Aboyne. ``I tend to rush
my shots when I am on my own, but Steve has slowed me down,'' she said.
Craik's 70 hardly flattered her impressive striking. A No.5-wood to 15ft
yielded an early birdie at the fourth on her way to the turn in 35, then she
struck a No.3-iron to 15ft for another birdie at the tenth.
Loveys, a teaching professional from Broadstone, worked hard to keep Craik in
her sights. She dropped shots at the first two holes, birdied the third, then
executed a fine recovery from a greenside bunker to within a yard of the hole
for a birdie at the long eighteenth. Leading third round scores (GB &amp; I unless
stated):
213 - T Craik 71, 72, 70.
217 - T Loveys 72, 73, 72.
218 - A-M Knight (Aus) 75, 69, 74.
219 - D Doniger (US) 72, 77, 70.
220 - S Melin (Swe) 75, 74, 71.
</TEXT>
