<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000031</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000031</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Last dregs of the liquid lunch?</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCIS SHENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>98</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110177</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RESEARCH shows that the ``liquid lunch'' is disappearing from the working day -
though alcohol continues to be misused by some employees in a worrying way.
One survey, which excluded teetotallers from its figures, nevertheless showed
that 60% of senior British managers never drank alcohol at lunchtime and 24%
did so less than once a week.  When the whole workforce was questioned, 71%
said they never drank alcohol at lunchtime and 12% did so less than once a
week; 32% had never drunk during the working day; and 41% said they drank less
than they used to.
The reason for not drinking varied but 96% agreed that they wanted to keep a
clear head throughout the working day. Those who did drink during the day
usually had no more than a pint and a half of beer or two glasses of wine, with
men tending to drink more than women.
Yet one major Scottish company found that 23% of its male workers regularly
drank between 21 and 50 units of alcohol a week, and 18% of women drank 14 to
35 units, putting them into the ``at risk'' category. A unit is a glass of
wine, half pint of ordinary-strength beer or a measure of spirits.
Eleven per cent of male workers drank more than 50 units a week and 2.5% of
women more than 35 units, putting them into the ``in danger'' category. For
women in the 17-30 age group, this percentage doubled to 5%.
</TEXT>
