<HEADLINE>Cork and Malcolm rescue a lost cause Dynamic duo make England's gamble pay</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975110178</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE dynamic Derbyshire duo of Dominic Cork and Devon Malcolm stopped South
Africa in their tracks yesterday.
But England captain Mike Atherton must have feared the worst during the first
day of the second Test at Wanderers in Johannesburg.
It was he and manager Ray Illingworth who had handed the hosts a route to
riches by deciding to bowl first on a pitch that performed precious few tricks.
But, by close of play, England's spirits were high again - thanks to Cork and
Malcolm.
Between them, they reduced South Africa to 278 for seven after part-time
spinner Graeme Hick had ended a stand of 137 by dismissing a third Derbyshire
player, Daryll Cullinan.
For something like five hours yesterday, England looked on course for the most
humiliating of hidings.
England gambled, and it worked in the end with big Dev knocking over
century-maker Gary Kirsten and Dave Richardson when he was thrown the second
new ball.
Take away Cork's magnificent figures of four for 74 from 27.5 overs, however,
and the visitors would have been in a right state.
Almost every time a boost was needed, the 24-year-old provided one in a manner
that impressed another man who used to provide cricketing miracles on a regular
basis. Ian Botham, now a media pundit, watched and nodded his approval.
Cork gave England a flying start by dismissing Andrew Hudson for a seventh over
duck, an away-swinger lobbing to Alec Stewart in the gully via bat and pad,
while bowler and most close catchers appealed for lbw.
Then, after Kirsten and Hansie Cronje had feasted on some wayward bowling to
add 71 runs in just 17 overs, back came Cork to achieve a breakthrough just
before lunch.
South African skipper Cronje collected six 4s off Darren Gough and Angus Fraser
on his way to 35. But he could only edge another cracking delivery from
England's man of the morning.
At 75 for two, the gamble to bowl first was just about intact. It appeared
hopelessly off target three hours later, however, as rock solid left-hander
Kirsten and Cullinan compiled a partnership of 137.
Kirsten did not give a chance in his maiden Test century. It needed an unlikely
bowling hero to engineer an escape route.
Hick persuaded Cullinan to push forward 14 runs after his reprieve and this
time Russell held a routine opportunity off the outside edge.
That, insisted Cork, was the opening England knew they could exploit. Jonty
Rhodes, whose Test place is already under threat, made just five before pushing
tamely at the Derbyshire all-rounder.
And when the second new ball was taken, Malcolm forgot all his troubles, put
thoughts of technique behind him, and simply concentrated on steaming in. It
worked like a charm.
Kirsten's near six-hour innings, containing sixteen 4s, ended on 110 with a
catch behind following a tired drive. And, three balls later, Richardson turned
away from a bouncer to give Russell his fourth catch - lobbed up off the bat
handle. But, fittingly, the day finished with a Cork celebration. Brian
McMillan was pinned in front of his stumps.
