<HEADLINE>Flocks threatened by `super' scab mites</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT  ROSS  Farming Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110180</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE prospect of entire flocks of sheep facing slaughter on welfare grounds will
become a reality as the mites which cause sheep scab become resistant to
available insecticides, according to Dr Gerald Coles, a senior research fellow
at Bristol University.
There are only three types of insecticide available - pyrethroids, invermectin
and organophosphates. Scab mites have been found to be resistant to
pyrethroids; a suspected case of resistance to invermectin has been recorded
and organophosphate resistance has been described abroad.
``When - not if - sheep scab develop resistance to all three groups in the UK
we will have to go over to slaughtering flocks on welfare grounds,'' says Dr
Coles, writing in The Sheep Farmer.
``If, as seems most likely, multiple resistance occurs in common grazings,
large stretches of countryside could lose their sheep flocks. But it does not
have to happen.''
Dr Coles, who admits to being concerned by the spread of sheep scab in the UK,
advocates an approach to sheep control in line with that of New South Wales,
Australia. There sheep health is improving under farmer-owned, farmer driven
health schemes.
``The technology is already available to eradicate a number of sheep diseases
in the UK, including scab lice and keds. A decision has to be made on what to
control. Obviously scab and lice will come at the top but worms and foot rot
should not be far behind.''
Dr Coles insists that local control schemes must be driven by local farmers -
not the Ministry of Agriculture. That way the farmers will be determined to
make it work. Farmers in a control area would have to provide a certificate of
the disease status of sheep being sold to another farmer.
``Get it wrong and you might be sued,'' he warns. ``You might be served with a
quarantine order only permitting you to sell on to an abattoir. If all else
fails, in New South Wales, a farmer who has refused to comply with control
measures could have the farm compulsorily de-stocked.''
One advantage is that ``clean'' areas become an attraction for for buyers who
are keen to obtain disease-free stock. Prices rise accordingly.
``If we go on as at present sheep health will continue to decline with diseases
spreading and drug resistant parasites taking over,'' says Dr Coles. ``It need
not happen. We could have improving sheep health and some diseases eradicated.''
He suggests that the UK government would supply technical and legislative
support where necessary if they were asked strongly enough.
Dr Coles is prepared to embark on a nationwide tour of meetings of sheep
farmers to promote this approach,providing local vets and Members of Parliament
are also involved.
``It will cost money - but it will cost even more not to start new disease
control and eradication schemes,'' he said.
</TEXT>
