<HEADLINE>More demand doesn't mean more funding</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOAN GRADY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>98</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110181</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
REFERRALS to the Employee Counselling Service have gone up by 50% this year,
but there has been no proportionate increase in donations from employers,
writes JOAN GRADY.
Last year employers were asked to consider matching their donations to the use
of the service. Despite this, the 1994 annual report shows only a 21% rise in
donations, and the prognosis for the future is not good.
``The demand for the counselling service has never been greater,'' says
treasurer Robert Stewart. ``The response to the employers' questionnaire
conducted in May indicates overwhelming satisfaction with the service, but we
are not receiving any more resources to ensure this high level of service can
continue.''
Strathclyde Regional Council is the service's biggest supporter, providing more
than half the funding necessary to keep it running.
Andrew Stewart of Strathclyde Regional Council has worked alongside ECS for
many years. He is in little doubt as to its usefulness.
``The main benefit of the service in that it's seen to be absolutely
confidential,'' he says. ``There is a clear division between employee and
workplace. Employees know they can get help there without it being referred
back to the boss.
``Initially people didn't believe it could help them, but that changed
dramatically with the help of some enlightened managers and shop stewards.
``Being able to demonstrate that it could and did help meant reaching people
earlier - before it was too late to save their jobs. You can't force people to
go, they have to want to.''
Stewart suspects that if finances do not improve and ECS is forced to charge
for its services, fewer employers will make use of them.
``Employers might turn away from it since they are getting free counselling
just now,'' she says. ``The service in Glasgow is exceptionally professional.
If it were lost it would affect a great many people.''
</TEXT>
