<HEADLINE>Festive displays at garden centre</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Darren Rodger</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>38</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975110182</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE traditional silver tinsel holds a special significance for Findlay Clark at
Boclair Road, Milngavie, this Christmas. For it's the 25th anniversary of the
highly regarded garden centre - and they are celebrating their silver jubilee
in style, with the biggest, brightest, and best festive spectacle so far.
And that's no mean feat.
Over the years the centre has established a singular reputation with families
and shoppers as an essential part of Christmas - and many must wonder how the
centre could possibly improve on last year's offering.
``There will be customers, for example, who haven't seen our revamp,'' said
company buyer Alan Docherty. ``The main improvements took place in May, but we
are continually adding new bits. There is now a brand-new pet shop - three
times the size of our previous area and with numerous tropical fish,
guinea-pigs, rabbits, budgies, cockatiels, and finches - and we are constantly
enhancing the quality of all our displays.
``The centre continues to evolve and now, in the run-up to Christmas, we have
reached the peak of excellence - an excellence reflected in the quality and
scope of our festive displays.
``Customers will be hard put to find such a varied display of quality Christmas
trees, accessories, and gifts - from glassware to outdoor clothing and plants -
anywhere else in Scotland.''
Naturally Santa plays a starring role in the proceedings and children will be
enthralled by this year's fairy-tale setting for the traditional grotto.
Visitors to Santa have to walk through an enchanted forest of artificial
Christmas trees and past an animated display of Santa and his reindeer to reach
Sleeping Beauty's castle.
After walking up the drawbridge, children enter a magical snow-covered garden
beneath scores of twinkling lights before coming to the castle courtyard full
of houses, a magic fountain, and fruit stall. Sleeping Beauty slumbers in a
four-poster bed and a fairy-tale ending is assured in the throne room, with
some kind words from Santa and, all-important, a present from his bottomless
sack.
To return to the subject of Christmas trees, Findlay Clark has a massive
selection of artificial trees, both decorated and plain, from nine-inch
table-toppers to 10ft specimens suitable for the biggest of houses.
There are, among others, Canadian pines, ridge and Arkansas firs in blue,
green, and with snow effect.
Under cover outside, the ``real'' trees range from the needle drop-resistant
variety to the common-or-garden Norway spruce and ball-rooted specimens which
people can use, in increasing size, year after year.
``The trees are all grouped in size categories - from 3ft to 15ft in stock and
larger sizes to order - and each tree is individually labelled, giving its type
and size.
``All the trees on display are unwrapped so customers can come, take their
time, and buy the tree of their choice, which we then wrap in netting.
``We are now open from 9am till 7.30pm, seven days a week, so people can even
come after work when they don't have to worry about the rat race.''
Back in the warmth of the centre, you will be spoilt for choice when it comes
to decorating your tree.
There's a dazzling display of Christmas lights, both indoor and out. As well as
a basic set (#6.99 for 40) there are candle, winter crystal, and lantern-style
lights, and a string of illuminated Christmas houses is ideal for arranging
round doorways.
Then there are the increasingly sophisticated chaser lights with multi-mode
controllers which produce a variety of effects, the most expensive being a
kaleidoscope set at #46.
Baubles come in every colour under the winter sun - champagne pink and gold,
mauve, purple and blue - either plain or patterned so people are able to
decorate their tree to compliment existing decor.
The main sales floor is dotted with themed Christmas trees, each reflecting a
different mood - from a white tree draped in pearl-like strings of beads; a
kaleidoscope tree with gifts reminiscent of an Eastern bazaar; a rustic tree
laiden with berries and autumn fruits; and a mystical tree with signs of the
zodiac, moons and stars.
There are even trees to celebrate any family's new arrival, coloured, as you
might expect, in blue or pink. They can be found in the Kiddies' Corner which
is themed around a nursery, complete with a seasonal wallpaper border, a double
bed full of huge rabbits and teddies, and a wooden train made from half-barrels
filled with smaller soft toys.
If you're looking for a decoration that's a little bit different then Findlay
Clark has the answer: a Christmas-tree-like spiral which you decorate and hang
from the ceiling. Underneath is a wicker base which you can festoon in garlands
of tinsel.
The centre has everything you need for floral arranging, from ribbon to
polyester packs of holly and large golden-leaved apples - and therein lies the
secret of Findlay Clark's success.
``Most stores and supermarkets have got Christmas decorations but only a
limited selection. We go from the bottom to the top in terms of
sophistication,'' said Alan. ``In our colour-matched and themed displays we
also try to show people how particular items can be used.''
A new line this Christmas is a range of ceramic Snow Babies - complete with
houses and trees - which are very popular in the United States; and then there
is the Dickens village range of lit-up figures and houses which make ideal
table centre-pieces.
Round the corner a large animated Santa ornament is busy with his paintbrush,
and other moving figures read stories or play festive music.
Candles have always been a part of Christmas, and the growing popularity of
Scandinavian wooden candelabra is also reflected in an impressive display.
In the giftware section everything is just that little bit different, that
little bit special.
``Again we specifically aim to buy giftware that is not going to be readily
available in shops in the town.
``As well as our brassware there's a whole range of continental glassware,
rustic-style, as well as more traditional Caithness-style glass.
``There's a range of terracotta ware and all different styles of ceramics, and
we show how you can mix and match to suit your own particular environment.''
There are toiletries from Crabtree and Evelyn, napkins for Christmas parties,
shortbread and biscuits, right through to gourmet foodstuffs. Fresh whole
apricots, whole cherries in syrup, and fresh pears in wine are all avilable
from the preserves stand.
As you might expect, house plants are a big seller.
``You can buy everything from a bottle garden plant from one inch high right up
to six-inch specimens. We have got palm trees, weeping figs, and all sorts of
hanging plants, both flowering and foliage.
``We have a big range of orchids, which are becoming more and more popular as
Christmas presents, because the prices have become quite reasonable.''
The poinsettias are very eye-catching, particularly the bi-coloured variety in
creamy yellow with a pink centre. Mini-clerodendrons in flower and cyclamen -
from the small variety to the large flower-covered hybrid - are other
attractive gift ideas.
``Large plants make nice presents, particularly the foliage plants which can be
quite unusual. People appreciate them because they can enjoy them all year
round.
``Air plants - arranged, for example, around ceramic figures and animals - are
popular too because they take no looking after. We also sell bits and pieces
for making your own arrangements.
``Then there are the traditional terrariums and new ones from the continent
with mirrors behind them.''
The centre also specialises in bonsai trees - ready arranged and in kits,
complete with tools, scissors, and instructions.
And just because winter awaits doesn't mean the garden has to be bare. ``We
have a range of outdoor plant arrangements which you can still use to brighten
up the patio at Christmas. There is a range of figs, ivys, conifers, and
winter-flowering plants; jasmin and camellia, which is ideal for an unheated
conservatory and which flowers in January and February. There is a range of
winter-flowering shrubs, hollies, Christmas roses, and ornamental cabbages, all
displayed in containers for the patio.''
If you're looking for the ideal gift for the outdoor-type, you'll be spoilt for
choice in the Stirlingshire Saddlery, which stocks a huge range of outdoor
clothing, hats, and footwear alongside the saddles and bridleware.
But before you return to your car in the centre's massive free car park you can
relax in the Egon Ronay-recommended Famous Coffee House with a light meal,
snack, coffee and cake, or even Nardini ice cream.
Oh, and don't forget that wrapping paper - and the bows and ribbons and
ornamental filigree . . .
</TEXT>
