<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hill farmers' struggle goes on</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAN BUGLASS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110183</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE struggle to secure the financial survival of Scotland's hill farmers in the
north and west is set to continue, according to John Ross, the president of the
NFU.
Clearly disappointed at the Government's decision on Tuesday to do no more than
hold the current levels of HLCAs, Mr Ross has now indicated that further
pressure will be applied on the Scottish Office in the union's efforts to
consider the special needs of the Highlands.
Last year no less than #40.8m came to Scotland's 13,500 hill farmers, but Mr
Ross reckons that this is insufficient to cope with the special needs of some
extremely disadvantaged areas.
In early October the NFU met a large number of hill farmers in Fort William who
recounted their difficulties. Mr Ross was clearly impressed with their
arguments for higher subsidies. Commenting on that submission yesterday he
said: ``We're not talking about inches of rain - we're talking about nine feet
and lambing figures frequently no more than 55%. Agriculture in these areas is
on the knife edge.''
The Scottish Office agriculture team headed by the Minister, Lord Lindsay, are
fully aware of these problems but sources claim that to hold the line in a time
of cuts in public expenditure should be viewed as being positive rather than
negative. Meanwhile the UK farming unions are quietly - and very much off the
record - congratulating themselves in a similar vein.
In Scotland the argument for increased HLCAs has not been helped by the record
statistics revolving around the annual sales of Blackface rams. At the
principle sales just short of 6000 rams grossed #3.7m while a 44 rams sold at
#10,000 each or more. The top bid of #50,000 came at Lanark last month for a
six-months-old ram lamb, while all those rams averaged no less than #611. That
figure has been widely taken to suggest that the pleas of poverty are more
localised than general.
Efforts to highlight the special difficulties of the remote areas will continue
and the NFU is sure to stress that these will increase if the new proposed EU
Transport Regulations are implemented in their draft form. Feed costs are also
on the increase. The official Government line will reveal early in the new year
that hill farming incomes for 1995 have risen by just over 10%.
</TEXT>
