<BYLINE>KRISTY DORSEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110186</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Investment Trust, which holds a broad-based international portfolio,
easily beat its benchmark index in the year to October 31.
The independent Edinburgh-based trust with total assets of #909.9m saw net
asset value per share rise 12.4% to 281.4p.
That was well ahead of its benchmark, the FT/S&amp;P Actuaries World Index, which
rose by 9.2%.
Fund manager Ian McLeish said strong performances in UK and US equity markets,
the appreciation of bond holdings, some special one-off dividends and a 27%
increase in the trust's unlisted portfolio all helped to achieve a record
performance.
The only drag on overall performance came from emerging markets hit by the
aftermath of the Mexican financial crisis, but they only account for 12.7% of
SIT's equities assets.
``The markets in the Far East really didn't do a great deal over the last
year,'' Mr McLeish said, ``But our view is that these areas will come around
again - they're very high-growth areas.'' With that philosophy in mind, the
trust chose to increase its investment in emerging markets by #19.5m in the
year to October.
Mr McLeish said this constituted only a small part of the overall #78.8m
increase in holdings of quoted equities during the year.
The increase was partly funded by #44.3m generated from the conversion of
warrants into trust shares in February.
</TEXT>
