<HEADLINE>Korean eyes on the world top ten</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>99</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110188</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n KOREAN car companies regularly predict that they will be in the motor
industry world-wide top ten by the turn of the century.
Some observers regard this as fairly unlikely, since there are still many
Korean cars which lean heavily on old-fashioned or borrowed technology and
styling. That is really no surprise, considering that most of the Korean
manufacturers drifted into motor manufacturing sideways.
There are examples in the Scottish motor trade of businesses which began as
one-man operations developing into networks with dozens of branches. But
Hyundai Motor Company, the Korean industry leader, puts things into perspective.
It was founded in 1940 as a small-vehicle repair shop, and is now part of
Korea's largest business conglomerate, Hyundai Business Group. There are
170,000 employees world-wide, and annual sales exceeding #45 billion.
Kia was originally a precision engineering company, while SsangYong opened for
business in 1939, making handicrafts. Then it transformed itself into another
conglomerate with interests in cement, oil refining and, latterly, vehicle
manufacture.
Daewoo, which is currently pioneering the direct marketing of cars in Britain,
was founded in 1967 as an exporter of clothing and textiles. Now the Daewoo
Group, with interests as varied as hotels and space technology, is in the weird
situation of including two quite separate car-building enterprises . . .
Daewoo Motor is the obvious one, but points in a motor-club quiz might be won
by somebody who knew that the other - working with assistance from Suzuki - is
Daewoo Shipbuilding!
</TEXT>
