<DOCNO>GH951201-000044</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000044</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Power turns on the Lantra</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROSS FINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>99</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110190</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN it comes to offering opinions on cars from the countries usually lumped
together as the Pacific Rim, many observers reckon that the cheaper models are
the ones to go for. They often reckon there's no point in paying extra for
top-line versions which simply do not justify the additional cost. That trend
of thought may have hit the buffers, thanks to the new Hyundai Lantra.
Driving a 1.6-litre saloon before its bigger-brother 1.8, I felt the first car
was smooth and nimble enough. But the extra 200cc of the new 1.8-litre Beta
engine - the second in the series of Hyundai's own self-designed power units -
seemed a bigger step up in performance and response than the modest increase in
capacity implied.
On a hilly coastal route, the well-equipped 1.8 Lantra really stormed away,
thanks partly to the fine power-to-weight ratio produced by its 125bhp engine,
in a bodyshell lighter than several of its European rivals.
But there was a good torque spread too, as well as more accurate steering than
many Korean cars provide, plus quite sporting handling and a four-square
stability on the road.
Using multi-curved body panels with nothing in the way of ornamentation or
external clutter, the new Lantra looks well in the metal and is a much more
stylish car than the smaller Accent. Trim levels and interior layout are
attractive and businesslike, but, whereas the ugly-duckling Accent has
excellent passenger space for its class, the Lantra scores fewer points for its
rear-seat accommodation.
One stretch of unusually bumpy road produced an odd effect in several of the
test fleet cars. A curious chittering noise was eventually traced to the glass
sunroof vibrating. However, the effect was never heard on normal tarmac.
Hyundai is trying hard to create a new image for itself with the latest Lantra,
and its marketing in this country is about to become much more forceful.
While the appearance of the car is a match for most of its class competitors,
and the performance package, especially with the 1.8-litre engine, no longer
lags behind, the company's big advantage remains in its pricing structure.
The Lantra is a well-finished and well-presented car, with the entry level 1.6
LSi very competitively priced at #9999.
The better equipped 1.6 GLSi costs #11,499, the 1.8 Si comes in at #12,299, but
the version which goes against the old take-the-cheapest theory is the 1.8 CD.
This model costs #13,749 inclusive of air-conditioning and anti-lock brakes,
which are #1869 optional extras on other models. It looks and drives like
unusually good value for money.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
