<DOCNO>GH951201-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Names of dead used by loan swindler</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110191</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LOAN firm executive arranged false loans using the names of dead people.
Douglas Paterson, 45, took out a total of 17 false loans using the names of
former customers and the deceased in a fraud lasting almost six years.
At Edinburgh Sheriff Court yesterday Paterson, of Craiglockhart Terrace,
Edinburgh, admitted acting with others to defraud the firm he worked for, Wagon
Finance Ltd, of #383,700 between 1986 and 1992.
He was caught out when the firm sent letters to customers direct from its
Middlesex head office and received queries.
A woman whose husband had died before he had supposedly got a loan and a man
who had paid off his loan and was surprised to learn he had taken out another,
both complained.
Depute-fiscal Jacqueline Currie said that the fraud began when Paterson was
manager of the firm's Inverness branch.
Two large loans had gone bad and there was no prospect of getting the money
back, so Paterson started making the bogus loan applications to get money to
pay back the bad debt.
As well as paying for the original bad loans, he was servicing the bogus loans
and he had to make more false applications to pay for them.
Until about 1990, Paterson just used the false loans to pay off other false
loans but he then started taking money from the account for himself.
Miss Currie said that although the total amount of the false loans was #383,700
many of the loans were paid off with interest and profit and the loss to Wagon
Finance amounted to #150,291.
Paterson and another employee in the Inverness office were sacked when the
fraud was discovered in 1992.
Defence solicitor Eric Scott said that Paterson had settled with the firm by
paying it all his assets.
Sheriff John Horsburgh, QC, deferred sentence for background reports until
December 20 and allowed Paterson bail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>City takes heart from  GrandMet chairman</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110192</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE valedictory presentation to the City by Grand Metropolitan's Lord Sheppard
was greeted with considerably more enthusiasm than most he has given since he
became chairman in 1987.
Market reaction to the 3.5% decline in pre-tax profits to #912m, ignoring last
time's #291m of exceptional reorganisation costs, was to push the shares
marginally ahead to 442p, with sentiment encouraged by the evidence that the
Pillsbury reorganisations are now taking effect.
Other changes are further back up the line but even so, cost savings in the
year to September amounted to #83m and more than enough to offset the #71m blow
from the loss of the distributorships for Absolut vodka and Grand Marnier
liqueur.
Lord Sheppard, who is being succeeded by George Bull, happily pointed out how
he had sold the Intercontinental Hotels at the peak of the market and quit the
milk industry before the deregulation chaos, while also making excellent
purchases such as Hublein and Pillsbury, which brought in the Burger King
franchise operation.
The most worriesome aspect is the dullish performance in IDV, where Europe was
disappointing. Overall spirits volumes rose just 2%, with the top five brands
led by Smirnoff, ahead by 4%.
Although GrandMet has over a dozen of the world's 100 top-selling spirits, it
needs one or two additional very high case volume brands on the lines of
Baileys, with both Smirnoff and J&amp;B scotch showing negligible improvements. But
Scotch does not seem able to excite the young drinker in most markets and who
look for alternatives including American whiskies and the newer spirits such as
tequila.
Pricing remains under pressure and although Mr Bull is hoping for a 2% rise
this year as are his competitors, that will require hard pounding.
Burger King operating profits were marginally ahead at #166m on a 7% rise in
turnover to #5230m. An additional 657 restaurants were added to the chain to
bring the total to 8030 and with claims that it is the best performing
hamburger chain in the US as regards growth. However, there was a reduction in
refranchising profits of #34m and that trend will continue.
The more mundane Pillsbury foods put in highly respectable figures from its
flour-based products, Green Giant and from its Haagen Dazs ice-cream, although
there is the threat that me-too products will slice away future growth.
GrandMet is spending vastly on advertising, with the budget last year leaping
19.7% to #1079m. Fortunately, it does have the cash flow to support this.
The dividend total has been raised 6.8% to 14.9p with a 9.4p final.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
