<DOCNO>GH951201-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Skimming milk price</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110193</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FUTURE pricing policy for milk will mean that altering the balance between fat
and protein will become increasingly important for farmers wishing to stay in
profit, says David Roberts, senior dairy specialist with the Scottish
Agricultural College.
His view is that keeping milk fat levels down will be a vital aim. Research at
SAC has shown that there are many ways to reduce fat percentage while
maintaining milk yield and protein content.
``Our experience is that there is no quick fix for increasing milk protein
content,'' he said.
``Certainly there is no need to invest in expensive feeding equipment to
achieve these increases. Modest but worthwhile increases of up to 0.2% can be
achieved easily by changing the diet.''
Longer terms or larger increases need a combination of factors.
Results from SAC's Acrehead Unit show consistent year on year increases in milk
protein content by paying attention to feeding the dry cow, changing the
composition of a concentrate and by improving silage quality.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
