<DOCNO>GH951201-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Construction firm consolidates interests in west of Scotland Miller opens Glasgow office</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KRISTY DORSEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>25</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975110194</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDINBURGH-based Miller Group, one of the largest privately-owned housing,
construction and development companies in Scotland, officially opened its
Glasgow office at 35 Baird Street yesterday.
Miller Group chief executive Keith Miller said the new office would give the
group a focused area from which to run its various business interests in the
west of Scotland.
The group provides a full range of construction services covered by the five
main areas of civil engineering, construction, developments, homes and mining.
``Miller Group developments can be found throughout the west coast of
Scotland,'' Mr Miller said. ``With our strong ties in this area, we firmly
believe that now is the ideal time for the company to consolidate its business
ventures by launching a new office in Glasgow.''
The #13m refurbishment of Celtic Park, the upgrading of the M74 and the M8, and
housing developments in Paisley, Bearsden, East Kilbride and Newton Mearns
represent some of Miller's western Scottish interests.
CBI Scotland director Iain McMillan, who performed the opening ceremony, said
the Miller Group was an excellent example of the kind of company the CBI wants
to encourage: a stable, steady-growth business with effective management and a
commitment to organised development.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A taste of his own remedy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975110195</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Herald, I fear, ``carries too much fat - which at the end of the day means
we all pay more than we have to''. How about giving the ``redneck'' George
Birrell (November 25) a taste of the non-``eunuch'' discipline that he
recommends so freely for other so-called incompetents, ``eviction by the
rampant forces of capitalism''?
In a previous incarnation in a soi-disant ``Scottish'' tabloid I believe he
proved to be mathematically challenged. Now in The Herald he has shown himself
to be stylistically, orthographically, and grammatically challenged.
I presume the ``grey-haired grannies eeking out an existence in sub-post
offices in Highland villages'' were squealing at his appearance on the opposite
side of the counter. ``Irresistable'' is proof of lax spelling, while he must
think that ``siren message'' implies a warning hooter, not a mythological
reference of quite a different meaning.
I refrain from mentioning the many other inelegances and infelicities but
merely suggest that he should pay back part of his fee for every such mistake,
or better still be shown the door for incompetence.
Charles Blakely,
11 Braidwood Road, Kilwinning.
</TEXT>
