<DOCNO>GH951201-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Changes are essential for profitability and competitiveness</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975110196</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Herald is an important publication in shaping public opinion, so it is
disappointing that your article of November 30 on the Hamilton postal strike
did not give the full picture. What was missing was Royal Mail's side of the
story.
Unfortunately, the lengthy story also contained inaccuracies which, in order to
give the readers the full picture, have to be addressed.
First it was stated that Royal Mail last year made a profit of #1500m. Not so.
The pre-tax profit for the last financial year was #302m.
The profit strategies of the Post Office Group, of which Royal Mail is part,
are driven by the need to meet Treasury cash targets. In the last financial
year the group had to pay to Treasury coffers more than #200m - and this was
before we had to pay a further #110m in Corporation Tax.
Readers may be interested to know that, over the past decade, the Post Office
Group has paid to Government some #1250m at today's prices.
Second, the story refers to alleged cutting back on second-delivery mail. Let's
be crystal clear: Royal Mail has not cut second deliveries to a single
customer. Second deliveries are important to us and they are important to
customers.
The reality is that we are now getting much more mail through in time for first
delivery and we need to change so that we have enough staff to carry out these
first deliveries while not being overstaffed for the much lighter load of
second deliveries. All we are doing is changing the mix of staffing. There is
absolutely no threat to second deliveries.
The key driver for the changes we are seeking is ensuring that our customers
receive their mail when it is ready. The only counter suggestion that we have
received to our proposals is to hold back mail which is ready for first
delivery in order to justify the overstaffing on second deliveries. That's
unacceptable to us and to our customers.
Third, there was an allegation that the changes were are seeking are ``just
about saving money''. Not true. They are driven by the need to meet customers'
rising expectations and by the fact that we must keep pace with competitors.
The reported massive rise in business for courier and fax companies over the
past week testifies to this.
The best way to secure long-term job security is to exceed customer
expectations and to beat the competition. We need to change to ensure we remain
successful as a business which provides a nationwide service at a universal
price.
Fourth, the article referred to a trend towards casualisation. With change on
the horizon our strategy has been to employ staff on a temporary basis over and
above our permanent staff to ensure that our core of permanent employees is
protected. This has been successful and, indeed, since June we have been able
to offer permanent jobs to 800 temporary staff.
Alex Gibb,
Director Delivery,
Royal Mail Scotland and Northern Ireland,
102 West Port, Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Reid and Duffy take over as Dixon relinquishes control</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER  CHIEF FOOTBALL WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975110197</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
By KEN GALLACHER
DUNDEE Football Club are in new, but familiar, hands this morning after the
Canadian millionaire Ron Dixon, owner of the Dens Park team for close to five
years, finally relinquished control as forecast in The Herald 24 hours earlier.
The departing Dixon forecast that manager Jim Duffy could become the chairman
of the Tayside club in the future. Said Dixon: ``I hope that Jim Duffy would
eventually become chairman of the club when the other people involved may
decide to move out.''
Dixon, of course, has never hidden his admiration for the player-manager who
carried Dundee into the Coca-Cola Cup final against Aberdeen just last Sunday.
And yesterday it emerged that Duffy and his vice-chairman Malcolm Reid were
involved in the #3m buy-out of the club with financial backing from two local
businessmen.
The earlier indications had been that the Vancouver-based Dixon wanted #2.2m
for the club but hoped to retain the stadium itself. That was always going to
be a major problem in any deal but the one announced yesterday had Dens Park
being transferred to the new consortium along with the football club.
Said Dixon: ``I have had offers for the club before but I did not feel it was
appropriate to sell to the earlier bidders. This is a deal which is right for
this club.''
Dixon arrived back unexpectedly in Scotland to attend the final last Sunday
and, almost immediately, he was setting the wheel in motion to sell. After a
lengthy and mysterious absence from Dundee, he explained he was looking after
more pressing business interests in other parts of the world and talked of the
possibility of a merger between his club and their local rivals Dundee United.
Yesterday that kind of talk was forgotten as the deal         for new ownership
was announced at Dens Park.
Dixon maintained: ``This sale was at my initiative. The club is going to go on
and get stronger. It was on the verge of being closed down when I took over.
Now there are no debts and the new men in charge are the right people to take
things forward.
``Malcolm Reid has learned a lot about running the club in the last few years
and he will be chairman now, but eventually I believe Jim Duffy will take on
that role. He and Jimmy Nicholl are the two best coaches in the country and Jim
teaches young men how to lead their lives as well as play football.
``I am happy to leave these men in charge . . .''
Said life-long Dundee supporter Reid, the new chairman: ``People should
appreciate just what Ron Dixon has done for this club. Now I hope that the
locals will get behind us when they see what we are trying to achieve here.''
The first-division club have known troubled times but now the uncertainty
appears to have gone. Reid is respected in the city, and Duffy after his recent
cup run, and the promotion possibility which exists for the club is revered.
The #3m buying price - Dixon bought the club for just #600,000 and then gave a
peronal loan of #1.5m to clear outstanding debts - is due to be paid over a
five-year period.
q DUNDEE United front players Andy McLaren and Robbie Winters have accepted new
contracts with the Tannadice club.
Manager Billy Kirkwood has spent most of the season adding big-money buys to
the United staff in a bid to return to the premier division. But he said last
night: ``These two young players have loads of potential and securing them on
longer contracts is every bit as important as spending vast amounts in the
transfer market.''
</TEXT>
