<DOCID>GH951201-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>`Prince' can rule supreme</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WHITE GOLD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>36</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110198</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EGYPT Mill Prince looks the one to be on in the Crowngap Construction Handicap
Chase at Sandown today.
He has often been the supporting act in big races, none more so than in the
Mackeson Gold Cup in which he has been placed in each of the last three seasons.
It looked as though he had stolen the show when he jumped into the lead at the
last in the Cheltenham feature this term, only for Dublin Flyer to head him in
a stirring finish.
That was a fine effort from Egypt Mill Prince against a horse who goes into the
King George VI Chase at Kempton on Boxing Day with a leading chance.
Flyer's Nap can pass his big-race audition in the P &amp; O Handicap Chase. Robert
Alner will have the Welsh National at Chepstow on December 27 in mind for the
gelding who gave the trainer the biggest win of his career in the Fulke Walwyn
Kim Muir Chase at the Cheltenham Festival last March.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
