<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Alert over Arran water. Lecturer in sheep dip call</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAIN WILSON and JENNIFER CUNNINGHAM</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110200</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LECTURER in food safety is preparing a formal complaint to the European Union
over alleged breaches of drinking water regulations involving sheep dip
pesticides on the island of Arran.
Dr Lewis Routledge claims that tests for sheep dip residues by Strathclyde
Regional Council's water department have taken place mainly outwith the dipping
season.
He fears that watercourses have been contaminated - and wants urgent action to
guarantee that water quality standards are maintained.
A Strathclyde spokesman yesterday said Mr Routledge was ``creating an
unnecessary scare on the island,'' and insisted:
q Water quality, both chemically and biologically, has received top grade Class
1 categories by the Clyde River Purification Board in tests since his
complaints.
q No sheep dipping takes place in Arran's water catchment areas, and monitoring
on the island meets the Water Supply (Water Quality) (Scotland) Regulations of
1990.
But Mr Routledge is adamant that, when holidaying on Arran in July, he was told
by a bailiff that it was ``common practice'' for unused sheep dip to be
disposed of by tipping into rivers in spate.
Mr Routledge has already won an EU victory over water quality south of the
Border, and said yesterday: ``I am quite prepared to make a formal complaint to
the EU about Strathclyde.''
He is a food science lecturer at Newcastle College of Higher Education, and his
specialist subject is water pollution.
That interest is now combined with a personal campaign for the safe disposal of
sheep dip chemicals after his twin sons suffered paralysis from contamination
from stored sheep dip south of the Border. Both have since recovered.
Mr Routledge's allegations of breaches in quality standards on Arran have led
to meetings by islanders over complaints about discoloured drinking water.
Their fears were allayed by numerous officials who attended a public meeting
earlier this week.
However, Mr Routledge claims that, over the past three years, four out of five
Strathclyde tests on Arran for sheep dip pesticides were made outwith the
dipping months of August, September and October.
He will complain to the Scottish Office as a first step towards a European
order, boosted by an earlier EU victory against the predecessors of Northumbria
Water over problems with Newcastle water supplies.
Mr Routledge also took heart from the National Centre for Toxic and Persistent
Substances' recent call for the disposal of sheep dip to be reviewed by
Government.
Mr Routledge said: ``I already have a second stage judgment against the UK
Government from the EU on the question of water quality, and this complaint
could be added to that. It could lead to a third stage judgment, which would
leave the Government liable for heavy fines.''
A Strathclyde water services' technical official said that random sampling on
Arran is set 12 months in advance. The programme tests typical samples of
water, as supplied to customers at different times of the year. Not one test
for sheep dip residues had failed.
He added that such results were expected, because all water intakes on the
island are above the level where sheep dipping takes place.
Strathclyde has approved plans for a #6m filtration system for Arran's holding
reservoirs.
</TEXT>
