<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>TV stations calm soapy bubble over festive schedules</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALLAN LAING, Entertainments Writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110201</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was a classic standoff in the TV ratings war. A mischievous scheduling move
by ITV which put EastEnders and Coronation Street head-to-head against each
other on Christmas Day. Soap fans, or at least the ones without video
recorders, would have been faced with the unthinkable - which one would they
watch? Clearly, something had to give . . . and it was the BBC who blinked
first.
Yesterday BBC1 Controller Alan Yentob finally backed down and agreed to
rearrange his Christmas schedule, thereby averting a clash between the two top
programmes.
The scriptwriters for both series have pulled out all the stops to draw viewers
on one of the biggest viewing days of the year. EastEnders promised, not only
Arthur Fowler languishing in the pokey on Christmas Day, but also the shock
return of long-lost and left for dead Frank Butcher. Meanwhile, down Coronation
Street there would be a romantic cliffhanger involving Raquel the barmaid and
her ex, Curly.
When the BBC became aware of the clash earlier this week, Mr Yentob made a
late-night phone call to Marcus Plantin, his ITV counterpart, urging him to
reverse the last-minute decision which created the dilemma. But Plantin stood
firm, forcing an angry Yentob to juggle his schedule.
BBC chiefs accused ITV of manufacturing a situation which was against the
interests of the viewers. But Mr Plantin declared that he reserved the right to
indulge in a spot of ``tweaking'' in the light of other channels' decisions.
His schedule alterations were only made after the BBC revealed details of its
Christmas viewing on Wednesday. EastEnders would be shown in two halves; the
first at 6.30 when it would be up against an ITV special featuring Soldier,
Soldier stars, Jerome and Robson. Mr Yentob even spoke of a truce with ITV to
save soap fans from an agonising decision.
``We've reached an unofficial agreement - I've seen their schedules and they've
seen mine. It was in nobody's interests to pit the two shows against each
other,'' he said.
However, the words were no sooner out of his mouth than ITV rescheduled
Coronation Street for 6.30pm.
A BBC spokesman explained: ``We know from long experience that viewers resent a
manufactured clash of this kind. Once we saw ITV's change to their schedule
after we had announced ours, we had no alternative but to re-schedule our
Christmas in the best interest of the viewers.''
The BBC, which regularly wins the Christmas Day ratings battle, has now
shuffled its mid-evening programmes to slot in EastEnders at 7.30.
Head-to-head clashes between the two soaps are very rare. It happened once
before, when BBC1 introduced a third EastEnders episode in April last year.
ITV was unrepentant about its ruthless rescheduling, which it confirmed was a
response to the BBC's schedule launch.
q A long-awaited return by Inspector Morse gave ITV its biggest peak-time
viewing share this year, it was claimed yesterday. Unofficial overnight figures
showed 15.3 million people tuned in - 64% of the available television audience.
</TEXT>
