<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000056</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000056</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stagecoach gears up for further expansion</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975110202</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STAGECOACH, continues to motor ahead in the fast lane, with a constant eye on
the railways.
The UK's largest private bus operator boosted pre-tax profits by 43% to #20.7m
during the 24 weeks to October 14 and celebrated by raising the interim
dividend 27% to 2.1p.
This pleased the City, where Stagecoach shares rose 5p to 283p.
Ian Wild, a transport analyst with broker BZW, said the results were ``Bang in
line'' with expectations, despite a dip in operating profits on bus operations
in southern England.
Stagecoach passenger traffic rose by 1% during the half year, bucking a 0.5%
decline in UK bus traffic as a whole.
But the Perth-based company is turning its attention to trains and is bidding
for British Rail passenger service franchises as they arise.
Executive chairman Brian Souter shrugged off Stagecoach's failure to make the
shortlist for Great Western and London-Tilbury-Southend, two of the first three
train operating companies to be put on the market.
``We are going in with a very very wide net and I think we will get something
in the end,'' he said.
Stagecoach should hear by Christmas whether or not it has won the third
franchise for South West Trains, which operates services from London to
Southampton and Exeter.
But it also has four other bids in the pipeline, whose outcome should be known
within three months.
Stagecoach has teamed up with the management of Network South Central in London
to bid for both that franchise and the Gatwick Express operation.
It is also gunning for the Inter City East Coast Mainline service from London
to Edinburgh and Midland Mainline, which operates trains from London to
Sheffield.
Mr Souter expressed a firm intention to bid for Scotrail when it eventually
comes on the market, even though he does not regard it as the most attractive
train operating company available.
``We would intend to bid for Scotrail as well, but I would have to say that the
South of England franchises are more interesting,'' the Stagecoach chairman
said.
Mr Souter said a fall in the profitability of Stagecoach bus operations in
southern England over the last six months was mainly due to increasing economic
prosperity in the area.
Many staff were leaving Stagecoach for jobs elsewhere, forcing the company to
spend more on training new drivers, he said. The higher staff turnover also had
a disruptive effect on operations.
Mr Souter said other causes of the disappointing performance were the late
delivery of new buses and the exceptionally hot summer, which kept people off
sweaty crowded buses.
Turnover in southern England remained steady at #21m, but operating profits
there fell 15% to #3.3m.
Stagecoach remains on the lookout for opportunities to buy more bus companies
in the UK and continental Europe, following its venture into Portugal earlier
this year.
The company will take over operation of bus services linking Lisbon with its
western suburbs of Cascais and Sintra on January 1 and already has an eye on
the future privatisation of suburban railway services in that sector.
Mr Souter said the opportunities to buy bus companies in continental Europe
should increase with the approach of a 1999 deadline for all European Union bus
services to be put out to tender.
Stagecoach was also ``well positioned to get further growth in the UK market,''
Mr Souter said, even though it already runs claims to run 13% of the nation's
bus services.
He played down the impact of Stagecoach's repeated run-ins with the Monopolies
and Mergers Commission (MMC) over allegations of unfair competition and
predatory practises. Mr Souter said the second half of the current financial
year could see further acquisitions.
He expressed satisfaction that Derek Morris, a new face, was chairing the
current MMC inquiry into Stagecoach's purchase of Chesterfield Transport in the
north Midlands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>VENTURE CAPITAL Strong performance by 3i</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975110203</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S largest provider of venture capital, 3i, is well placed to track what
is going on in the British economy. As such, its interim results to September
30 reflect the UK's strong economic growth during the period. 3i increased its
total return on shareholders' funds by 13.5% to #277.3m, more than made in the
whole of 1994.
The interim dividend is raised by 10.7% to 3.1p. This is more than double the
rate of increase declared in the investment trust sector so far this year.
The group continues to see a string flow of investment opportunities both in
the UK and in continental Europe. Investments in Scotland were at a record
level, with over #30m of committed new investment, a rise of about #10m on last
year. 3i's Scottish portfolio now stands at 281 companies, with a value of
#269m.
Willie Watt, director of 3i Scotland, drew attention to some of its high level
investments such as DL Wholesalers, Walker Dickson and Clairemont Electronics.
In addition, he added that 3i was pleased to have committed over #13m in 15
emerging Scottish businesses such as Scotsafe and Deveron Environmental.
During the period, the company realised three significant investments. These
included the flotation of Meconic in June, with a valuation of over #40m. 3i
had a 25% stake.
Mr Watt said he expects to see continuing high levels of demand for investment
capital across the spectrum of deals from start-ups to large management
buy-outs. ``We remain committed to being at the forefront of investing in
independent businesses in Scotland'' he added.
In total, 3i invested #324.9m in the first six months of the year, including
#39.7m of third party co-investment funds. Its portfolio at the half-year
consisted of investments in around 3300 businesses with a combined valuation of
over #3200m.
On the revenue side there was a 28% gain in the surplus to #42.2m. Dividend
income from investments rose 30% on a year ago, reflecting higher profitability
of the portfolio. The value of 3i's UK equity portfolio rose 17.4%, ahead of
the FT All-Share index.
Commenting on the performance, chief executive Ewen McPherson said that while
some sectors experienced difficult trading conditions, the majority of the
portfolio continued to benefit from the relatively stable economic environment
and, for UK exporters, more favourable exchange rates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000058</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000058</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stuck in Dickensian mode</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975110204</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OH dear, what a hard life Julie Davidson has, sitting wondering if she's going
to have to pay bank charges because her cheque hasn't arrived (November 24).
Those nasty, lazy, ``incompetent'' postmen just have no idea how they are
affecting the lives of the middle classes who fought so hard to keep them out
of the clutches of privatisation.
Ironically, privatisation might have given them wages and conditions more in
keeping with the last twentieth century than the Dickensian mode they are stuck
in at the moment. I mean can it get any worse than a six-day, 43-hour week
(every week) starting at 5.30am for a basic take-home pay of #140?
This is a hard job, especially in a Scottish winter - no early closures for
snow here! Try walking round in the rain for five hours with four bags of
shopping calling at 400 addresses, and you may have an inkling of how hard.
And remember, no mistakes, Julie Davidson is watching. You may have the secret
police watching too, or managers timing your every movement.
If you're off ill more than twice a year you can expect a warning letter. But
don't think you can air your grievances in a letter to the papers - you can't,
because you've signed the Official Secrets Act.
The postmen and women are not asking for much, just fairness. At the moment
they get the worst of all worlds, neither getting the good hours, conditions,
and holidays of other public servants, nor benefiting financially from the huge
increases in productivity they have achieved (there has been a 40% increase in
the volume of mail handled over the last 10 years).
Managers, trying to justify their own existence, are constantly bringing in
changes.
The Royal Mail has no competition in letter deliveries, it's the most efficient
in the world and it makes massive profits - #480m this year with over #200m
going straight to the government. So what are all these changes for? Profit
versus service.
Postmen and women are at the end of their tether, having been used and abused
for years. They are the infantry off whose backs the rest of the service makes
its living, yet they are treated like some kind of inferior beings.
Much as Julie Davidson hates the fact, the mail service is still a vital part
of the social and economic life of this country and the rest of society,
especially the poor, would miss it if it were to disappear, unlike the personal
musings of an overrated, overpaid, uninspiring feature writer.
Wendy K Foster,
25 Berl Avenue, Houston.
</TEXT>
