<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000059</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000059</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gavin has it tapped</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>37</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110205</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOLLOWING close upon the heels of Gavin Hastings, the book, comes Hastings, the
movie. Hastings' up-dated autobiography was published just a month ago and now
a 75-minute video entitled: ``Hero: The Gavin Hastings Story'' has been
launched.
The former Scottish captain, who retired with a record of 61 international
appearances and a Northern Hemisphere record tally 667 points, charts the
development of his career in the video which marks the first rugby personality
profile from the producers, Cameron-Williams.
Yesterday, executive producer John Williams said that pre-publication sales
mounted to around 20,000 and the target market was 150,000 copies: ``This is on
a par with some of the football videos that we've been involved in.
The video, written, produced, and narrated by Dougie Donnelly, features footage
of the Hastings' career and interviews with family, fellow players, and SRU
director of rugby Jim Telfer, who declares that Hastings was not only an
excellent player but an excellent ambassador for the game.
q.EDINBURGH Academicals have said that their meeting with the SRU over David
Sole's comments about referee Colin Henderson following their match against
Melrose had been ``amicable and constructive'' but because Sole could not be
there, the SRU secretary had been in touch with him to arrange an alternative
date for a meeting.
``However, David has a busy business and family life - catching up on the 10
years he gave almost exclusively to rugby - and there may be some difficulty
dove-tailing arrangements for a meeting,'' said the club.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000060</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000060</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Third time unlucky</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>40</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110206</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DETA Hedman, the world No 2, was the only woman to survive a couple of rounds
in the qualifying competition of the Embassy World Professional Darts
Championship at Earls Court, London, last night. And then it was third time
unlucky.
Women are being allowed to play in this prestigious event for the first time,
and of the 11 in the draw, nine were beaten in two straight sets in their
opening matches, while Welsh internationalist Sandra Greatbach went down 2-1 to
Holland's Bert Vlaardingerbroek.
But Hedman, who lives in Witham, first beat Canadian Carl Mercer in straight
sets, and then defeated John Hook of Middlesex 2-0 in her second match. The
Essex girl, however, still had to win three more matches to be one of the eight
qualifiers who go through to the Embassy Championships at the Lakeside Country
Club, Frimley Green, in January.
Her fine run came to an end in her third match when she was beaten 2-0 by Gary
Spedding, the 27-year-old Cumbria County, player from Workington.
</TEXT>
