<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Firms `cut cash to Tories'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110207</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COMPANY donations to the Conservative Party have dropped, according to research
published today.
A survey found 172 companies gave #2,461,655 to the Tories in the year to March
1995, down from 198 traced as giving #2,836,600 the previous year.
It is the lowest number of companies and the smallest amount given for the last
five years not distorted by the General election, say researchers.
In 1990, the Tories' best non-election year, gifts of #3,815,071 from 309
companies were traced.
The survey appears in the December issue of Labour Research, published by the
independent trade union organisation the Labour Research Department, which
sifts the accounts of about 5000 UK firms each year for evidence of party
donations.
Firms must declare gifts of #200 or more if they produce an annual directors'
report.
Overall, the survey found about 50 companies which had stopped giving to the
Tories in the last 18 months.
They included United Biscuits, who had given an average of nearly #70,000 a
year for 15 years, the Rank Organisation leisure group, which gave a total of
#435,000 between 1979 and 1993, and insurance group Sedgwick, which had given
some #20,000 a year for 15 years.
</TEXT>
