<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000062</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Torrance in share of lead</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>42</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975110208</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SAM Torrance continued his golden year by taking a share of the lead at the Sun
City Million-Dollar Challenge with a three-under-par 69 yesterday.
Torrance, runner-up to fellow Scot Colin Montgomerie in the European Order of
Merit this year, sets the pace alongside US Open champion Corey Pavin.
The American made three birdies in the last four holes to climb up the
leaderboard while Torrance missed a short putt at the last to drop back into a
tie.
Montgomerie, whose three-foot putt on the final hole at Valderrama in October
consigned Torrance to second place on the European Order, was struggling at the
bottom of the 12-man field after a seven-over-par 79. He could not stop pushing
shots to the right as he went out in 40, and also found the greens treacherous.
Defending champion Nick Faldo shot a par 72. He was in touch with Torrance
until a            disastrous triple-bogey 8 at the long ninth. His fourth shot
hit the island green only to spin back into the water. He took three more to
get down and tumbled from three under par to level.
Torrance made the only eagle of the day at the same hole, sinking a 20ft putt
after a superb long-iron shot.
Unusually, heavy rain before the tournament toughened the rough to a level
normally associated with the US Open. With a gusting wind also troubling the
players, there was a premium on straight hitting.
But Pavin said he relished the tough conditions and lavishly praised the Sun
City layout.
``I am in awe of the way the course is set up,'' he said. ``The greens are
perfect .''
Zimbabwe's Nick Price, champion two years ago, bogeyed the last to join
American Tom Lehman at one under, while home favourite Ernie Els was with Faldo
and Bernhard Langer of Germany on level par.
Lehman underlined the difficulty of playing from off the fairway, saying: ``The
first cut of rough is okay but if you are beyond that, you're in big trouble.
If the wind remains, the tournament will be won by a pretty high score.''
q Nobilo birdie blast - Page 40.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Driven to win</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>88</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110209</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN the great days of the BMC Competitions Department, the Monte-winning entries
may have been Mini Coopers. But the tough and powerful sports cars which romped
over the mountain passes of the Alpine Rally, and hammered their way along the
Balkan goat tracks of events like the Spa-Sofia-Liege, were the Austin-Healeys.
BMC had a formidable team of drivers, especially in the Austin-Healey 3000s;
people like Donald Morley, Timo Makinen, Logan Morrison from Stirling, Paddy
Hopkirk and Pat Moss, who shattered the rally establishment by winning the
Liege-Rome-Liege outright.
Five Austin-Healey 3000s were built up for the works team in 1962, all with ARX
registration numbers. Through the years 37, 47, 57 and 77 ARX have all
disappeared, some cannibalised by the works mechanics to keep other Healeys in
fighting trim. The only one to survive, and in remarkably original condition,
is 67 ARX, now in the safe keeping of Tom Fitzsimmons. When the factory sold it
off in 1964, it was bought by long-time Austin-Healey enthusiast Ted Worswick,
and then passed to Syd Segal, who had a stable of ex-works Healeys, dismantled
67 ARX and never found the opportunity to bolt it all together again.
The next English owner, Nick Hill, put it back on the road, but not in the
spoiled ``super-restored'' condition in which many famous competition cars are
seen. He rebuilt it just as it had been in its heyday, still with the little
gadget behind the seats where the Morley twins kept their vacuum flasks, since
the original locations in the doors shattered them to bits.
In 1988 Victor Gauntlett, well known as part-owner of Aston Martin Lagonda Ltd,
bid #128,000 for 67 ARX at auction. He did some classic rallies with it, but
was equally careful to leave the car in original trim.
After a few years' ownership, Gauntlett in his turn put 67 ARX into an auction.
Prices had faded by that time, and it was not bid to anything like its reserve.
Tom Fitzsimmons came to a private arrangement with Gauntlett, and brought the
car to Scotland.
After a recent rebuild of the triple-Weber engine by yet another Healey
specialist, John Chatham, 67 ARX has probably had a power boost over the 210bhp
or so it produced during its works-team career. It may now be heading towards
240.
All the logbooks kept during the car's career are still with it. This is one
famous machine whose provenance cannot be doubted.
Tom Fitzsimmons is keener on racing than on rallying, and 67 ARX, as a genuine
classic competition car, has been invited to events at the Nurburgring and
Dijon, and the famous Coys weekend at Silverstone. But if an ex-works Healey
ever dreams, 67 ARX will drift back to the days when it was scrambling for time
over the dusty roads to Titograd, or powering up the hairpins of the Col de
Restefond.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Academy Chamber Orchestra, RSAMD, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Kenny Mathieson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975110210</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is a fact of contemporary musical life in Scotland that we have high
expectations of the standards reached by our student ensembles. There was
little doubt that the Academy Chamber Orchestra would play with a high degree
of technical proficiency, confirmed last night in a relaxed reading of
Schubert's Overture in the Italian Style in D major.
The same composer's Unfinished Symphony posed a greater challenge. For the most
part the students rose to it, although they might have benefited from the
firmer control of a conductor here, rather than the direction of Leon Spierer
from the first violin chair. Both the quality of the ensemble sound and their
command of dynamics and rhythm were impressive, and if they did not always
succeed in turning the notes into fully expressive music-making, they did find
a lovely expansiveness at times.
Doubtless suitably encouraged by that success, they turned their attention to
Beethoven, opening the second half with a bold, energised performance of the
Prometheus Overture. Spierer led by example throughout, and they responded with
a sparkling account of the sunny, playful Symphony No 1, in which the finer
nuances of inner detail received scrupulous attention.
An occasional tentativeness aside, these were all confident performances which
required little allowance for the inexperience of the performers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
