<HEADLINE>A man of basic instincts</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Douglas Thompson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975110211</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A man
of basic
instincts
Douglas Thompson talks to Michael Douglas, an actor who knows intimately the
excesses
of Hollywood living, about the breakdown of his marriage and the importance of
family ties
A haircut says it all about the generation gap. Cameron Douglas, son of
Michael, grandson of Kirk, aspiring actor and the new kid on this particular
family's Hollywood block, attended the glittering premier of his father's new
movie with an ever so closely cropped head.
Later his father, with his hair curling around the collar of his checked sports
jacket, was laughing as he said: ``When I was in my rebel stage I just wanted
my hair long. Now he can't get it short enough.
``It's all about growing up, and Cameron is into that difficult 15 to 16 to 17
period. I can still remember how complicated these years were. My parents were
divorced and that was hard to handle for me. Now Cameron has to deal with the
separation of myself and his mother.''
Michael Douglas and his dramatic looking wife - he met the then 19-year-old
Spanish-born Diandra Mornell Luker on the eve of Jimmy Carter's presidential
inauguration and they married eight weeks later in 1977 - split up this summer
amid ongoing reports of his serial philandering.
It had always been a tense marriage. He was 32 when they married and had been
around - he lived for five years with smokey voiced actress Brenda Vaccaro -
while his wife was a young student with no friends or family in America.
She had dropped out of her diplomacy studies in Washington and moved with her
husband to Los Angeles. He says now that was probably a mistake. Hollywood was
a tough town for a nave, sheltered, sweet-natured, newly-wed Senora. She
didn't fit in.
``She knew nobody, she felt she walked in my shadow, she had nothing to occupy
her while I buzzed around this wonderful, exciting life,'' says her now
estranged husband.
He adds: ``And I wasn't exactly the most understanding husband. A large part of
me believes in the work ethic, being the provider - it's in the genes, I guess.
I worked really hard to provide and I'm sure she still bitches about how hard I
work.
``And I have to agree that I didn't spend the appropriate time, enough time, at
home. I know how difficult it is for ladies who don't have a career, per se, in
terms of finding out who they are and their own identity.
``In other relationships in my life I've dealt with that. But I don't have a
lot of patience with it. I've always felt like I'm working hard, providing,
making a good home, a good life for everybody - which is not to be sneered at.
And if you're having identity problems, go get something to do.''
Sixteen years ago Diandra Douglas did just that. She got pregnant. Her aim was
to be the perfect wife and mother.
She complains now her husband made the job difficult: ``You can't have a
healthy family life with children when you're away 10 months of the year.
Cameron and I are such close friends because in a way we grew up together.''
The couple are living in separate homes. Cameron lives with his mother and is
attending a Californian high school. His father says the youngster wants to be
a radio DJ and then move on to film school.
However, he adds: ``Give the guy a break. I didn't start acting until I was 23.
Cameron's 16. I see my kid playing football now and he's struggling on a team
and he's got another year to go and he says: `Well, dad, I don't know if I'll
be playing a whole lot.' And I say: `Cameron you're playing, man. You're
playing a southern Californian high school football team. What do you want?' It
makes me proud. I used to play football and all of a sudden I see my son out
there.
``You want to nurture, but basically this is coming to me late. You just try to
hang out and you get a little shot of wisdom in there along the line.''
He himself was a youngster when his parents divorced. He went to live with his
mother, now Diana Darrid, in New York. She took him to California for a year
when he was 11. He recalls: ``I'd been to private school - blue blazer, flannel
shorts. Junior High in Los Angeles was a shock. It was a tough school. They had
killings. Kids carried knives. I remember the first girl I ever kissed there.
She had her mouth wide open. Yuk! I couldn't believe it. Nobody told me
anything about this!''
More of a shock was seeing his father make love on screen, most notably to Lana
Turner in The Bad and the Beautiful. ``I sneaked on to the set while they were
doing a love scene. That memory will stay with me always - boy, it was hot. But
my father was embarrassed about the whole thing.''
Cameron has seen his own father in action with Sharon Stone, Glenn Close, and
Demi Moore. ``He knows it's just movie-making. When he was younger he saw Fatal
Attraction at a friend's house. I wouldn't have wanted that but he dealt with
it. He's got a good heart and he knows about the movie business. Like me he's
been brought up in it. Come on, he wants to be part of it.''
Douglas is matter of fact about almost everything. In answer to reports that he
was treated for sex addiction he says he did go into the Sierra Tucson
rehabilitation centre in Arizona three years ago, but adds: ``There wasn't
anything to all that. I went to rehab for alcohol abuse. I had done Basic
Instinct and it got started. Sex addiction? I mean, I wish it was that simple.''
He says his problem resulted from 25 years of hard working and drinking,
``pressure and knocking it back''. He also had the pressure of a famous father
to deal with. As his son Cameron has today.
Cameron has watched his father's name - maybe infamy - rise following his Oscar
for Gordon Gekko, an eerie mirror of Kirk Douglas's best roles, in Wall Street
in 1987 and then the sex dramas Fatal Attraction, Basic Instinct and last
year's Disclosure.
``People hooked these pictures into my own private life. But a marriage is a
marriage. I celebrated 18 years of marriage. Over 50% of marriage in this
country ends in divorce.''
He leans forward in his chair in a Beverly Hills hotel suite. His knee is
jumping. He looks cool and healthy but he does fidget. He's anxious for a
Marlboro. You ask about the marriage surviving: ``Well, we have separate abodes
but we talk every day. And of course we have the common bond of Cameron. We
have a son we love a lot. I don't know......'' Then he laughs and adds: ``You
know, we get on better now we're apart than at some times during the marriage.''
He is remarkably philosophical about his situation. Cameron lives with his
mother - at one point this year his father was living with his mother who also
attended the gala screening for The American President. Douglas plays a widower
President with a teenage daughter. He is attracted by environmental lobbyist
Annette Bening (aka Mrs Warren Beatty) and in an election year publicly begins
to court her. Oval Office romance hurts him in the opinion polls. But he's in
love.
It is romantic comedy played by very politically correct rules by all concerned
- these are liberal, that is Democratic, film-makers and any comparison to
skirt chasing in the Clinton White House is just, they tell us, fiction.
Even the sex - especially for a Michael Douglas movie - is old fashioned Disney
one foot on the floor stuff. And the leading man is likeable not leering.
Douglas does laugh and smile a lot during an hour's talking.
He admits he walked in his father's shadow and had to prove himself to himself
and Hollywood - and to his father. ``That was exactly it for years.''
He's 51 now and says when he turned 50 he felt he had accomplished everything
he wanted. It's hard to accept when it's explained he has a dozen film projects
in the pipeline as actor and producer - he won an Oscar for producing One Flew
Over the Cuckoo's Nest when he was 31.
But Spartacus and all those other giant roles his father played in turn played
with his brain: ``I wouldn't exactly say it was an inferiority complex. I think
early on as an actor or even before I started acting when I had a father to
follow who had 10,000 warriors or fleets of Viking ships...... there was a
larger than life persona.
``And you know my father, even in real life he has a dynamic quality about him
and so I figured early on: `My God, how can I ever be the man my father is?'
But what happens is you get your own career and your own sense of yourself and
your own work. You get to appreciate him much, much more.
``My father has been really supportive and has had a great time with my success
so we have never really competed. People ask that question and he always says
you don't understand.
``It's a sense of immortality to watch your son, and then your grandson gives
you a sense of immortality. As he's gone into his seventies it's become a
little more important in his life. He's been great.
``As far as Cameron is concerned - he's dad's only grandson - he'll be fine.
He's had to deal with the same things I did. Sometimes he would come home and
say: `You know, dad, the only reason the kids like me at school is because of
you. Because you're hot - and girls like you.' I said: `Cameron, I remember
exactly that as a kid and felt the same thing. They'd say he's Kirk Douglas's
son.'
``Now, they say: `Here's Michael Douglas's son.'' This happened to him and he
had to struggle through that kind of stuff. But he's got a good sense of
confidence. I remember watching him twirl his hair. I do the same thing. And my
mother does it. Now most of the hair is gone. It'll grow back.''
Just as in any other family the children need growth in other ways too. It just
takes some longer than others......
</TEXT>
</DOC>
