<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Greenock Central, Greenock Arts Guild</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Sara Villiers</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975110213</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE quips from the audience almost outnumbered those in John Maley's script in
this boisterously, if enthusiastically, received production. But not quite. One
heckler's admonition that ``you have to go to the canteen tae smoke here'' to
some on-stage puffing raised some giggles but the cast had plenty of sharply
observed one-liners to fire back with, such as the caustic comment to a
teenager addicted to the lottery instants cards, ``You'd be better off
scratching your balls.''
Full of ribald and raucous energy this CAT, a theatre collaboration with NCH
Action for Children in association with Inverclyde Intensive Probation Unit,
gives voice to the preoccupations and lifestyles of local youths. Thankfully
the constant humour offset what was otherwise a very bleak picture of days spun
out by shoplifting, gambling, and descent into heroin addiction.
The overriding message - drugs are for mugs - is hardly an original one but the
performances were engaging.
Although director Irvine Allan has split the action into irritatingly short
sequences, which make the thin narrative very jagged, it's an absorbing slice
of live drama. The production is accompanied by a visual arts exhibition and
the final performance on Saturday will be followed by a gig by Whiteout.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000068</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000068</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scotland: the way ahead is clear</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975110214</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ST ANDREW is a long-suffering sort of saint: yesterday, on his name day, three
separate sets of politicians and activists pinned the saltire on their own
proposals for Scotland's future. In the way of these things only one will win
favour with the electorate, and that is just as well. In Edinburgh the Scottish
Constitutional Convention's proposals for a Scottish Parliament were formally
launched with dignity, ceremonial, and the inevitable pipe band. Mr Alex
Salmond of the Scottish National Party chose the same moment to describe his
own constitutional blueprint and, straining the patience of the Saint to
breaking point, the Secretary of State for Scotland produced the detailed
version of his musings on the subject.
Behind the gallimaufry of the day there is a desperately serious point. All of
these proposals deal directly with the future governance of Scotland and it is
clear that in this country, just as in the rest of Britain, there is a deep
antipathy to the current political dispensation. That assertion does not hang
unsupported; all political parties report as much, although they do not like to
speak of it. Last week the annual survey of British Social Attitudes
illustrated the depth of cynicism abroad in the land and reported that fewer
than one in four voters had the slightest confidence that politicians put
nation before party. The effect was particularly notable among the young and
there is no doubt that the same effect applies throughout Scotland, though
hopefully in a less damaging manner.
Yet we have one great advantage, and it was on display in all its distinctly
variable glory yesterday. The very illogicality of the political situation in
Scotland, where poll after poll shows a desire for Scots to have more control
over their own affairs, where Scots in recent years have persisted in giving
the majority of their votes to any party but the one which sits in authority
over them, has acted as a catalyst for political creativity. People have sat
down and thought about what should be done; they have gathered together,
written pamphlets, made speeches, and by their activity encouraged those who
disagree with them to do the same thing. It is good and healthy and although we
suffer in Scotland from what can only be called a democratic deficit in the way
we are governed, yet we have enjoyed a debate which has in itself been
liberating.
It has not all been stimulating stuff, of course. Those who argue in favour of
devolution have suffered occasionally from the wearing of rose-tinted glasses
while those who oppose have often lowered the debate by resorting to lurid
warnings of doom. Businessmen appear particularly confused, with a recent
survey for the Scottish Chambers of Commerce indicating a shift of opinion
towards acceptance of devolution, an opinion which appeared to be contradicted
by an agnostic senior representative of the CBI in Glasgow yesterday.
Nevertheless the effort has been worth while and it is now time, especially
with a maximum of 15 months or so before the next General Election, to absorb
what has happened and to take it forward.
In assessing the conflicting claims there is one constant, and that is the
importance of the Union for all Scots. Yet this concept needs to be defined if
it is to be understood. We live in a united state which is called the United
Kingdom, but it is not a unitary state as the Union represents a shared
sovereignty involving the preservation of separate nationhood. That is a fact -
even though it is persistently ignored by the Prime Minister, whose reading is
dyslexic in the extreme and who continues to represent Scotland as a subsidiary
part of a unitary nation. Devolution, Mr Major believes, is a threat to the
Union. As unionists we would argue that it is his understanding of the nature
of the Union and the policies which flow from it which present oportunities to
anti-unionists and which are most likely to endanger the Union. The Secretary
of State for Scotland, Mr Michael Forsyth, has seen that this approach is
insufficient. With some subtlety he has set about concocting a response to
those who argue for devolution. At a gut level his target is clearly the
revenue-raising capabilities of the proposed Scottish parliament, what he is
pleased to call the ``Tartan Tax''.
In his speech yesterday he raised the terrible prospect of jobs being lost and
Scots forced to pay dearly to live at home through the imposition of the
Scottish parliament's proposed 3p revenue-raising powers. This is lively
politics, but suspect in many respects. We already know from the work of
Strathclyde University's Professor Neil Hood that devolution, with all that it
entails, would have no effect on the willingness of foreign companies to invest
in Scotland. There is evidence from some economists, presented today in this
newspaper, that the ``Tartan Tax'' would not deter the growth of domestic
investment in Scotland but would, instead, have the useful effect of dampening
the harmful fluctuations in the business cycle.
Mr Forsyth's idea of devolution is to make great play of involving the Scottish
Grand Committee in what will in fact be toothless play-acting, and apparently
to give more powers to local councils in matters such as responsibility for
some trunk roads and over settling their capital spending priorities. It is a
mystery how this squares with his determination to retain powers to cap local
authority spending and to force councils into joint ventures through the
controversial Private Finance Initiative. Mr Forsyth clearly has difficulties.
To move too far towards genuine devolution would oblige him to accept some of
the arguments of his opponents, and this he will not do. His proposals are weak
and disappointing and fail utterly to meet people's expectations.
If you believe the Union to be of great importance to Scots the arguments of Mr
Salmond fall, even although they are presented with considerable style and
insight. The SNP's support waxes and wanes, upwards with Braveheart and
downwards as the emotions cool, but it represents an adventure which a majority
of Scots will not contemplate, including many of those who voted for Ms
Cunningham in Perth and Kinross this year.
There has been a hardening of opinion over the years in Scotland in favour of
constitutional change. If such change is needed, and it is, the most acceptable
means of achieving it lies in the work of the Scottish Constitutional
Convention. We have already welcomed devolution in principle, arguing that it
will allow the development of Scottish skills and talents which are at present
stifled or lost to other countries. The programme which has been brought
forward by the convention is democratic, balanced, and creative. There are many
details which must still be worked out and even more arguments to win. Yet it
is clear that in this great debate an important step forward has been taken.
The requirement now is for more debate, more detail, and an understanding that
the status quo, or even peripheral tinkering with it, is simply not good
enough. Scotland needs a new political dispensation and the way ahead is clear.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Desire under the Elms,Tricycle, London</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Carole Woddis</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975110215</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
INCEST and infanticide, greed and lust, there is certainly something raw and
elemental about Eugene O'Neill's Desire Under the Elms - the play that in 1924
America stirred up so much animosity it was banned from being performed in
Boston and other American cities.
Set against the background of a harsh, unremitting landscape and the constant
invocation of an inflexible, demanding Old Testament God, O'Neill's reworked
Greek tragedy could be too much.
Polly Teale's magnetic Shared Experience production, however, finds both the
passion and poetry of O'Neill's tortured tale, paradoxically by underlining the
melodrama and bringing home its Irishness. Teale herself has spoken of
transplanting O'Neill's 1850s American Mid-West to Ireland in the 1950s in
order to create a Beckettian world of universal longings.
In Neil Warmington's elegantly simple but also erotic and spiritually symbolic
shack, Teale's production, however, also seems a portrait of how the West was
won and forged by the toil and labour of hordes of Irish immigrant farmers and
their families. Even more, she brings to light the price paid by women in a
man's world.
This performance paints a picture of the life-force at its most terrifying and
crushing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
