<DOCNO>GH951201-000070</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000070</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Heart of the matter</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Phil Penfold</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975110216</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Phil Penfold meets Kerry Fox, star of a new film which reveals a tragic wartime
love affair
THIS month, television viewers are going to see a lot of actress Kerry Fox. In
a couple of weeks she stars in Saigon Baby, an emotionally charged story of
baby-buying in South-East Asia.
Before that, however, she stars in this Sunday's powerful wartime romance The
Affair - a film which opened her eyes to a little known, some might say hidden,
agenda of atrocities far away from the front-line of battle, but in a sleepy
English village during the Second World War.
``The film's first and foremost a love story,'' stresses New Zealand born Fox,
of Shallow Grave and A Village Affair fame. ``But it's also inspired by a
real-life case, where a black American GI was charged with raping an English
woman, and later hanged for it.''
The 105-minute drama - it's the biggest ever co-production between BBC TV and
American company HBO Showcase - tells the story of a passionate love affair
between a young, married Englishwoman, Maggie Leyland (Fox), and a black GI
Travis Holloway (Courtney B Vance). When her husband, Edward (Ciaran Hinds),
unexpectedly returns from active service and discovers them together, she is
torn between love and familial duty, and is forced to make a decision which has
devastating consequences, and which haunts her for the rest of her life.
Before filming the drama, Fox spoke to several women who lived through the war
and witnessed affairs between friends and visiting American soldiers. She also
watched a documentary containing interviews with eight woman, now in their
mid-to-late 70s, who had suffered great tragedy and trauma through love and
unrequited passions, and were only now able to speak frankly about their
feelings.
``For so many women whose husbands had gone off to war, it was an unusual
time,'' says Fox.``It was a time of vulnerability, but also great freedom.
While they were suffering much pain through the absence of partners, they
suddenly found their emotions being challenged. Having had no individuality for
years, they had no ability to express themselves properly, and often they had
no control over the situation.''
Looking elegant in a black silk trouser suit, Fox takes a sip of wine and says:
``I listened to women who endured separations and terrible tragedies - and like
Maggie bore their crosses silently. That made me have so much confidence in
this screenplay.''
But taking on the part of Maggie Leyland was a major surprise to Fox herself,
as she came to the production of The Affair at a time when she was convinced
she would not be doing any work.
``I was still in the Phillipines where I had just finished filming Saigon
Baby,'' she recalls. ``That had been a killer of a job - physically and
mentally - and I was at my hotel packing for a much-needed holiday in
Australia, when I received a 100 page fax from producer David Thompson in
London.
``David said at the top of it, `Don't go to Australia, you've got to come back
to the UK for this.' So I read the screenplay at 4.00am. Shooting for the film
was to start in six weeks' time. I knew there and then I had to do it.''
So Fox changed all her plans, and two days later - jet-lagged after an 18-hour
flight from Manila - she was in London auditioning for the part of Maggie. At
first, Fox readily admits, the attractions of doing The Affair were superficial.
``After Saigon Baby, I thought The Affair was a breeze - and in certain
respects, it was,'' says Fox. ``Filming in Norfolk, and going back to my flat
in London every night, was a lot safer and cosier than filming in the middle of
the Philippines, where we were walking among human waste and dead dogs.
``I was freer to indulge my emotions, and besides, we had huge American
trailers on set, and dependable BBC catering for lunch!
``But then, the more I got into Maggie's dilemma, the more it became a hugely
emotional challenge. It's beyond me to think how I'd have dealt with being a
woman in wartime with her husband away. How would I cope without knowing if I'd
ever see him again? I'd find that impossible enough.
``But then to find myself becoming involved with another man, knowing it was
wrong. To be that vulnerable - and then to have to lie about him when she faces
the very real threat of losing her son. The terrible tragedy for Maggie is that
had she told the truth from the start, she could have saved Travis's life.''
Producer David Thompson had long wanted to make a film about black servicemen
because their presence in Britain is a little-known aspect of the Second World
War. He pursued his interest in the subject after reading article about 19
American soldiers executed during the war at Shepton Mallet prison in Somerset.
``It seemed an extraordinary, incongruous state of affairs. How could these men
have been hanged in the middle of the sleepy English countryside?
Of the 19 GIs hanged at Shepton Mallet, 12 were black. ``This is an
extraordinary statistic considering that black prisoners made up only 10% of
the entire American military here,'' says Thompson. ``Apparently, there were no
white soldiers executed on the sole charge of rape, only black GIs.''
n.The Affair is on BBC1 this Sunday at 9.05pm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
