<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975110217</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
In his usual anti-Catholic diatribe, Faithful daughter of Mother Church
(November 28), John Macleod yet again demonstrates his total allergy to the
truth.
At the time of the setting-up of the Irish Free State in 1922 the proportion of
the population in the 26 Counties who were not Roman Catholics was 5%, and not
the 10% attested to by John Macleod.
There is no doubt that this figure has fallen, but equally there is no doubt
that it has not fallen as a result of ``hundreds of Protestants bombed, burned
or frightened out of the Emerald Isle''.
After the implementation of the 1921 Treaty and the 1920 Government of Ireland
Act, with the creation of separate Governments in Belfast and Dublin, the only
pogroms to occur happened in the North.
Sectarian riots in the summer of 1920 claimed in excess of 80 lives in Belfast
and Derry. The cause of these clashes was the expulsion from their jobs in the
shipyards of Belfast of the Catholic workers by the Protestant workers, and the
oppression of the Catholic population by the police and Government.
J J Lee observes in his Ireland 1912-1985: Politics and Society that in the
first six months of 1922, 171 Catholics and 93 Protestants were killed, ``often
in the most revolting of circumstances''. He adds: ``On a per capita basis,
Protestants were scoring four kills to every one by Catholics''.
At this time there were available for the maintenance of law and order in the
North of Ireland a remarkable number of police officers by comparison to the
rest of the UK - one policeman to every two Catholic families. And they were
armed! That they did not prevent this slaughter was due to the fact that they
were taking part in it.
No similar reports, then or later, emanated from the Free State.
The explanation for the decrease in the percentage of Protestants resident in
the Republic of Ireland today is the long-term effect of the First World War on
the Anglo-Irish community.
John Macleod also writes: ``To this day, the elections of a Protestant on the
Dail is a novelty''. And so it may well be, but it is a possibility enshrined
in the Constitution to protect the rights of the small Protestant population of
the 26 Counties. This is still the case today. Unlike in the North.
In the North, PR was abolished by James Craig in 1929. This removed the last
vestige of democracy in those Six Counties. It was now a wholly gerrymandered
State.
John Macleod refers to Article 44 of the 1937 Constitution which recognised the
``special position'' of the Catholic Church. This is no great surprise in view
of the attempts of English and later British Governments to exterminate the
Catholic Church and its followers from Ireland. An attempted genocide that
spanned many centuries and many kings, queens and governments.
Article 44 also recognised the rights of the other Churches in Ireland. It is
of great credit to Eamon de Valera that he specifically included in this
recognition ``the Jewish congregations'' at a time when the Jewish people in
other parts of Europe were already being herded into concentration camps.
If John Macleod takes exception to a Roman Catholic bishop reminding his Irish
flock that, irrespective of any change to the Constitution of the Republic of
Ireland, in the eyes of the Church you cannot obtain a civil divorce and
continue to receive the Sacraments if you should subsequently remarry, then he
should also inform the Archbishop of Canterbury of his displeasure. After all
that Protestant prelate preaches to the same tune.
Hugh McLoughlin,
24 Russell Street,
Mossend, Bellshill.
</TEXT>
