<DOCNO>GH951201-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chilling out with the music of love</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>David Belcher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975110218</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
All over the country, David Belcher learns,
easy-listening fans are coming out of their wardrobe units and into the Boudoir
THEY call 'em tunes, today's kids do, but melodious is what most modern records
aren't, isn't it? If it's not yon horrid techno blare, it's your blarting punky
post-post-grunge racket. Young 'uns . . . cuh! If you ask me - and no-one did -
this new generation will end up deafened, daft, and unable to engage in any
form of social intercourse whatsoever.
Yet maybe things aren't entirely bleak. Because some wised-up, now-a-go-go
kiddies are skipping along the mellow path of enlightenment to
Easylisteningville, the place so uncool it's red hot, grand-daddio.
How to define easy listening? Edinburgh groove-maestro Pete Baikie should know.
As well as providing Channel 4's Absolutely with musical interludes, he's
responsible for the easy-listening theme tune to Vic Reeves and Bob Mortimer's
Shooting Stars on BBC.
According to Pete, easy listening is ``the aural equivalent of Peter Wyngarde's
visual appearance in TV's Department S: velvety and dapper. Easy listening is
brassy trumpets and a reverberant Farfisa organ. Most crucially, it's dance
music for folk who are unashamed to confess that they can't dance - and they
aren't going to take any pills which will delude them that they can.''
In Glasgow, Boudoir is a Tuesday-night mecca for easy listening buffs. Located
in the 13th Note's basement, Boudoir this month celebrates its third
anniversary. Its founder, the mysterious Doctor Paul, hymns easy listening's
night-time lure.
``You can't have conversations in other clubs, which I regard as a grave
insult: `Here's some loud music - we assume you do not wish to talk.' Boudoir
is about love, and love means people speaking to one another.'' As well as
playing Ker-Plunk, Operation, and 3-D Connect Four with each other, staple
Boudoir pastimes all.
Doctor Paul is dismissive of the current wave of new easy-listening CD
compilations and re-issues, stressing the role of charity shops. He scoffs at
A&amp;M's re-release of greatest-hits albums like Guantanamera by the Sandpipers
and Burt Bacharach's orchestral epic Reach Out. ``CDs are a complete rip-off!
Why pay #15 for one album when you can go to a charity shop and get loads of
beautiful vinyl for the same price. Hundreds of LPs at 60p each.''
For how much longer, though. Charity shops in Glasgow studentland are running
low on stocks of Ray Conniff albums. It's harder to find 75p bargains such as
Action Replay: BBC Sporting Themes, including Pot Black, or the insomnia-curing
Kaleidoscopic Vibrations of the Moog by Perrey and Kingsley, both of which are
among Doctor Paul's most memorable finds.
So take the Doctor's prescription: check out Largs and Perth. ``Largs is full
of old Mike Sammes-lovers who keep dying, while in Perth, no-one's cool enough
to buy James Last In Russia.''
James Last? James pigging Last? I can't be doing with James Last . . . he
noodles other people's songs to death.
``Not if you get to his versions first. James Last's really funky. Listen to
his interpretation of the 2001 Theme and you'll learn that the beauty of easy
listening is cover versions that are slightly twisted.''
Ach, awa' wi' James Last. Bring me top Glasgow rhumba-pumpers the Johnny 7
instead. I meet two of the quartet in their city-centre penthouse pad,
liberally furnished with sixties-era lava lamps. Jason Famous and Dickey Molenz
are indisposed, so it's Pat M'Bongo and Rick Flick who view me over their
suspiciously effulgent moustaches.
It transpires that Boudoir was where the band were re-born, their 40-year
career having taken a dip after the highlight of appearing at the Montrose
Festival with Jimi Henderson.
Now, however, the band feel the emergent easy-listening scene is in imminent
danger of mainstream dilution by trendy London bandwagon-jumpers. They
pooh-pooh Radio 1 joss-dickey Chris Evans for his enthusiastic championing of
Mike Flowers's Pops de-fanged version of Oasis's Wonderwall. ``All these
listeners that Radio 1's lost? They're going to Radio 2, it's obvious,'' sneers
Pat.
``There are two bitterly opposed easy-listening camps these days,'' continues
Rick. ``There's hardcore: Engelbert, Bassey, O'Connor. And there's softcore -
Abba, Neil Diamond - for folk who think it's all a joke, a laugh . . . Well,
that's cheesy listening in our book - not proper easy listening.''
So it's not a joke?
``No. And you'll find all Glasgow's coolest indie bands down the front at our
live gigs. Urusei Yatsura, AC Acoustics, the Pastels, Bis, Pink Kross, One
Dove. Having got their teenage angst out with their loud, rowdy guitar music,
they come to us to chill out and experience the mood-music of love.''
Clued-in cats thus need feel no shame at openly embracing a music which has
hitherto been terminally unfashionable?
``With age comes musical wisdom,'' says Rick. ``There's nothing wrong in
admitting that you like Trini Lopez and Doris Day as well as Rangers Against
The Machinery, or whatever they're called. All over the country easy-listening
fans are coming out of their Formica-covered wardrobe units.''
Similarly, when the Johnny 7 work their magic on more contemporary numbers such
as Blur's Girls And Boys or Nirvana's Smells Like Teen Spirit, the band don't
consider they are changing them. ``Rather, we are returning them to their
original form, easifissimo. Anything that liberates musical taste is good after
all. Because narrow-minded devotion to any one genre is bad. Apart, that is,
from a devotion to easy listening.''
This formula is certainly paying off for the Johnny 7. They'll be on STV's
Chartbite Christmas Special, with live Glasgow gigs scheduled for Glasgow
University Union's Dafter Friday on December 15; Cottiers, December 21, and the
city's official George Square Hogmanay bash.
They may also at long last fulfil a booking to support Bjorn Again at Glasgow
Royal Concert Hall on December 23. They were meant to last Christmas Eve, ``but
we stayed in to watch Never Say Never Again on the telly,'' says Pat.
``We'll definitely turn up this time,'' says Rick. ``Unless they screen You
Only Live Twice.''
Their most immediate engagement is an unusual gig in Habitat on Tuesday
evening. ``Our contract specifies 24% discount,'' says Pat, confessing to a
fancy for a nice coffee table. ``And a pot-rack for me,'' says Rick.
Pot? Surely, you don't mean . . .
Rick looks aghast. ``Drugs are out of fashion. The rack's for my pots. I like
to cook up a nice chicken fricassee.''
That's the practical tastiness of easy listening. Hear it, children. Before you
no longer can.
n Essential listening (even if it is on CD).
The Easy Project: 20 Loungecore Favourites, various (Sequel); The Sound Gallery
(EMI) and The Sound Spectrum (Castle), various.
Three current compilations variously offering top film and telly themes, among
them The Avengers, Catweazle, Budgie, Thank Your Lucky Stars, and Get Carter,
as well as the Milk Tray ad. Step this way for rampant drums; sickly organ, and
inappropriate trumpets. Above all, there are no words to get in the way of the
easy listening message, and that message is: Frug your Eezee-Wosh hipsters on
my brown shag-pile till we combust, baby!
</TEXT>
