<DOCNO>GH951201-000073</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000073</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Parents place their faith in our education tradition</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Brian Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975110219</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WAS deprived of a first-hand look at the faces of Tory MPs as the Chancellor
of the Exchequer sat down at the end of his Budget speech, but by all accounts
they were a picture to savour.
Any Tory Chancellor who can provoke headlines like ``A penny for your votes''
from the Daily Telegraph and ``Where's the magic?'' from the Daily Mail,
alongside a cartoon of a very large hat and a very small rabbit, has my vote.
The truth is that the Tories are now so constrained by borrowing (in spite of
the family silver and North Sea oil) and low tax yields having de-skilled and
short-timed half the British workforce, there is little room for manoeuvre
without the financial markets going into tailspin.
Anyway, enough of the Budget. I wasn't even there, though that is not always a
barrier to the reporting of events. By the time Mr Clarke stood up I was en
route for an altogether happier occasion in my constituency.
The scene was Gateside village hall, with a portrait of our greatest
egalitarian, Robert Burns, hanging over the entrance. Seldom had this
well-balanced and distinctive community been on the receiving end of so much
political and media attention.
It arose from the fact that a petition had been organised, calling for a ballot
to decide whether or not Gateside Primary School, with its 62 pupils, should
become only the third in Scotland to opt out of the local-government system and
become ``self-governing''.
I admit this initiative, when it first surfaced, took me by surprise. The more
I spoke to and received letters from local people, the clearer it became that
it had been no more premeditated by them - including some who belatedly
discovered the significance of what they had signed.
For the past month I had been saying to all who asked that I was happy to leave
the outcome to the good sense of my constituents, the parents, who would
benefit from the minimum of outside interference. Seldom has such faith been so
richly rewarded.
The meeting was quite splendid and concluded with the school board being
authorised to seek legal advice on the signing of the petition and whether the
parents could have their signatures back.
For good measure, I was mandated to ask Michael Forsyth to call the whole thing
off now rather than allow it to drag on for another two months pending a
ballot, under the auspices of the Electoral Reform Society, which no more than
two or three seemed to want.
It would be idle to deny I enjoyed the occasion politically. The icing on the
cake was an ill-judged contribution in support of opting out from Forsyth's
long-serving sidekick, one Alan Hogarth, who announced himself as representing
the Cunninghame North Conservative Association. I am much obliged, Mr Hogarth.
But the success of the occasion lay in the triumphs of something much less
transient than party politics. In word and deed the meeting turned into a
testimony to the intrinsic worth of the Scottish education tradition, of which
I have never been more proud to be a product.
The spokesman for the school board, Alistair Wilson, told the meeting that the
more he knew about opting out the more he recognised it as not just nonsense
but dangerous nonsense, completely alien to the Scottish tradition of the local
school as part of the community. It was a fine articulation of what virtually
everyone in that hall felt in their bones.
People were angry that their own names had been taken in vain and that the name
of their village had been dragged through divisive publicity in a cause which
they wanted nothing to do with. The head teacher called for an early end to
uncertainty which was affecting the children's education.
Almost all those who spoke with such strength and confidence were clearly
products of the education system which a few individuals, usually from outside
it, commit so much zeal and deviousness to undermining. And once again they
have failed.
By Wednesday I was back in Westminster listening to the same Michael Forsyth,
with his latest wheeze for restoring Tory fortunes. The Scottish Grand
Committee, it seems, is to be turned into a perpetually travelling circus in
which the Deer Amendment (Scotland) Bill can be debated at leisure.
Watching this hunched and furtive little figure, as he read out this hastily
cobbled together nonsense, I tried again to work out what makes him tick.
Apart from sheer prejudice it is, I think, a dehumanised conviction that
politics is all about illusion, about fixing, about putting one over on your
opponents. People are meant to say: ``Isn't he smart'' as the highest form of
tribute.
But that is not what they say at all. Rather, they are reinforcing the view
that government by an unrepresentative and extremist clique, as represented by
Mr Forsyth, has gone on for far too long. And that takes me right back to the
reaction of decent people in Gateside village hall.
Same malign architect. Same public response. Three cheers for the Scottish
educational tradition.
</TEXT>
