<HEADLINE>Royal SNO, Glasgow Royal concert Hall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Tumelty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975110220</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHAT an odd ragbag of pieces last night from the Royal Scottish National
Orchestra: a bit of pleasant juvenilia, a rarity, and an unusual view of a
masterpiece. All fascinating to hear, though not amounting to much.
Russian conductors seem to have a thing about Elgar, and I recall Alexander
Lazarev, when he was appointed principal guest conductor of the RSNO, muttering
about wanting to do the olde English gent. It would be interesting to hear
Lazarev conducting something meaty (the symphonies), but last night we had to
make do with the attractive, eclectic, and rather vegetarian collection of
pieces that comprise the second Wand of Youth Suite.
Things picked up with pianist Murray McLachlan as soloist in Dohnanyi's
brilliant Variations on a Nursery Song, which take Twinkle Twinkle Little Star
on a stellar trip through a galaxy of musical styles. Wittily played, if a
little underpowered by the pianist, this was one of those performances which
suggested that Alexander Lazarev, though he can seem dour, has in fact a droll
sense of humour.
Outstanding performance of the night, however, was Stravinsky's Petrushka, with
Lazarev appearing to dump the usual panache of the piece, concentrating instead
on textures that were so clear, raw, garish, and lurid that you could see right
through them; an often gripping performance.
</TEXT>
