<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Release of the spirit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jean West</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975110221</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
As Scottish prisons groan with overcrowding, JEAN WEST asks: do we really need
so many scapegoats?
THIS week two seasoned prison officers broke down and wept at the fatal
accident inquiry of a tragic young charge. The lifeless corpse of teenager
Arlene Elliot was found hanging in her cell at Cornton Vale prison just outside
Stirling in the summer. She was the latest young casualty of a draconian penal
system hellbent on revenge and still intent on showing society who is boss.
The 17-year-old from Partick, Glasgow, had admitted shoplifting offences and
was awaiting reports while on remand.
Three days earlier another girl, Kelly Holland, at 17 again barely out of her
childhood, took her desperate suicidal thoughts to their awful conclusion. The
youngster, on remand at the same prison for breach of the peace, had a history
of similar charges. She left her devastated parents, Edward and Isobel, a
letter begging forgiveness. After soul-searching for reasons for letting them
down, she still could not say what drove her to offend repeatedly. Two wasted
young lives. Two trivial charges.
The Howard League for Penal Reform have said they consider it verging on the
barbaric to keep jailing young girls. But alternatives to custodial sentences
do exist as an innovative project in Greenock aims to show this week. At the
town's Arts Guild, young offenders from the Inverclyde intensive probation unit
will make their stage debut with a labour of love far removed from criminal
activity. The scheme is part of an enlightened effort to keep 16 to
21-year-olds away from the ``universities of crime''.
A new play Greenock Central, sponsored by National Children's Homes and
directed by Cat A Theatre Company, gives 14 young offenders the opportunity to
look at their lives and express feelings about the situations while
contributing something positive to the community.
Unit leader Paul Carberry said: ``We offer different programmes to help young
people deal with their behaviour and wean them away from crime as a direct
alternative to custody.''
He added: ``At the unit we have mutual respect for each other. There is
dialogue and we try to reach a common understanding. From that comes change.''
There are many reasons - social, economic, psychological, some even say
physiological - why people turn to crime. Carberry's wards are encouraged
through creativity and positive peer influences to examine their individual
problems and look at ways to break free.
``The majority of young people here are second-generation unemployed,'' added
Carberry.
George McIvor, 21, had just completed an intensive probation order. When he
punched his pal unconscious during a brawl he braced himself for jail. Already
pulled up by the police for taking prescribed drugs and selling stolen goods,
he expected months if not longer inside. Ironically, referral to the Inverclyde
project put him side by side with the youth - once more a mate - he knocked out
after a night on the town. George got through the unit and found himself a job.
So, was it a better option than doing time?
``Well, I've not been jailed yet,'' said George who stars in the play.
``The unit has changed me a lot. I look at things differently now. Before I
would do anything to feed a drug habit, now I know it's not worth it.
``The play has been a great ego boost. I had never acted at all before but I
look forward to going on stage. My friends and family are coming to see it.''
Greenock Central is both comic and tragic. The natural wit of many of these
youngsters has been tapped effectively by Cat A playwright John Maley. This is
punctuated by a sadness that comes from human disasters all too familiar in
their short lives.
George told the story of the death of his friend: ``Last October a pal who had
stayed with us and was like a brother died from an overdose. It had a really
deep effect on me. I've seen it happen too often.''
Cat A administrator Annie George said: ``The play looks at the real lives of
these young people. It looks at petty crime, drug abuse, drinking, and
gambling, and at their wistful dreams of escape.''
Irvine Allan, who directed the piece, has long been attacking a system in
Britain which incarcerates more young people than anywhere else in Europe apart
from Turkey and by the end of last year had more than 12,400 on remand.
He said: ``A lot of the young people in Greenock Central are written off as
unworkable, uneducatable, untouchable if you like. But it's not the case. The
performance helps give them a sense of value.
``Short, sharp, shock, military discipline, boot camp-type solutions don't
work. The need for revenge prevails. We are still looking to marginalise and
demonise these young people because of our own fear and misunderstanding.''
He added: ``It's a learning process both for us and for them. And it is a
positive thing to see people learning to create rather than destroy.''
A cautious community in Greenock are beginning to warm to the youngsters. Some
members have become involved.
Jean Robertson said: ``My attitudes have been completely changed. I thought
that people who took drugs and drink were hobos. But the boys and girls here
are not like that. They would be the first to help you if you have a problem.''
Perhaps Michael Howard could take a leaf from her book.
n Greenock Central runs at the Greenock Arts Guild until Saturday, December 2.
Guests on Saturday night are Greenock band Whiteout.
</TEXT>
