<DOCID>GH951201-000076</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Tin  Soldier, Coupar Institute, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mary Brennan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975110222</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONCE upon a time, fairy stories were how wee weans learned about the many faces
of good and evil. This was long before plastic surgery and plastic money meant
folk could be two-faced on the never-never. Fairy stories - especially the ones
by Hans Christian Andersen - acknowledged cruelty in a far more profound way
than any splat-blat cartoon, and the endings often suggested that happiness
could come in unexpected ways.
The Tin Solder - adapted and directed by Chris Craig for Wildcat - understands
the power of this. Celebrates it in a production which believes that even young
children - I watched it with mainly under-eights - can engage with quite
complex issues of bleakness, joy, integrity, and courage.
Enter the figure of Andersen - Hans Christian played by an engagingly avuncular
David Anderson - who guides the narrative, and makes the words work as if they
were magic spells. As he thinks them out loud, or writes them down, they bring
alive the pretty, quirling Ballerina (Veronica Leer) and her stalwart, smitten
Tin Soldier (Sandy Nelson) whose happiness and love is envied and apparently
destroyed by the fiery Goblin - a marvellously growly prowly creature (Lesley
Robertson), who is literally heartless.
Craig has stayed commendably close to the story, right to the bitter sweet end
when the innocents are engulfed by flames but their true hearts remain melted
together for ever.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000077</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000077</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Offensive tone</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975110223</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I TAKE issue with the offensive tone of John Macleod's article on the Irish
divorce referendum (November 28). Surely the Catholic Church is to be applauded
for attempting to stabilise and promote Christian family values.
John Macleod's negative attitude is in evidence with the short sharp statement
that abortion is outlawed in the constitution but failing to take the
opportunity to commend the Catholic Church for her stance in this issue, as I
was under the impression that he shares the same view. Regarding his aside on
infallibility, he fails to grasp the real meaning behind this emotive term in
that it is the Church's duty under the stewardship of the presiding Pope to
ensure the Gospel truths and all that emanates from them are upheld and
protected throughout the ages.
There has been an ongoing evangelisation within ``Mother church'' for some
considerable time, thus I trust allaying his concern for Latin American
Catholics departing for pastures new. We too adhere to Scripture and can, and
do, spread the Good News without restriction. Many of his articles in recent
times have tackled the Catholic church on several issues. We are sufficiently
broad-shouldered to take the criticism. However, it is of great sadness that
when producing his critique John Macleod does not reflect on St Paul's words
contained in I Corinthians, Chapter 13; then his writings could take on the
spirit of charity and his opinions would have wider credibility.
Thomas Finnigan,
18 Teesdale,
Stewartfield, East Kilbride.
</TEXT>
