<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000078</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000078</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wrong Challenge</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975110224</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IARTHUR Scargill has presented an important challenge to progressive elements
in the Labour and trade-union movement. It would determine the shape of future
social and trade-union rights under the next Labour Government. Nevertheless,
this challenge is misplaced.
A breakaway party of socialists now would be incomprehensible to ordinary
working people and trade unionists. They wish above all to see an end to
Conservative rule.
To embark upon a breakaway would make it even easier for Tony Blair to sever
the remaining links between the Labour Party and the trade unions. It would
make it harder to advance arguments to reinstate necessary legal safeguards on
legitimate trade union activities.
A Labour Government will most likely be faced with severe economic difficulties
as the longer-term structural weaknesses of the UK economy become manifest.
Tony Blair might well, as Harold Wilson did twice, be tempted to declare states
of national emergency.
A crisis of sufficient magnitude could even lead the Labour Party into a
Government of National Unity. This too is a scenario with a strong historical
precedent.
To remove the left from the Labour Party at this crucial juncture would be to
prevent a consequential more wide-ranging realignment of Labour policies in the
future.
Charles Woolfson,
31 Chancellor Street,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000079</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000079</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sad farewell to driving force of flower power</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Tom Shields</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>diary</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975110225</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STUART HENRY, the Scottish disc jockey who died last week, took his
unconformist ways with him - if not to the grave then certainly on the road to
it.
Stuart was Scotland's most prominent member of the flower-power generation. He
was the focus of those get-togethers in the botanic gardens which made
Glasgow's West End seem just like San Francisco's Haight Ashbury. (Well, the
kaftans were similar.)
His successful career took him from Radio Scotland (the floating one, off
Dunbar) to the big-time on Radio 1 and then to Radio Luxembourg. He suffered
from multiple scleroris for the last 20 of his 53 years.
And so to the story of his last journey. The crematorium in Luxembourg, where
he lived, being unavailable, Stuart's family and friends had to take his body
across the border to Belgium.
Despite the European Union's philosophy of no frontiers, the Belgian border
police refused to let the cortege through. Only after long argument was the
funeral party allowed to go about its sad business.
One of the reasons for the Belgian polis being suspicious was the garb of the
funeral director. He was wearing denims instead of the traditonal dark suit.
Cronies conned
THE chairman of the Largs Cronies Burns Club St Andrew's dinner introduced the
main speaker for the night - his cousin Sybil from Australia. Cousin Sybil
walked in wearing a blonde wig and dark glasses which she whipped off to reveal
herself as none other than Kirsty Wark, TV journalist par excellence and old
girl of Wellington Academy, the Ayrshire finishing school.
Ms Wark then took off her dress. For those who may have allowed Ms Wark's
comeliness to intrude into their thoughts as she conducts serious interviews on
Newsnight, it should be pointed out that she was wearing another dress
underneath.
Here's to new
technology
ALEX Salmond of the SNP addressed the St Andrew's dinner of the Scottish
European Association in Brussels. The programme for the proceedings was
translated into the other European languages for the benefit of guests from
other nations. A new bit of European Union hi-tech computer software was used
which gives instant translations. Mr Salmond's ``toast to Scotland'' appeared
as ``petit pain grille a L'Ecosse''.
Posthaste
ONE of the first bits of mail to hit our desk in the wake of the postal strike
was a Christmas card. Nice and early, we thought.
But what gives a certain piquancy to its smart delivery by the now returned
postal service is that it was sent, even before all 12 million items in the
backlog of strike-bound mail have been sorted and dispatched, by no less a
communicator that Peter Howarth CBE, managing director of the Royal Mail.
Mr Howarth's greeting shows a fluffy robin red breast jamming up the slot of a
letter box . . . appropriate enough in the light of recent postal chaos. But
what may exercise the letter-writing classes even more - to say nothing of
those still waiting for cheques, pin numbers, and football tickets turned
ephemera - is that Mr Howarth states, alongside a tariff of his organisation's
charges: ``We all like to receive our Christmas cards early''. . . no mention
of letters that were posted a fortnight ago and have not yet arrived.
Urging speedy action on the Christmas-card front Mr Howarth continues: ``At
this time of year we deliver up to double the normal amount of post.'' This
year we all know why.
Fitting climax
WE whetted your appetite earlier this week, perhaps, with some book excerpts
which failed to win the Literary Review magazine's annual Bad Sex Prize. It was
all sweaty armpits, meaty thighs, and quivering flesh.
To qualify for the Bad Sex Prize, the passage should be ``redundant,
perfunctory, unconvincing, and embarrassing as well as unacceptably crude''.
And the winner this year is from Philip Kerr's Gridiron published by Chatto &amp;
Windus with:
His tremulous thumbs gathered the elastic waist of her panties and plucked them
down over the twin golden domes of her behind and back up over the suspended
sentences and Sobranie filter-tips of her stocking tops as, obligingly, she
brought her knees up to her chest. She straightened her feet and the little
stealth bomber of black lace and silk was his.
Quickly he threw off his own clothes and rolled on top of her. Detaching mind
from over-eager gnomon and its exquisitely appointed, shadowy task, he made
love to her.
The Literary Review judges were particularly impressed by ``the suspended
sentences and Sobranie filter-tips of her stocking tops''. A gnomon, if you
didn't already know, is the sticky-up bit of a sundial.
Philip Kerr, the writer, should worry at this mocking of his prose. His book is
going into paperback and the film rights have been sold for a million dollars.
Wise up
OUR festive competition requires you dear readers to nominate a fourth Wise
Person to visit the stable in Bethlehem bearing an appropriate gift.
The first award goes to Ken Cawley of Coatbridge who was quick on the fax with
the following nominations:
Robert Maxwell, with a personal pension plan for the baby Jesus.
The leader of Monklands District Council with a pink job application (should
He ever need a job).
Duncan Ferguson, offering a kiss - a Glasgow kiss. Gazza might also be there,
elbowing the other Wise Men out of the way to get a better look.
Entries accepted by letter, fax, e-mail, or racing pigeon to the usual
destinations
</TEXT>
