<HEADLINE>Scotlean Pigs lifts turnover</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<FLAG>farming digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975110226</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Scotlean Pigs, the Carlisle-based co-operative pig marketing group, has ended
its trading year with a turnover in excess of #41m.
Chairman James Wylie said that membership had increased by almost 25% and now
stood at 137. Pig sales increased to 13,000 a week.
With the addition of another member of staff Scotlean has begun to encourage
pig marketing co-operation in the West Midlands area.
Mr Wyllie forecast another year of growth but emphasised that member commitment
was the first ingredient in maintaining the co-op's strength and its standing
with abattoir operators.
Correction
THE winner of the Holstein Friesian junior cow section at this week's Dairy
Scot event was Alister H Laird of Blyth Farm, Blyth Bridge, West Linton. His
entry Altona Lea Broker Emma also took the junior cow inter-breed prize and won
the special class award for cows giving over 10,000kg. She was judged to have
the best udder in the Holstein Friesian section.
New phase
THE second phase of Aberdeen and Northern Marts new auction centre at Elgin
will be officialy opened next Wednesday.The new hall will be used for furniture
and antique sales and other specialist non-agricultural events.
Meat cuts
SLAUGHTER staff at Scotch Premier Meat's Edinburgh plant have agreed to
concentrate their working week into four days as part of a cost-cutting
exercise. The slaughtermen will continue to work the same number of hours and
the throughput of beef and lamb at the plant will not be affected. The benefit
to the company is a considerable saving in cleaning and washing-up costs and
the opportunity to carry out essential maintenance on a Friday. The plant's
boning and butchery departments will continue to work a five-day week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000081</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000081</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Time to cash in on spin-off from science</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Alf Young</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975110227</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHERE are the industries and jobs of tomorrow to come from? Easy question to
pose. Devilishly difficult one to answer with any ring of conviction.
We've grown blase about computers and their software, hole-in-the-wall-banking,
mobile phones, video stores, theme parks, and all the other trappings of
mid-1990s life. Many of today's can't-be-withouts didn't even exist in the
mid-1970s. So what, come 2020 say, is next?
Some money is on biotechnology. More seems to be on the burgeoning age of
information. A BBC poll for the Bookworm programme the other day revealed a
disturbingly high percentage of the sample convinced books and the printed word
had virtually had their day. Superseded by silicon, victim to the Internet and
the CD-ROM, the printed word is heading for smokestack status it seems. If that
poll is right much of the forestry industry is in for a profound shock and
people like me can start looking for another job.
Needless to say I think these doomsters are a bit wide of the mark. If the
bicycle can reinvent itself and survive the advent of mass car ownership, if
mail volumes continue to expand in line with the growth in fax traffic, I
suspect newspapers (and books) will be around long enough to see me out and a
bit beyond that.
That Bookworm poll had another intriguing finding. Significantly more of those
questioned would want to be marooned on a desert island with a scientific book
than with a volume of poetry.
We have a curiously ambivalent attitude to the sciences and the technologies
they spawn. At one level we caricature scientists, like inventors, as madcaps
in white coats, surrounded by bubbling test tubes, wreathed in electric
discharges. At a more sinister level, both nuclear and genetic engineering -
the fruits respectively of scientific inquiry into the fundamental particles of
matter and life - are widely perceived in the public mind as grave potential
threats to our planet and our humanity.
But we also, as the poll suggests, maintain a reflex belief that science can
still solve many of this world's problems. Science, not poetry, might get you
off that island the poll is saying. So, to return to my original question,
science and technology would surely feature high up most people's lists of
where tomorrow's industries and jobs will come from. Applied science has
already given us everything from the internal combustion engine to the memory
chip. Why should it stop there?
On Tuesday Scottish Enterprise released the first details of its year-long
inquiry, with the Royal Society of Edinburgh, into the commercialisation of
Scottish science.
The picture Scottish Enterprise paints is of Scotland's 13 universities alive
with fruitful scientific inquiry but singularly failing to convert enough of
what is discovered into spin-off companies and jobs here in Scotland.
The problem is not that Scottish science is unproductive. As the inquiry report
shows, Scottish universities have a disproportionately large share of UK
academic science. Around 15% of all the higher degrees for example. In terms of
publications per researcher ``Scotland ranks third in the world, producing 50%
more papers than the United States''.
It's not even that Scotland's scientists are all hostile to commercialising
their work. Some 53% of Scottish academic scientists are currently working
closely with industry compared with 34% of scientists in American universities.
And yet, research for the inquiry has identified only 60 surviving spin-outs
from Scottish university science over the past 15 years, employing in total
just 1500 people. In contrast, a single Swedish university, Chalmers in
Gothenburg, can list 200 spin-outs currently employing 2700 people. MIT in
Massachusetts has spawned countless businesses employing 200,000 people.
Clearly Scottish science has a long way to go to realise its full potential in
the wider economy. Scottish Enterprise chief executive Crawford Beveridge rates
this challenge even more important than persuading more Scots to become
entrepreneurial and launch start-up businesses. But past under-performance in
unlocking what Beveridge calls ``the massive store of intellectual property in
our universities'' has complex roots which will be hard to unravel.
The UK funding community is notoriously risk averse when faced with hi-tech
proposals. University rules and regulations and the burden of administration
under which many academics labour hinder the spin-off process. Academic culture
rates an individual's publication history much more highly than commercial
ambition. Too few indigenous Scottish companies are big enough or sophisticated
enough to exploit the science which is on offer. And get academics to see that
they might be the wrong person to take their science to market is another
hurdle.
But, if nothing is done to ease these constraints, Scottish scientific
discoveries will continue to be exploited by others. The main wealth generated
and the jobs created will, for the most part, pass Scotland by. The next stage
of the inquiry promises an action plan. We certainly need action.
In terms of tomorrow's industries and jobs Scotland's public strategy in recent
years has been to tout for as big a share as we can get of investment from
elsewhere and, more recently through the business birthrate initiative, to
reawaken in more Scots the instinct to start businesses of their own.
Bidding for inward investment has always carried a price. Such is the
competition that that price is getting bigger. And the kind of investment that
tends to come - at the assembly end of the production chain - is vulnerable in
the medium term. The birthrate strategy is about changing fundamental
attitudes. That, by definition, is a very long game. So Scotland's economy
desperately needs additional targets. Exploiting more of our academic science
in the commercial arena deserves top priority.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ketchup on floor in takeover scrap</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Julie Davidson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975110228</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF I held shares in Forte I'd be voting to take the weight off my feet. An epic
city contest between the Forte family business and the hostile raiders of
Granada, the telly-to-tagliatelle conglomerate, is drawing up its battlelines,
and as regards taking sides it comes down to this: are you a happy eater or a
fast feeder? Do you like table service at your roadside restaurants or are you
a connoisseur of queues - a confident practitioner of the slick skills required
by self-assembly meals?
Forte liberated the peripatetic family from self-service stress by bringing us
Little Chefs and Happy Eaters; Granada lets the customer take the strain with
wobbling trays and instant decision-making. I know who I'm rooting for.
The self-service restaurant is one of the nastiest innovations of the twentieth
century. Its reductionist approach to eating - its uncouth dismantling of the
social and cultural rituals of sitting down to a meal - has proliferated more
enthusiastically in Britain than anywhere else, which says everything there is
to say about our attitudes to eating out.
The self-service restaurant exists grudgingly in continental Europe - in the
French motorway chain of Jacques Borel, in the student howffs of the Latin
Quarter, in the McDonald franchises of Berlin and Rome - but it thrives and
prospers in Britain. And even where it is not synonymous with portion control
and packet ketchup it signifies haste, discomfort, and agitation.
Its influence has spread far beyond the works canteen, the motorway, and the
shopping mall. It has dismally exceeded its original function of quick, cheap
catering for the hurrying hungry. Cheeseparing city councils and mean-spirited
cultural institutions (who see no connection between art and eating) invite the
public to serve themselves with vegetarian lasagne and boxed Chardonnay.
Decent food prepared in spectacular settings gets degraded by the queue, the
tray, the tables which are never cleared fast enough, the customer's desperate
memory-search. Cutlery? Napkins? Butter? Seasonings? ``I'm sorry, I'm not
jumping the queue, I'm just trying to get a roll.'' It turns a peaceful meal
into a rowdy initiative test.
Is the saving on waiting staff wages reflected in the prices of the fare? Not
noticeably; the coffee served at table in the Patisserie Florentin,
Stockbridge, costs much the same as the coffee collected at the counter of the
handsome Patio Restaurant in Edinburgh's botanic gardens. Innocents abroad seat
themselves at its outside tables, dreamily admire the frieze of Edinburgh's
skyline, await service. By the time they notice the crocodile inside they've
lost their appetite.
Where was the self-service restaurant invented? America, probably, but even
America pursues the concept more cautiously than Britain. Outside the orbit of
Big Mac and its clones the ``all-day breakfast'' and other all-day victuals -
the uninterrupted provision of inexpensive, quickly prepared food - is supplied
by the diner, where men and women of legendary temperament serve table. It's my
impression that the American diner was the model for Forte's Little Chef chain,
later complemented by Happy Eaters.
You enter. You are approached, and usually welcomed. ``Smoking or
non-smoking?'' You sit. The menu is before you, with its junior version. You
reflect, you discuss, you order. One Chef's Special, one Healthy Option, one
cheeseburger and chips, three rounds of toast (``Brown bread or white?''), tea
for two, and a chocolate milk shake. Over the years, up and down the miles from
Inverness to Peterborough, a route map of the Little Chef menu has been etched
on my palate.
Hearty food for three, cooked before our eyes and pleasantly served. Cost,
about #15. Grrr, Gerry Robinson, chief executive of Granada, who has made the
amazing public statement that if he wins control of Forte he will reduce staff,
remove overheads, ``sweat the assets'', and raise prices. He has his sights on
the hotel group, the largest in the country, but his special interest in the
Happy Eaters and Little Chefs sounds sinister: ``The service at the sites is
bad in our view. The original concept still looks good but has not been kept up
to date. We would introduce fast food into these sites. We want commercial
relationships, such as Burger King, that give us a good return.''
Decoded, what does this mean? As one who is willing to bet she's had more hot
dinners at Little Chefs than Gerry Robinson, let me make an educated guess. In
the Granada school of restaurant criticism ``bad'' service is ``slow'' service,
as in table service; the kind of service which doesn't suit fast food, fast
turnover, and ``a good return''.
In fact, across the spectrum of Forte's interests, from its luxury hotels to
its roadside diners, Mr Robinson has found faults which lead me to only one
conclusion: Rocco Forte, who accepted control of the company from his
89-year-old father three years ago, has been serving the public too well. He
has been giving them value for money.
Now there's a novelty - a captain of a leading service industry whose
management has been serving customers more conscientiously than shareholders.
In the Granada chief's ledger, Forte has even been undercharging customers. If
Robinson gets his hands on the Posthouse hotel chain he plans to raise prices
by 20% to 25%.
Such cockiness. Besides its budget and middle-market hotel chains Forte owns
some of Europe's finest: the George V in Paris, the Ritz in Madrid, the Hotel
Eden in Rome, the Hyde Park in London. Granada's experience of managing hotels
runs to one themed enterprise and 20 motorway lodges.
Still, nothing much should surprise us in the service industries. A local
stooshie has broken out in Edinburgh, where some city centre pubs plan to
charge entrance fees of #10 on the key night of the city's five-day Hogmanay
holocaust. Any day now we expect Sainsbury's to instal turnstiles at its doors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000083</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000083</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No headline  present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jack McLean</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975110229</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DOUBTLESS this is a strange position to take upon the question of drinking and
driving. But then it is based on a strange position anyway. For a start I don't
drive, neither do my brothers nor other immediate family, and the first time I
took a driving lesson I killed a dug. It was a wee dug of low intellect but
entitled to life I suppose and I can think of a few humans whose termination
would have seemed more appropriate than this cur.
At least the wee furry thing died outright - I was sufficiently an apprentice
driver to execute the animal painlessly. A more experienced driver would have
run over the dug with perhaps less cavalier aplomb and the wee beast would have
taken hours to croak it. In my case I was a rotten motorist and splattered the
wee thing all over the roadway in seconds.
As it happens I am a sentimental man and gret something rotten, which is what
the driving instructor did too because he was going to have to spend an hour in
the police station reporting the untimely demise of a wire-haired mongrel with
weeping puppies in the background. Thus I have never bothered my arse about
driving lessons ever since. Seems to me that dugs are better aff without me
really, and nowadays I permit taxis to speed me from point to point without a
dug on my conscience at that.
Now this is nothing about mutts, except drivers. Once again this year we have
the campaign agin the drunk-drivers. We run it every year, all throughout
Britain. The chief constables love it; gives them a chance to turn up in
uniforms with silver tabs, just as if they were real sojers, and pontificate to
us all. Chief constables are flanked by flunkeys who speak in the sort of grave
tones which they don't seem to possess when they are out of their minds at
Christmas parties run for polis by the gendarmes.
D'ye see, the polis get to run in all thae drink drivers, thousands, well,
hundreds, well a few, at Christmas time in a way they can't run in the bastards
who break into cars, let alone houses, all the year round. Oh, awffy easy to
pick up a drunk driver and even easier to challenge three zillion perfectly
respectable chaps of a night and discover that about 2% of those they would
practically wish to detain under the Terrorism Act have had a libation
consisting of about two gins with a mixer.
As it happens, far from reducing the permitted roughly-a-pint, or one Bacardi
for ladies, I would increase it. Few, if any, motorists ever stop at just one
pint. Don't tell me about no drink at all: that is a licence to lose it. If we
stay by sensible limits what I would do is increase the limit, and those above
it I would bloody well jail. I would organise city barracks for those above the
three-pint level or whatever in which they would have to spend all the next 12
months inside, and not at home for weekends, liberty extracted and their
misdemeanors made shamingly public.
Scottish Television ran a list of names and addresses (it was wee Denis Mooney,
subsequently of Scottish Action, who thought it up too), and very effective it
was. For years we have been operating a useless on-off switch whereby anybody
with a wee notch above the permitted level got a year's ban and so did the scum
who shoved a bottle of methyl alcohol down their damned throats and knowingly.
But we are not talking sense about alcohol and driving or Christmas and New
Year: we are not talking sense at all. We are talking prohibition. The nation
has went daft over prohibition in recent years. Some call it the nanny state,
and certainly in the matter of other's pleasures it seems so. But the past
months or so have seen the manifestation of the glories of the prohibition
stance.
Did you ever imagine anybody could start putting us all aware of the evils of
tobacco and beer in the wake of a few teenagers dying from ecstasy at dances or
heroin in the streets and saying that lager and Silk Cut are just as bad for
you? Behave yourselves. I doubt if any teenager in four centuries has croaked
it through shoving a can of superlager down his or her throat. Fags surely kill
but it takes a million or so of them over many a year. But we are in the age of
senseless prohibition.
Parisian authorities recently proposed a bye-law which would mean you couldn't
smoke a Gauloises in a pavement cafe. Dublin seems to think they might manage
legislation banning fags in pubs. Algeriques in Paris are bombing the Metro and
Dublin girls are leaving their shores daily for abortions in England and we are
worrying about cigarettes? I was reading Richard Gordon's Doctor books not so
long ago. Dating from the early 1950s they were. Awash with beer and whisky and
gin and fags. And fun. And common bloody sense too.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Why Le Jog is no jaunt</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROSS FINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975110350</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MANY motor clubs organise their rallies with eye-catching or fairly silly
titles. Within the last few weeks, East Ayrshire Car Club has run the
Mullwharchar Rally, named after a prominent hill south of Loch Doon, and
Lanarkshire Car Club members have been out on the Sir Walter. But the prize for
the most ingenious name goes to Le Jog, which runs from tomorrow until Tuesday.
Brainchild of John Brown, a rally navigator, co-driver and organiser of long
experience, Le Jog is an expression of the event's geographical limits. ``LE''
is Land's End and ``JOG'' represents John o'Groats, because we are talking
really big mileage here.
Its full title is The Land's End to John o'Groats Reliability Trial and Touring
Trial.
That longer-winded name identifies it as being outwith the usual run of modern
motor-sport. In fact, after two previous events, it has become one of the most
popular, as well as one of the most authentic, competition runs for historic
and classic cars.
The entry list of more than 120 cars and crews - most taking part in the main
event, the others in the more relaxed touring section - goes back into the
realms of Lanchester, Alvis, Jowett and Lea-Francis from earlier decades, as
well as Ford Cortinas, Sunbeam Rapiers, Volvo PV544s and Austin-Healey 3000s
from before the cut-off date in the 1970s.
Over the past few years there has been an upsurge of interest in historic
rallies, which are run all over the UK and Europe. Part of the appeal is
undoubtedly getting rally cars of the past back into action, but there is also
an element of being able to enjoy genuine competition driving without going
overboard in cost.
There are two main types of historic rally. One involves high-speed
special-stage action on privately owned, often forest roads. Some events of
this type stand on their own, while others are historic sections of rallies run
mainly for modern cars.
Le Jog is the other kind. As events like the Monte Carlo used to do, it
features long road sections with shorter regularity stretches where a precise
average speed has to be maintained to avoid penalty - for early or late arrival
- as well as manoeuvring tests on private ground.
It may sound a pushover, but an event like this, which runs from breakfast time
on Saturday until much the same time on Tuesday with just one overnight stop,
is no dawdle.
And while the drivers have to try their utmost on the manoeuvring tests,
drivers and navigators concentrate intensely on the regularity sections.
Keeping up an average speed of, say, 29mph seems ridiculously easy until you
try it, in the dark, on a freezing or fog-bound winter night, on a maze of
lanes in mid-Wales or over some hill road in the Highlands, perhaps in an
elderly car with no heater, vintage lights, heavy steering and only a draughty
hood for shelter.
Especially when being six seconds early at a check point is an even more
agonising failure for the crew involved than being eight seconds late.
There is a remarkable spread of entries for this year's event. They come from
all over the UK as well as from Belgium, Holland, Denmark, Finland, Germany and
Switzerland. And what cars! A 1924 Lanchester six-litre Tourer, vintage
Bentleys, a Brough Superior, a chain-drive Frazer Nash Nurburg, a Talbot 75, a
pair of Lagonda LG45s, one of the rare Rover-based Marauder sports cars of the
1950s, an Aston Martin and a Ford Thunderbird, Mini Coopers, Jaguars, MGBs, a
Rochdale Olympic, a Lancia Fulvia and Augusta, Porsches, even a Rolls-Royce
Silver Wraith.
Scottish-based entrants, on home ground from Bonchester Bridge on Sunday to the
finish at John o'Groats on Tuesday, include Branislav Sudjic in a 1927 Type 44
Bugatti, Sue Shoosmith in a 1926 Bentley, Fred Multon in an Austin-Healey 100/4
and Laurenc e Grainger in a Volvo 122S.
Old rally hands reading through the entry list will appreciate, from the names
of some of the navigators, that many of these crews are not out to finish
second. There is no rubbish about doing it just for fun.
Willy Cave, Don Barrow, Colin Francis and others were co-driving aces when
these cars were new. Barrow, for instance, was with Timo Makinen in a works
Austin-Healey 3000 when they finished second in the 1964 RAC Rally. He is
navigating another Healey this weekend and, although the pace may be different,
he will be taking things just about as seriously on Le Jog.
All in all, it is no place for the faint-hearted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
