<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bank takeover talk persists</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<FLAG>business comment</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975110352</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TAKEOVER prospects for the Royal Bank of Scotland should have faded after
yesterday's reassuring full-year figures. But no, turnover was high with nine
million shares traded although as yet there are no names that raise any
eyebrows.
Unless any bidder was foreign, there would almost certainly be an automatic
reference to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission as none of the conceivable
UK putative bidders such as BAT, NatWest, Prudential and more particularly and
potentially the most threatening, HSBC would raise competition conflicts.
But then it is difficult to see what any other financial institution would add
value as far as Royal shareholders are concerned given, that the Royal appears
to be operating more efficiently than any other UK bank apart from the Bank of
Scotland, which has only a handful of English branches and Abbey National -
although that still remains a building society in all but name, albeit livelier
than most of that herd.
At times, somewhat weary sighs are heard from one or two senior figures at the
Royal whenever Direct Line is mentioned - probably feeling that the tail is
wagging the dog.
But that insurance subsidiary is probably now the only substantial company in
the sector making money out of motor underwriting as the latest quarterly
figures from the composites begin to indicate.
And while profits for the current year may struggle to keep above #100m
(#112m), few other organisations could have maintained profits as Direct Line
did in the year to September when income was falling by 10% and will benefit
substantially when weaker competitors fail and the cycle moves upwards again.
However, the speculation will undoubtedly continue, but with the prospect of
current year profits reaching about #660m it would require a pretty pricey
offer to succeed.
Healthy 3i
THE economy may have turned down in the past few months, but earnings growth
has been impressive for many companies this year, which, in turn, has led to
generous dividend payouts. This strong corporate performance is reflected in
the healthy interim results from 3i.
Its quarterly Enterprise Barometer of small and medium-sized companies mirrors
trends seen in other economic surveys, namely a reduction in business
confidence in recent months. The Barometer Index remains positive but has
fallen to plus 17 from plus 45 in September.
Overall, companies continue to be confident about their own prospects in terms
of continued growth in turnover and profits. 3i's Chief executive, Ewen
McPherson, does not expect the Budget to have any impact on the outlook for
confidence.
The prospects for employment also appear to be better than the weaker GDP may
suggest. Over 60% of 3i companies surveyed expect to employ more people at the
end of this year compared to the end of last year.
In his Budget speech, the Chancellor praised the contribution that small and
medium-sized firms made to the economy.
Much of last year's strong growth in the UK economy was down to buoyant
exports. The proportion of 3i companies that export has been rising in recent
years: 63% of respondents export compared with 46% in April 1990.
France and Germany remain the dominant export markets. The 3i survey shows that
smaller companies are more likely to derive a higher proportion of their
turnover from exports. Manufacturing firms are also more likely to export.
Bid talks off
WELSH Water will have to go hostile if it wants to win Swalec following the
breakdown of talks between the two, and it is hard to see this being in the
interest of anyone.
The only rationale behind a hostile bid would be the savings available from a
merged company.
Swalec's claim that these would amount to only #11m annually is no doubt an
understatement and outsiders reckon they could amount to #30m-#35m, if all went
well.
This would arise from combining head offices, billing and computer systems, and
maintenance depots. There would also be major tax advantages in that Welsh
Water's accumulated advance corporation tax could be offset against Swalec's
profits.
But there could be heavy costs in implementing a merger, particularly in the
computing field where the companies use different systems. The reduction in
Swalec's workforce since privatisation has been achieved through a voluntary
scheme which was popular as a result of the age structure of the workforce. The
easy cuts have been achieved.
Further reductions would probably involve compulsory redundancies which, apart
from alienating employees, could also upset customers. They could well resent
their local utilities slugging it out in a no-holds barred takeover battle.
Welsh Water's lamentable diversification record does not inspire confidence in
its ability to manage a major merger. It can hardly tell Swalec how to run its
business better as the electricity distributor's track record shows it has
sound management who are already running a tight ship.
Rather that going through the huge cost in legal and professional fees of a
contested takeover bid, shareholders of both companies would do better from
co-operation agreements which could result in lower costs in various areas such
as depots and even billing systems.
</TEXT>
