<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Germans dash rate cut hopes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>R E DUNDAS, Chief Financial Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110354</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Bundesbank has dashed hopes of pre-Christmas cuts in interest rates around
the globe to boost the flagging economies of the major industrial nations.
The German central bank left its discount and Lombard rates unchanged after its
council meeting, frustrating hopes of an easing of monetary policy.
The Chancellor of the Exchequer, Kenneth Clarke, would now have to act
unilaterally at his meeting with the Governor of the Bank of England on
December 13 if he decided to satisfy demands for lower interest rates at home.
The Bundesbank council meets again the day after.
Earlier Mr George adopted a cautious attitude on rates. He described the
Chancellor's Budget as ``very sensible'', but added, ``We shall have to wait
and see,'' if it would create the scope for a change in monetary policy. ``A
lot of factors go into that sort of decision.''
Sterling, which has lost ground since the Budget, rallied slightly after the
Bundesbank stayed its hand. On Wednesday Mr Clarke said that he would not play
fast and loose with interest rates in response to political pressures. Last
night it looked unlikely that he would take the risk.
The Bundesbank's official discount rate was held at 3.5% and the Lombard
emergency financing rate at 5.5%, both unchanged since late August.
There had been strong speculation before the meeting that the time was ripe for
the German central bank to cut key rates for the first time in three months to
kick-start a sluggish economy.
German inflation is 1.5% and the money supply is sluggish with the economy
slowing down. A cut in German rates had been expected to spark off a round of
rate reductions on the Continent.
``They could have done it if they had wanted to and they could have justified a
move,'' said Holger Schmieding, chief economist at Merrill Lynch in Frankfurt.
``I think they will seek to keep rate cut hopes alive for the next month or two
before making a move,'' he added. He said the next official rate cut was most
likely to come in mid-January.
But economists noted the Bundesbank still had scope to ease its main money
market rate in coming weeks and was under no pressure to deliver an official
rate cut.
The securities repurchase rate or repo rate could still ease by about 20 basis
points before it bumped into the discount rate, they said.
The Bundesbank had unexpectedly raised its key money market rate on Wednesday
by one basis point to 3.98%, but economists had said the rise -the first in
three years - did not preclude a further cut in official rates.
The rise in the repo rate, was due to technical market factors and not a change
in policy, according to Bundesbank watchers.
</TEXT>
