<DOCID>GH951201-000089</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Profit-taking sends Dow sharply lower</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110355</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
New York close: # = $1.5319
New York, Thursday - Blue-chip stocks closed sharply lower on profit-taking as
investors called a time-out after the market racked up six straight sessions of
record highs.
The Dow Jones industrial average ended 31.07 lower at 5074.49, retreating from
yesterday's record high of 5105.56.
Analysts said economic data released this morning pointed to slow growth in the
economy, bolstering hopes of a possible interest rate cut as early as December.
October US durable goods orders slipped by 1% and the Chicagoland Business
Barometer fell to 49.9 in November from 53.4 in October.
``We have a very overbought market in the Dow,'' said Paul Rabbitt, senior
quantitative analyst at Oppenheimer &amp; Co. But he said underlying market
strength was limiting the weakness in stock prices.
``The market is overbought but it has to be viewed in a context. There is
momentum,'' Rabbitt said. ``I think the momentum will carry the market by
bumping the trading ranges higher.''
Retailers reported that November same-store sales were disappointing.
``Retail sales are a little on the soft side,'' said Philip Orlando, chief
investment officer at Value Line Asset Management. ``The scarier point is that
for them to get those weak sales they had to have a heavy promotion already in
season.''
He expects this Christmas to be the worst holiday season for retailers this
decade. ``Retail sales this morning support my theory,'' he said.
</TEXT>
