<DOCNO>GH951201-000090</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>LIG seeks net benefit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110357</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LONDON International Group, the world's largest manufacturer of condoms, is
launching its Durex brand on the internet computer network as part of an
``on-going'' initiative to globalise the condom brand.
The company says the new site will also promote `safe surfing' on the internet
by providing tips on condoms, romance and safe sex for those exploring the
on-line world.
Unveiling a rise in pre-tax profits from #1m to #6.5m for the six months to
September 30 as it continues to recover from its 1993 slump, LIG also signalled
its intention to increase its share of the market with the purchase of the
`Mister' condom brand in South East Asia for #2m, its first condom
manufacturing purchase for many years. Mister is the long established brand
leader with 40% of the fast growing Malaysian market. With Durex the number two
brand, LIG will control around 70% of this market.
Chief executive Nick Hodges said, ``Together with market leadership in Hong
Kong, Thailand and Singapore, our strength and position in Malaysia provides us
with a strong platform for growth in these and other markets in South East
Asia.''
In the US, Avanti, the group's polyurethane condom, has retained its 3% market
share by value in the 13 western states and current clinical and pricing trials
are expected to be completed by 1996. This will be followed by a US national
launch at a substantially increased price. LIG says it remains positive about
the long-term potential of Avanti as a high priced niche product.
Meanwhile, the group's ``encouraging performance'' has meant a resumption of
payment of an interim dividend, with shareholders receiving 0.5p against
nothing last time. Earnings per share rose from 0.32p to 1.43p.
Sales of the health and personal products business were up 7.3% to #139.5m,
with core products, condoms, surgical and specialist gloves achieving
underlying growth of 13.8% after adjustments for currency movements, brand
disposals and promotional smoothing.
LIG says it is on track to meet its goals even though further rationalisation
will be needed. ``We are on track to meet our goals and budgets for the year,
our second-half is traditionally a stronger trading period for the group,''
said chairman Michael Moore.
The firm is continuing to pursue a divestment strategy of brands which do not
support core business and for which satisfactory prices can be obtained.
