<DOCID>GH951201-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish Radio wants to extend its empire to the Irish Republic</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975110358</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Radio Holdings, Scotland's largest commercial radio group, wants to
extend its growing media empire to the Irish Republic.
The Glasgow-based company is leading a consortium which will submit an
application in Dublin today for the Irish national radio licence to run an FM
station covering the entire country.
The move comes as Scottish Radio unveils record profit of #5.1m, up 22% in the
year to September 30 on turnover up 9% at #17.2m.
Finance director Jim Bowman said the company hopes to hear the result of the
Irish licence application before its annual meeting on February 15.
He declined to give further details about the project, which represents
Scottish Radio's second foray across the Irish Sea.
Last month Scottish Radio purchased the Morton group of weekly newspapers in
Northern Ireland for #11.2m, setting the stage for the development of a more
diversified media business.
Once the Morton purchase has been digested, Scottish Radio plans to buy more
weeklies in the UK or Eire, but Mr Bowman said the group would continue its
tradition of making amicable, not hostile purchases.
This policy enables Scottish Radio to make purchases by issuing more of its own
shares as well as by paying cash.
The company operates Radio Clyde, Radio Forth, Radio Tay and Northsound in
Scotland and claims that all these stations are market leaders in their own
area.
Local advertising revenue grew at a steady 6% last year, while national
advertising, booked through its London sales house SIRS, soared 22%.
A final payout of 4.4p raised the full-year dividend by 20% to 6.5p and
Scottish Radio shares gained 2p to 312p.
The company has made a good start to the current financial year, with broadcast
revenue rising 7% in October and November. Chairman Ian Chapman said he was
``confident of the medium and long-term prospects''.
Scottish Radio's two new Irish ventures reflect its deliberate attempt to break
out of a cramped radio environment in Scotland where there is little room to
grow further.
``Any expansion that we might contemplate in commercial radio would not be in
Scotland, where there is nothing significant left to go for,'' Mr Bowman said.
Scottish Radio had a 40% stake in West Cumbria Radio, which began broadcasting
to the Workington and Whitehaven areas in September and Mr Bowman said it is
now interested in the regional radio licences for Yorkshire and East Anglia,
which will be offered in 1966.
The finance director said Scottish Radio plans to apply its expertise gained in
local radio to local newspapers.
But this will be in partnership with Charles Villiers, the architect of the
Morton purchase, who has been appointed chief executive of the company's SCORE
Press newspaper division.
The company had #8.2m of cash and no debt at the end of September. But Mr
Bowman said it would borrow money to expand if this seemed appropriate.
</TEXT>
