<DOCID>GH951201-000092</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>You can be there,  as history rolls in</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975110359</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNLIKE some historic events, Le Jog welcomes spectators at controls and test
locations.
The first main time control in Scotland is the Horse and Hounds at Bonchester
Bridge on the A68, where the first car should arrive around 15.20 on Sunday.
The route then goes by way of Darnick and Stow to the overnight stop at the
Royal Scot Hotel on the west side of Edinburgh from 18.00.
After the only night stop on the event, the restart from the Royal Scot is at
07.15 on Monday. Competitors head for a test at Knockhill opening at 08.00,
then bypass Gleneagles Hotel on the way via Comrie and Lochearnhead to a main
control at Killin around 10.00.
Fortingall and Pitlochry are on the route to another main control at the
Dalrulzion Hotel, Glenshee, from 12.30. Edzell at 14.25 is on the way to a test
on the sprint course beside the Grampian Transport Museum at Alford from 15.30.
A route check at the Glen Avon Hotel in Tomintoul leads to another main control
at the Garth Hotel, Grantown-on-Spey, then a main control and dinner halt at
the Thistle Hotel, Inverness.
Down to Dores for 22.10, cars should be at Inverfarigaig from 22.30, then go
into Tuesday for another main control at the Lady Ross Cafe in Ardgay from
02.00.
Golspie at 02.45 offers a refuelling stop at the Sutherland Arms, and then
there is an early breakfast halt at Tongue Hotel from 05.45. The final stretch
takes the surviving cars to John o'Groats from 09.25, at the end of what the
crews will have found a memorable adventure - when they look back on it!
</TEXT>
