<DOCNO>GH951201-000093</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000093</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Swalec boosts half-time earnings</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Christopher Sims</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110360</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TALKS between Welsh Water and Swalec - South Wales Electricity - broke down
yesterday afternoon, with the latter saying that the proposed cash and shares
offer - worth 916p per share excluding the rights to National Grid shares -
undervalued the company, writes CHRISTOPHER SIMS.
``We are fed up that Welsh Water has now dithered for over three weeks without
tabling an acceptable offer,'' declared Andrew Walker, Swalec chief executive.
Mr Walker's hand was strengthened by good results from his company yesterday.
First half figures showed profits some 12% higher at #60.4m and the interim
dividend 5p up at 16p plus a special 100p extra payment.
Swalec is prepared to resume talking with Welsh Water but if the group insists
on going ahead with a contested bid, Mr Walker promised more for shareholders.
``You can be sure we have more powder in our locker,'' he declared. But he
added: ``We're not a scorched-earth kind of company.''
This was a reference to the defence package put forward by Northern Electricity
which left it with heavy gearing. The extra dividend is instead of another
buy-back of shares which the group had considered earlier. It has had
indications that shareholders preferred this. The move will raise gearing to
60% at the year-end, leaving scope for a further defensive cash payout.
Swalec's profits gain stems from a 21% drop in costs in real terms from a year
ago which more than offset a sharp fall in revenues from the regulated
activity. The group is more than halfway towards its target of cutting costs by
#45m a year. Manpower has come down by 30% in four and-a-half years.
In domestic supply margins improved sharply under more focused management and
lower bad debts with profits up from #5.5m to #9.8m.
The non-regulated interests include a joint venture cable operation which
continues its build-out with encouraging levels of connections.
There is also a contracting business which returned to profits after
restructuring. Swalec shares closed 24p up at 1113p while Welsh Water eased 7p
to 689p.
n.SOUTH West Water's profits were up 7% to #54m for the six months to September
on turnover 8% ahead at #155m. The interim dividend is raised 8% to 9.8p.
</TEXT>
