<DOCNO>GH951201-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dole backs plan for US troops in Bosnia</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110363</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton's plans to send around 20,000 troops to join a Nato
peacekeeping force in Bosnia received a crucial boost tonight when Senate
Republican leader Bob Dole said he would support the move.
Plans for the 60,000 Nato troops to police the peace in the Balkans began to
take definite shape tonight as Alliance ambassadors met in Brussels and the US
Congress began debating its proposed contingent.
``This is a very important time in American history. This is a very important
commitment the president has made. We wish he had listened to us (and lifted
the arms embargo on Bosnia long ago),'' Dole told the Senate.
He said he was preparing a resolution of approval, with provisions to protect
the troops and get them out in one year, for Congress's action late next week
or the following week.
The Clinton administration had spent the day lobbying Congressmen to back the
President's decision to commit US troops to oversee the Bosnian peace deal
struck last week in Dayton, Ohio.
Defence Secretary William Perry, Secretary of State Warren Christopher and
General John Shalikashvili, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, went before
Congress seeking its support to deploy US soldiers, although President Clinton,
their commander-in-chief, says he does not legally need it.
Without Nato intervention, Perry said, the war that claimed an estimated
250,000 lives would erupt again. ``The United States is the only nation that
can lead that force to success,'' he warned.
In New York, the United Nations Security Council tonight voted unanimously to
pull its blue-helmets out of Bosnia by the end of January - so making way for
the Nato force.
The Security Council decided to end its 40-month-old operation in Bosnia on
January 31.
Then, in two consecutive meetings, the council also voted to renew its mission
in Macedonia for six months and extend its operation in Croatia until January
15.
Nato policymakers met in the Belgian capital today to hammer out details for
the embarkation of an advance party of some 2600 elite troops next week.
The rest of the troops are due to start moving in shortly after the deal is
signed in Paris on December 14.
The Brussels session of the North Atlantic Council broke up tonight without
granting official authorisation. It was to meet again tomorrow to resume
discussions.
While the US Congress and the US public remain deeply divided over whether to
send American troops to Bosnia, the first American service personnel arrived
openly in the war-torn republic to scout the terrain today.
Ten US army and a similar number of air force members were in the Bosnian
government-controlled town of Tuzla to inspect their future command post for
the north-east sector and its huge airstrip.
Their open presence contrasts with secret visits by survey teams just before
and just after agreement on the Bosnia peace deal was reached in Dayton.
-Reuter/AP.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000095</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000095</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Casanova lives - in Italians</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110364</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Latin Lover is alive and well in Italy where an opinion poll released
yesterday found two out of three married men had cheated on their wives.
Half of the all-male respondents said marital indiscretions were a ``natural
tendency'' and a large majority said adultery by men should never or almost
never be a reason for divorce.
A poll for the Federation of Italian Psychologists interviewed 960 men. Of the
married men, 67.3% said they had committed adultery - 55% once, and 52% two to
five times.
``For Italian men, only adultery by married women is a taboo,'' said the
federation.
Unmarried MP Vittorio Sgarbi said: ``Whoever has only one lifelong partner is
mentally unbalanced. Cheating does you good, it cures boredom and
unhappiness.''            -Reuter.
</TEXT>
