<DOCID>GH951201-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Off the boil</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110365</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n HOWEVER they fared with the Chancellor this week, home owners with central
heating can budget for big savings through the latest technology.
The Government-backed Energy Saving Trust reckons a third could be lopped off
the average yearly gas bill of #600 by switching to a condensing boiler, which
ensures peak performance by harnessing some of the heat wasted by older
appliances.
The new boilers could pay for themselves within five years - more quickly if,
as some experts predict, fuel prices take off by the turn of the century.
For an information pack, and details of a special #100 promotion, phone energy
advice centres free on 0800 512012.
Ticket to ride
n NEARLY every bus and rail ticket ever produced says it somewhere: ``Not
transferable''. But ScotRail has signalled a change with a ticket that can be
transferred with their wholehearted endorsement.
The Flex-Pass provides 50 queue-free, cash-saving journeys between Glasgow and
Edinburgh and comes in book form. Users simply fill in the appropriate journey
date for travel in either direction. The ticket is valid until April 30 - first
class costs #420, the standard ticket #270, equal to 10% off peak-time fares.
For more information contact ScotRail travel centres or agents.
The star prize
n THE Three Kings would have been lost without theirs, and the Queen Mother is
proud of hers. Now you, too, can have something that's out of this world: a
star.
According to the International Star Registry, who include hundreds of
celebrities and VIPs among their clients, it's the ultimate Christmas gift.
They will name a star after you, or a loved one, registering the details at the
British Library and the American Library of Congress.
The Star Registry commemorative package, complete with certificate and
telescopic co-ordinates to pinpoint the star in the Milky Way, normally costs
#55 but Check-Out readers can enjoy a #10 Christmas discount. To order phone
0800 212493 or write to ISR, Freepost, 24 Highbury Grove, London N5 2BR.
Check-Out has one star to give to the first name out of the hat. Entries by
December 7 to Star Prize, Herald Features, 195 Albion Street, Glasgow G1 1QP
(first class post recommended).
Not so nutty
n AMID fears that confusion over metric labelling will lead to unfrosted and
undercooked poultry giving more families the ``turkey trots'' this Christmas,
vegetarians could have something to crow about.
For those unschooled in the wherewithal of the nut roast, Cauldron Foods have
come up with a temptingly healthy yuletide alternative that's simple to make -
tofu Christmas Parcels with Cranberry, a main course for four.
Wrapped in filo pastry, the key ingredient - along with mushrooms, red onion
and parsley - is the protein and calcium-rich, but cholesterol-free, soya bean
wonder food.
The recipe - and details of other tofu products like vegetarian sausages,
burgers and pates - is free to Check-Out readers sending an sae to Jenny Binns,
27 Fitzroy Square, London W1P 5HH.
For those committed to a fowl Christmas, advice is to ensure birds are fully
defrosted in a cool room before cooking, never a warm kitchen. Ensure there are
no crystals in the cavity after removing giblets. If in doubt, ask the supplier
about recommended roasting times per kilo.
Title spud
n ANYA, named after Lady Sainsbury, is the latest potato at Sainsbury's. Bred
by the Scottish Crops Research Institute, it's said to be like the Pink Fir
Apple variety minus the knobbly bits . . . Planning a new look for the New
Year? The Interior Decorators and Designers Association has a free leaflet
about its home and office services. Send sae to IDDA, Chelsea Harbour Design
Centre, Chelsea Harbour, London SW10 0XE (0171 349 0800) . . . Christmas
pudding based on one served to King George I in 1714 costs #3.75 from Haymarket
Catering Services, 138 Main Street, East Calder (01506 883772) or ask at
Haymarket Railway Station's Food on 4.
</TEXT>
