<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000097</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000097</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Travelling circus offers safety net</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Patrick Brogan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110366</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE British people have been witness this week to the awesome and overblown
mechanism of an American president. The phenomenon is akin to Queen Elizabeth
I, who used to bankrupt her less favoured subjects by staying with them. All
those hangers-on, all that electronic equipment, the huge cars, all that excess
of preparation, and overwhelming media presence.
Like the Tudors, American presidents maintain their authority by demonstrating
it. Bill Clinton, following his predecessors' example, has fallen back on the
trials and triumphs of foreign policy to get him over a tough time at home.
It's not to be sneezed at. For his first two years, Clinton ignored foreign
affairs, and there was no leadership in the world. He has now rediscovered the
power of the presidency.
All the progress that has been made on the Northern Ireland question has been
due to American prodding, including Tuesday's sudden agreement between Major
and Bruton. The Dayton treaty was only possible because the Americans pushed
for it.
Under the American Constitution, that means the president pushing.
In fact, this has been a good period for Clinton. In one week there was the
Bosnia agreement, the reopening, largely on his terms, of the federal
government after the Republicans had shut it down, and now the agreement
between London and Dublin, concocted at the last moment before the president
arrived.
But don't be misled. It could all fall apart, and the most brilliant success
abroad does not translate into solid votes at home. Jimmy Carter brought about
peace between Israel and Egypt, and George Bush won a spectacular war in the
Middle East. They were both thrown out on their necks at the next elections,
like a couple of latter-day Churchills. If Clinton wins next year, it will be
because of the weakness of the opposition candidate, or candidates, not through
his own merits or his foreign triumphs.
He was elected three years ago and it is now possible to run up a tally-sheet
of his presidency. He has proved a dud president, like so many of his
predecessors, and these few foreign successes don't alter that - and new,
spectacular failures won't make it any worse.
It is entirely possible that he will win the next presidential election while
the Republicans keep their majorities in both houses of Congress, and so the
gridlock will continue for another four years.
Now that the boot is on the other foot, Democrats can rejoice at gridlock,
because it prevents Newt Gingrich and his merry men wreaking total havoc on the
welfare system, the environment and the principle of progressive taxation.
This is not all the result of America's inadequate institutions: Clinton has
played a large part in grinding down his own presidency. Even more important
has been the general decline of the Democratic Party over the past 20 years.
Successful presidents have either swept into town on huge majorities, carrying
Congress with them, or they have been adept at manipulating Congressional
politics, or they have been particularly attuned to the zeitgeist.
The greatest, Franklin Roosevelt for instance, have been all three. Lyndon
Johnson had both a huge majority, after the 1964 election, and unrivalled skill
at managing Congress. He got the zeitgeist wrong, and it destroyed him.
Ronald Reagan caught the spirit of the times, and though his conservative
policies ran into the sands after a couple of years (that often happens), he
was always able to tell Americans what they wanted to hear, and so remained a
popular and effective president to the end.
Clinton, like Ford, Carter and Bush, to go no farther back, never had a
majority to support him in Congress, has shown minimal skill at playing off the
various factions and individuals in Congress against each other, and, as for
the zeitgeist, he hasn't a clue.
He has nothing much to show for his first three years, except that at last he
seems to have discovered a recipe for thwarting the Republicans and hanging on
to enough public support to stand a good chance of victory next year.
All he has to do is to point out that the Republicans, despite their laudable
desire to balance the budget and reform the welfare system, are in fact the
party of the rich, white suburbs and are also in thrall to business interests
who want to wind up the past decades' victories on the environment,
occupational safety, and land policy.
Industries that object to the clean air laws, for instance, have bought
Republican support in the old-fashioned way, with money. The party's official
position now is that the laws have worked, the air is clean, so we don't need
the laws any more.
Rather belatedly, the party has discovered a huge majority of Americans
actually approve of the environmental protection laws.
To cap it all, their chief spokesman, Newt Gingrich, is a stridently unpleasant
man. Clinton will run against him, no matter whom the Republicans nominate for
president.
This is a far cry from the high hopes Democrats felt after they won the 1992
election, only their second win in 24 years.
They expected a leader who would revitalise the party, give it a new sense of
direction, or at the very least establish it firmly and unassailably in the
centre of the political field.
Clinton failed on all counts. The best he and his party can now hope for is to
block the Republican revolution, a negative ambition and a sign the Democrats
are really brain dead.
But it must be said, as we saw in London and Ireland this week, that Clinton
carries off the business of travelling president very well. America, and its
president, have still a role to play in the world, even if they can't get their
act together at home.
</TEXT>
