<DOCNO>GH951201-000098</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000098</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>High road to the aisles</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jane Scott</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110367</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN Asda executives take the train on business, they travel second class.
``Have done for some time,'' cheerfully asserts PR manager Jeni Cropper,
describing how the Asda culture of saving money extends to recycling envelopes
and eating sandwiches rather than business lunches.
The past three years have seen the company opening a store in Cumbernauld the
week before last and another in Govan this month, making a triumphant return to
its cost-cutting roots.
Savage attacks on the price of books and pharmaceuticals have been allied to a
reconstruction of Asda's management and staff morale, plus a stream of bright
ideas in-store that make its three main competitors Safeway, Sainsbury's and,
possibly, Tesco often look simply tired.
If Asda is doing so well, say insiders (outperforming predictions on shares,
sales and customer numbers, high public profile thanks to the Asda Difference
TV advertising campaign) it is because it dominates the only area left for
increasingly sophisticated and similar supermarkets to exploit. The superstore
wars of the late nineties will be fought on customer service.
In the eighties, says Paul Smiddy, retail analyst with Credit Lyonnais Laing,
supermarkets fought each other on the design of the stores and the development
of own-label brands. In the early nineties the emphasis shifted to price, but
the arrival of continental discount stores such as Aldi and Netto meant someone
could alway sell it to you cheaper, even if it was straight out of the
cardboard box.
The mid-nineties found the big four supermarkets, knowing there was only so
much money to be made on food, established in retail parks on the outskirts of
towns with a raft of newly-built stores offering many High Street services;
pharmacies, post offices, dry cleaning, petrol, with the extras such as coffee
shops and baby changing rooms the customers were beginning to take for granted.
Although the big four will each target a certain sort of customer - Asda will
always attract lower earners than Sainsbury's, with its traditional emphasis on
quality and its glossy magazine snob value - this leaves customer service as
the only new way superstores can outpace the competition.
Safeway, whose parent company Argyll this week announced a steep share rise
after strong sales took the city by surprise, has advertised heavily its
customer services through the popular Harry toddler in the trolley campaign.
But for years, customer service was not the most important part of the
supermarket package. In fact, the introduction of bar-reading checkouts was
designed to shove more people through the tills quicker. Smiddy points to
Sainsbury's, for 10 years the acknowledged market leader by focusing on the
``mechanistic'' side of shopping, such as improving store hygiene, increasing
stock and making more trolleys available. This was at the expense of ``softer''
services (the company itself, in its interim results announcement on November
1, admitted it was seeking ``a warmer, less clinical image for Sainsbury's'').
It thereby allowed Tesco to clean up when that store introduced the important
``one in front'' queue system in 1993, ensuring no more than one customer was
waiting for a till at a time.
This, together with the increasing numbers of packers on the tills, shows how
retailers are focusing on the ``front end'' of the supermarket experience -
quality, freshness and a wide stock are now pretty much the same throughout the
big four, so it's the people on the tills who make the difference.
Sainsbury's eventually copied ``one in front'', but made the mistake of
advertising the service. It was forced to pull the advert when people
complained to the Advertising Standards Authority that the extra tills did not
open up when required, demonstrating the danger of making promises you can't
keep.
Tesco's other strength is its loyalty discount Clubcard, which already has
6,000,000 holders, indicating the scale of market share the superstores are
fighting for. City analysts put Argyll's strong showing this week down to its
ABC loyalty card, introduced late in the game but now taking off rapidly.
A loyal customer, Smiddy estimates, ``could provide #200,000 in sales to a
supermarket chain over his or her lifetime''. This is the equivalent of #20,000
in net profits. Sainsbury's was wrong-footed again on this one, initially
discounting the benefits of loyalty cards before belatedly introducing them to
hundreds of stores.
What characterises Asda and Tesco, says Smiddy, is an enterprise culture within
the stores themselves. He says Sainsbury's has traditionally favoured a
hierarchical management structure, while Tesco managers have more freedom to
try out their own ideas.
And at Asda, since the arrival of chief executive Archie Norman four years ago,
the whole staff has been involved in running the company.
Norman, a Harvard business graduate in his early forties who in his spare time
runs a small family farm in Argyll, was headhunted to run a company in deep
trouble.
Asda's roots are on the outskirts of Leeds, where in 1965 a consortium of West
Yorkshire dairymen and butchers opened the first of a rapidly growing chain of
``pile 'em high, sell 'em cheap'' stores for their products.
Throughout the seventies and eighties Asda expanded, opening its first Scottish
store in Edinburgh in 1972 (there are 28 in Scotland today, around 205
nationwide).
But in the late eighties, Asda acquired 69 Gateway stores, and with them a huge
and unmanageable debt. ``Asda Price'' became a thing of the past and the
company found itself with a stable of downmarket stores with a reputation to
match.
Norman changed everything. He brought in a team of young MBA business people
like himself, put new managers in nearly every store and launched a
``three-year plan'' of recovery which has just ended.
Asda stores are about 60% larger than the competition's, so Norman could offer
every in-store service available. The company thus has more petrol stations,
pharmacies, dry-cleaning shops, coffee shops and creches than anyone else.
Not content with having ``more bakeries baking fresh bread from scratch than
anybody else,'' according Jeni Cropper, the company also opened them up to the
public, who can now talk to the bakers as they work. Similar plans are afoot
for the butcheries.
Price is paramount. October's Food Retailing Survey from analysts Verdict
priced the Asda basket of groceries lower than any of its competitors. The
company recently succeeded in smashing the Net Book Agreement where booksellers
such as Dillons had failed, with the result that 30% of UK sales of John Le
Carre's Our Game were made in Asda, which is engaging in the same battle with
dietary supplements and pharmaceuticals - possibly with an eye on eventually
discounting NHS prescriptions.
The company recognises the threat to smaller retailers such buying power
represents, but, says Cropper: ``There's always a specialist route (for them)
to go down. Sixty per cent of people, up to recently, never went into a
bookshop. We have opened up lines to people who never bought books.
``We are aggressive. We are determined to give our shoppers the best value.''
The company recently bought the firm producing its highly successful George
line of clothing - to make him ``one of the Asda family then, properly'', says
Cropper.
Staff, in company literature, are known as ``colleagues''. ``In the company
there's a great feeling that nobody's more important than anybody else.''
At recruitment, staff are screened for their ``customer-friendly'' potential in
heavily-weighted questions on the application form and during the interview, a
more sophisticated process than any of its rivals.
Once on board, the Tell Archie scheme encourages the 69,000 staff to contact
Norman directly with their ideas; he receives some 500 a month. They are
allowed space in store to promote a line or an idea they think will sell, and
benefit from a share ownership plan and individual and storewide customer
service awards. Sainsbury's pioneered profit sharing, but has no store-based
incentive scheme; the same is true of Tesco, and Safeway shopfloor staff have
no effective bonus system.
In contrast, Asda staff are paid less than their top three competitors - around
#3.67 per hour, against Tesco's #4.26 - and recently saw their double time for
Sunday working cut to time and a half.
This may not be a negative, says Paul Smiddy of Credit Lyonnais; apart from
demonstrating that Sunday working, inevitably, is becoming an accepted part of
normal employment conditions, it means the company - where, remember, even the
executives travel second class - can therefore afford to employ part-time
workers for longer hours, giving them a greater share in the all-powerful
``Asda family''.
</TEXT>
