<HEADLINE>Soldier's court plea rejected</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110368</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Larnaca, Thursday
A COURT in Cyprus today rejected a British soldier's attempt to suppress a
statement in which he allegedly accused a fellow soldier of killing a young
Danish woman.
Private Jeff Parnell, 23, of Oldbury, West Midlands, made the statement nine
hours after he and two other soldiers were arrested for the murder last year of
23-year-old tour guide Louise Jensen.
The three soldiers, based at Dhekelia, are on trial for manslaughter,
abduction, and conspiracy to rape.
``Alan did it,'' Parnell is alleged to have said, referring to Private Alan
Ford, 27, of Birmingham. The third accused is Private Justin Fowler, also 27,
of Falmouth, Cornwall.
Parnell's lawyer argued that, as Parnell was drunk and tired when he made the
statement, it be ruled inadmissible. However Judge Takis Eliades replied: ``The
tiredness he was feeling was natural and it can't be said that it was to such
an extent that his freedom of judgment was affected.'' The hearing
continues.-AP.
</TEXT>
