<HEADLINE>Manager in #3m takeover</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ken Gallacher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110370</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DUNDEE Football Club has been sold by the Canadian who has owned the Dens Park
side for almost five years.
It is believed Mr Ron Dixon, who is based in Vancouver, decided to announce the
#3m deal only after learning The Herald had divulged the imminent sale
yesterday.
After being told of The Herald story, he promised an official statement by late
afternoon.
It revealed Mr Dixon was giving up control and that his vice-chairman, Mr
Malcolm Reid, a local businessman, and player manager Jim Duffy were part of
the take-over group.
They will be supported in the move by two wealthy, and as yet unnamed
Dundonians. The money will be paid to Mr Dixon over the next five years.
The initial asking price of #2.2m had not included the Dens Park stadium in the
deal, but that has now become part of the package, boosting the price to #3m.
Mr Dixon, who also stated that Mr Duffy could eventually become chairman of the
Tayside club, bought the club for #600,000 then kept it afloat with an interest
free personal loan of another #1.5m.
</TEXT>
