<HEADLINE>Drivers warned of morning after</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110372</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLICE yesterday warned motorists to expect a morning-after clampdown during
the festive season drink-driving campaign, the first week of which ends today.
Strathclyde and Central forces confirmed that extra road-checks had been
arranged to target morning commuters. In Lothian and Borders, with no specific
morning clampdown, initial impressions suggested an increase in motorists being
caught at that time of day.
Two arrested
POLICE investigating the death of a Caithness man, Mr Gordon Miller, 36, whose
body was found naked and battered in Liverpool on Monday, have arrested a
16-year-old youth and a man of 22.
Thieves of time
THIEVES who broke into Phillips Auctioneers, in George Street, Edinburgh, stole
watches worth more than #8000.
Bugging error
LOTHIAN and Borders police said yesterday that one of their own employees
inadvertently bugged the control room in their Edinburgh HQ. A statement said
they believed there had been no breach of security from the device, in a plug
adaptor.
Village facelift
THE Loch Lomond village of Balloch is to have a #300,000 facelift. Dumbarton
Council plans environmental improvements at the Moss o' Balloch car parks and
the River Leven slipway - despite objections from some villagers.
Flat siege ends
A SIEGE at a flat in Rhyl, North Wales, ended peacefully yesterday after more
than 10 hours. A man was arrested and was helping police with their inquiries
over alleged threats to kill and to cause criminal damage.
</TEXT>
