<HEADLINE>Institution divorced from reality</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Steve Bruce</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110373</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Archbishop of Canterbury is upset that a report from a Church of England
committee has suggested ``living in sin'' is not actually a sin. George Carey
roundly denounced the implication that no single form of the family was a
God-given ideal.
Religion has always been about sex, though once it was about everything. The
earliest European visitors to Australia reported back that the natives had no
religion. Because the aborigines did not distinguish the natural and
supernatural worlds in the way we did, because they did not have special
buildings for worship, the blinkered visitors missed the all-pervasive nature
of their spirituality.
The evolution of human culture has seen the shrinking of religion. The
Christian Church of the Middle Ages tried to dominate every aspect of life;
even such economic activity as the pricing of bread was thought a fitting
matter for church courts.
One of the few areas of life the churches have tried to keep in their grasp is
sexual reproduction. An institution which wishes to address the entire human
condition must have something to say about how life begins. The Genesis story
of Adam and Eve comes at the start of the Bible. When it has lost everything
else, religion will still try to tell us how to engage in sex and how to
reproduce the species.
For centuries the Christian Church had a more mundane reason for trying to keep
a grip on our private parts. Understanding that allows us to see why the grip
has become arthritic. In the feudal world, social and political power derived
from positions in a fixed hierarchy and those positions were inherited. The
Stewarts were so-called because their family held the hereditary office of
``steward'' to the king. Aberdeen's Marischal College was named after its
founder and benefactor, the Earl of Keith, the hereditary ``marshall'' of
Scotland.
The most important productive asset - land - was inherited. Where the rules say
the wealth of one generation should pass to the rightful heir in the next
generation, identifying the rightful heir was a serious matter.
Rich and powerful people, if rich and powerful enough, might reward their
bastards, but there was still an enormous difference between the rights of the
legitimate heir and the claims of illegitimate offspring. Where so much
depended on the legal relationship of the sperm and the egg, the Church's work
in giving supernatural justification to marriage rules, and policing the
observance of these rules, was actively supported by the rich and powerful.
The poor were always less easily persuaded. Church records of every epoch show
fornication and pregnancy outside of wedlock to be popular offences. Even when
almost everyone belonged to the same Church, it was impossible to prevent
promiscuity. When, after the Reformation, the great national Churches
fragmented into competing sects, it was all that much easier for people to
evade religious sanctions.
Industrial production displaced agriculture. The joint stock company freed
manufacturing enterprises from their dependence on the personal fortunes of the
owner. Political power shifted to assemblies of elected individuals.
Inheritance ceased to sit at the core of our economy or polity. Just which side
of the blanket someone was born on was reduced to a purely cultural matter. And
from there it was a short step to not mattering at all.
What is more revealing about the Church of England's predicament than the
headline story is a sub-text buried in George Carey's argument that ``marriage,
not cohabitation, is the institution which is at the heart of the good
society''. Here marriage is not defended on the grounds that it is divinely
ordained and that those who break divine ordinances will be punished with
eternal damnation.
Rather, it is advertised for its social benefits. Marriage is good for a
society. Perhaps it is. Perhaps any sensible Government should arrange social
policy to buttress such a useful institution. But to abandon the highest ground
of divine ordinance and to rest the legitimacy of marriage on its social
functions is to invite argument and neglect: argument because we can reasonably
disagree over just how functional is the traditional marriage; neglect because,
however concerned we may be in the abstract about the health of our society,
most of us make decisions on the basis of personal interest.
However, we can readily see why the Archbishop has to offer functional
arguments instead of prophetic denunciation. Less than three-quarters of us
even claim to believe in ``God''. Half of that number think of the divinity as
some vague ``higher power'' rather than as a personal deity with strong and
clear ethical standards. Less than a quarter of us claim to believe in hell.
Deprived of those weapons, the writ of modern Church leaders runs very small.
Of all the Christian Churches the Roman Catholic is closest to the medieval
Church in the claims it makes for its own authority. It has taken a clear
distinctive position on matters of sexual morality. Yet, as we see from the
incontestable fact that Catholic birth rates are the same as those for
non-Catholics of the same social class, it could be argued that even committed
church-going Catholics do not follow the teachings of their Church on
artificial contraception.
If the Pope cannot control his own followers, what hope have the bishops of the
Church of England got of influencing the sexual behaviour of the 90% of the
population who very rarely enter any place of worship?
n Steve Bruce is Professor of Sociology at the University of Aberdeen.
</TEXT>
