<HEADLINE>Clashes break out on Fatah anniversary</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From RULA HALAWANI</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110374</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Nablus, West Bank, Thursday
ISRAELI troops wounded 18 Arabs in Nablus today in a day of violence in which
two Israelis were also wounded by gunfire on a bus escorted by army jeeps.
Nablus residents took to the streets to commemorate the sixth anniversary of
the killing by Israeli troops of four Fatah Black Panther leaders.
Witnesses said youths, disdaining Israeli fire, stood in full view on rooftops
and hurled concrete blocks and large stones at troops. Protesters commandeered
trucks to use as barricades.
Demonstrators screamed at the Israeli troops ``Get out, maniacs'' and
``Occupation must end''.
Medical sources at Nablus's Rafidiyeh hospital said 18 people aged 20 to 35
were hurt, two of them seriously by gunshot wounds. Some were wounded by rubber
bullets.
Nablus district, with a population of 500,000, is to be the third Palestinian
area to be handed over to PLO rule. Jenin was handed over this month and
Tulkarm, in the northern West Bank, is to be evacuated by the Israeli army on
December 10.
Meanwhile, Israel today froze gradual handover of West Bank population centres,
set for completion by the end of the year, after the brief kidnap of two of its
soldiers in Jenin yesterday by Black Panther members retaliating against
Israeli attempts to arrest a Fatah man in nearby Qabatiyeh.
The Black Panthers are a militant offshoot of Palestine Liberation Organisation
leader Yasser Arafat's mainstream Fatah faction. They were leaders in the
northern West Bank in the fight against Israeli occupation during the
Palestinian uprising.
The kidnappers released the Israelis and their weapons after extensive
Israeli-PLO mediation. Israeli troops later lifted a siege of the Qabatiyeh
coffee shop where the Fatah man had taken refuge. He surrendered to Palestinian
police.
Palestinian police Colonel Wajih Abu Gharbiyeh told reporters today that four
Black Panthers had been arrested for the kidnapping and would be tried.
Later today, two Israelis were wounded when shots were fired at an Israeli bus
near the Jewish settlement of Shaked on Jenin's outskirts, the Israeli army
said.
The bus was being escorted by Israeli army jeeps and Abu Gharbiyeh said it was
in an area where the Israelis were responsible for security.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
