<HEADLINE>Man with murder on his mind</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Lord Macintyre</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975110376</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE morning after receiving a #10,000 cheque for the McVitie's Prize as 1995
Scottish Writer of the Year, Frank Kuppner is sitting drinking tea with lemon
in the Brasserie Metro in Glasgow's West End.
There has been no big overnight celebration: this quiet-spoken, studious man of
44 has invested too much of his life in developing his gifts to have his head
turned by success. ``The money releases you to concentrate your mind on other
things,'' he says.
Kuppner is a Glaswegian, educated at St Mungo's, who went to Glasgow University
to study English and German but left without taking a degree.
``It was a general sense that this wasn't really what I should be doing. I
don't regret it in terms of thinking I was wrong; I regret it in terms of not
making a better use of my time. Your surroundings are thick with people giving
you what is actually good advice, but there are things you have to find out for
yourself.''
After leaving Gilmorehill, Kuppner helped his father, an electronics engineer,
in his shop while trying to write. What maintained his creative drive was the
feeling he was about to do better than he was doing. ``I remember Francis Bacon
the painter saying that he was an optimist, but not about anything. I always
felt that way myself, without having any particular grounds to be optimistic.''
Kuppner's first book, A Bad Day for the Sung Dynasty, poems on Chinese themes,
came out in 1984. ``Before your first book's published you've no idea what sort
of difference it's going to make. Conceptually and in terms of your own image
it's crucially important. You think: I'm a writer. Questions of how precarious
it is, or if there's a living in it, are secondary.''
His first all-prose work, A Very Quiet Street, was published by Polygon in
1989. ``They put it out with a cover, saying: a novel of sorts. To me it's not
a novel of any sort, except in the sense that with any long prose work,
slightly unusual, it's perhaps safer to call it a novel than to present it as a
sort of academic text.''
The book has two themes: the Oscar Slater murder case and Kuppner's upbringing
in Glasgow. It uses the technique of imaginative reconstruction to integrate
the two themes. Is A Very Quiet Street faction - a mixture of fiction and fact
- as in Truman Capote's In Cold Blood? ``It's not faction, it's fact,'' Kuppner
says. ``It's an attempt to get as factual as facts can be.''
Of his next prose book, A Concussed History of Scotland, Kuppner admits: ``It's
a work I have difficulty in categorising, so I'm not surprised that other
people have difficulty in categorising it. It's like prose poetry. Reading
between the lines, I think it was no accident that for a couple of years after
that I didn't get anything else published. In terms of career structure it was
a bad move.''
Polygon couldn't have thought that when they accepted his latest book,
Something Very Like Murder (#8.99), which has won him this year's McVitie's
Prize.
What genre is it? ``It's not a novel of any sort.'' Like A Very Quiet Street,
it's an investigation of a murder case that has strong personal and
autobiographical overtones. It is based on the Willox murder in Glasgow in the
late 1920s.
``There were resonances because it was about a man living alone with his father
because his mother had recently died. My mother had recently died and although
I wasn't exactly living alone with my father, I was going down there and
helping out quite a lot. The murder occurred exactly between where my father's
first TV shop was and where we lived, so I used to cross this street quite
often.''
Why does the motif of murder occur in his two prose works? ``It's a way of
getting into normal life, apart from anything else, because the people who
lived next door and across the street were not recorded. There was no reason to
record their lives, unless something very unusual was about to happen.'' Murder
enquiries require testimonies, with people in the area having to account for
their movements at the time of the crime.
``I went to newspapers to find out stuff about the Willox case, and was
continually being sidetracked by really fascinating snippets of information.
Again, these accounts have to be quite dramatic, otherwise they won't get into
the papers. Nobody's going to say, so and so went out and bought half a dozen
rolls in the morning, unless they get knocked down on the way back.
``It requires a certain element of anomaly in the circumstances before the
normality is recorded. You get a terrific sense of life out of researching
this.''
Our conversation is closing; Kuppner is now going off to a writers' group to
share his gifts. ``I've published seven books, two about murders, but even
that's a gross exaggeration of the time I spend writing about murder cases.
Everything I've ever written about murder cases has been published. Other stuff
has not been published.''
Maybe the McVitie's Prize will change that? ``One tries to chain one's
optimism.''
</TEXT>
