<HEADLINE>Ibrox clash faces replay in court</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES FREEMAN Homes Affairs Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110379</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NUMBER of players from Rangers and Aberdeen football clubs may face court
action over incidents during the November 11 match at Ibrox, it emerged
yesterday.
An SFA disciplinary hearing in Glasgow yesterday suspended Rangers and England
midfield player Paul Gascoigne and his team-mate John Brown for one game.
However, Mr Tony Higgins, secretary of the Scottish Professional Footballers'
Association, said two of the other three players involved had been ``cautioned
by police''.
The men already interviewed were named by Mr Higgins as Alan McLaren of Rangers
and Billy Dodds of Aberdeen. Their caution indicates that there may be a
possibility of further action against them once reports are sent to the
procurator-fiscal.
Mr Higgins also said their cases had not been considered by the SFA because of
the police caution. Millions of television viewers witnessed the two men
clashing during play and a subsequent intervention involving John Brown.
Another Aberdeen player, midfielder Paul Bernard, is also thought to have been
interviewed by police and to have given a statement in relation to an incident
which involved Gascoigne.
The department of the Glasgow procurator-fiscal, Mr Andrew Normand, had called
for the investigation but had not yet received reports.
It will be up to the fiscal to decide which, if any, of the players involved in
the on-field incidents are to be treated as victims and which, if any, as
aggressors. It would also be open to him to take no action.
An SFA spokesman indicated yesterday that Gascoigne, Brown and Alan Lawrence of
Hearts and Sean Sweeney of Airdrie had all been found guilty of ``bringing the
game into disrepute''.
Both Lawrence and Sweeney were given one match bans for on-field bad behaviour.
But it appears the Glasgow procurator-fiscal has not become involved in the
Lawrence case, which involved an incident in an earlier premier division game
at Ibrox and that the fiscal at Perth has no involvement in the Sweeney
incident in which the Airdrie player appeared on television to take a kick at a
prone opponent during a cup semi-final at McDiarmid Park.
This is bound once again to raise doubts over the intervention of fiscals in
some on field incidents but not in others.
In an earlier article in The Herald, lawyers and leading figures in the game
called for a clear policy statement from the Crown Office and a consistent
policy to be applied across the country by every procurator-fiscal.
</TEXT>
