<HEADLINE>Wartime saviour of Jews cleared</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110380</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
St Gallen, Thursday
A SWISS court ended a painful chapter in its nation's history today when it
cleared the name of a police chief convicted 55 years ago of falsifying
documents to rescue up to 3000 Jews from the Nazis.
Jews saved by Paul Grninger, who died a broken man aged 80 in 1972, hailed the
verdict as a victory over racism and intolerance.
``The first lesson is not to be racist or judge people by their origin but to
judge them instead, as Grninger did, for what they are,'' said Harry Weinreb,
74, saved by Grninger in 1938 when he fled German-annexed Austria.
The court president, delivering the verdict in the same courtroom where
Grninger was tried in 1940, said the police chief had acted as an ``emergency
helper'' when he falsified papers to enable Jewish refugees to find sanctuary.
``That's not illegal and therefore he is acquitted,'' he said.
Grninger was police chief in the St Gallen canton, which borders Austria, when
neutral Switzerland closed its frontiers on August 19, 1938, to Jews fleeing
Nazi persecution.
At the same time, the Swiss asked Berlin to stamp the passports of Jews with a
J to make it easier for border guards to recognise them and turn them back.
Obeying his conscience, Grninger began to rescue Jews by falsifying records
and back-dating entry stamps in their papers to mislead authorities into
thinking they had arrived before the border closure. He was sacked in 1939 and
a year later convicted of fraud and fined.
Grninger never found regular work again, drifting from job to job. He was
awarded the Medal of the Just by Israel's Yad Vashem foundation in 1971, but
died a year later still unrecognised by his own            country.
The case has come in the same year, the 50th anniversary of the war's end, that
the Swiss Government has apologised for the first time for its shabby treatment
of Jews before and during the war.
</TEXT>
