<DOCNO>GH951201-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Councils get back some powers `Con trick' claim</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBBIE DINWOODIE, Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110381</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government announced the handing back of a tranche of minor powers to
Scottish local authorities last night as part of plans to undermine demands for
a Scottish Parliament, but the move was immediately condemned by the Opposition
as a con trick.
It was the second time in as many days that measures intended as ``popular
devolution'' by Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth were criticised as too
little too late by opponents.
St Andrew's Day was a constitutional battleground as both the Government and
nationalists sought to steal the thunder of the launch of plans for a Scottish
Parliament by the Scottish Constitutional Convention.
Mr Forsyth began the day with an onslaught on the ``tartan tax'' and he ended
the day in Glasgow with a speech announcing that he would be handing powers
back to local authorities as part of his constitutional campaign.
However, he made clear that his plans to strengthen the Scottish Grand
Committee would not involve giving it powers to vote down any legislation
brought before it.
Labour attacked his announcements. ``Giving a few powers back to local councils
and beefing up old quangos is not real devolution,'' said Shadow Scottish
Secretary George Robertson. ``It's a con trick.
``Given that the Tories have systematically stripped local councils of their
powers over the last 16 years, it's a bit like the burglar who strips your
house from top to bottom and then asks for congratulations when he gives you
back the candlesticks.''
But Mr Forsyth, in his Dick Stewart Memorial Lecture last night, said he wanted
to bring every tier of decision making closer to the people. The current demand
for devolution had been induced, he claimed.
``The devolution hype has, for six and a half years, been orchestrated through
the Constitutional Convention by self-interested politicians for party
advantage.
``Yet sometimes a benefit can indirectly derive from a cynical political
exercise and, provided the people of Scotland have the insight to reject the
base currency of the convention, it is good that they should scrutinise the
genuine coin of government.''
Mr Forsyth said the Convention of Scottish Local Authorities had provided a
list of 52 measures they felt would strengthen councils and he had agreed to
consider more than half of them, rejecting outright only nine. Councils would
now be given block grants and decide for themselves how to cut the cake.
They would regain the power to make local by-laws - ``a radical step in
constitutional terms,'' he claimed. Planning rules would be eased and councils
may in future be allowed to bid for housing being sold off by Scottish Homes.
``Taken together, these ideas amount to a considerable shift in the entire
emphasis of Scottish government, notably in its accountability to our people,''
he said. ``They are the first wave in a tide of reform which can sweep across
the shoreline of government to change the shape of it forever.''
There was a cautious welcome to some of the proposals from Cosla. Senior
vice-president Keith Geddes said they were a step in the right direction, but
they would continue to argue for 16 measures on which there was to be further
consultation.
But he added: ``Council capping is to continue and the case for councils to
have freedom to incur expenditure in the interests of their inhabitants - the
power of general competence - has not been accepted.''
Scottish Liberal Democrat leader Jim Wallace said it was ``a paltry and
inadequate speech''.
The SNP's parliamentary leader, Mrs Margaret Ewing, said that having stripped
local government of 120 powers they had handed a few minor powers back. ``By
hyping these proposals far beyond what they merited Michael Forsyth has brought
ridicule to himself and his Government.''
Both SNP leader Alex Salmond and Mr Robertson focused on the refusal to give
the Scottish Grand Committee the power to vote. But Mr Forsyth said his Labour
opponent was ``foolish'' to go down the road of that argument.
There was a power to create an English Grand Committee, he pointed out, and he
doubted whether a future Labour Government would be happy to see such a body
vote down its legislation should there be a majority of Tory MPs in England and
Wales. ``George Robertson is making a federalist case without realising it,''
he claimed.
</TEXT>
