<HEADLINE>Summit to plan Nigeria sanctions</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From BARRY BAXTER Gaborone, Thursday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110382</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BOTSWANA'S President Ketumile Masire will call a special summit of southern
African leaders to discuss sanctions against Nigeria over the hanging of nine
political activists, presidential secretary Bergsman Sentile said today.
``The meeting is being arranged. We are contacting the heads of states to
arrange a convenient date,'' Sentile said.
South African President Nelson Mandela had asked Masire to convene a summit on
Nigeria in his capacity as current chairman of the 12-nation Southern African
Development Community (SADC).
In Pretoria, a government source said South Africa was confident the summit
would be held within two weeks.
A diplomatic source said the summit was expected to be held in South Africa,
possibly on December 11.
The SADC comprises Angola, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mauritius, Mozambique,
Namibia, South Africa, Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia, and Zimbabwe.
The source in Pretoria said President Mandela wanted to report to the leaders
on initiatives he had taken to put pressure on Nigeria's military rulers after
the hanging earlier this month of the nine minority rights activists.
``What Mandela wanted to do and will do is to report to them on the initiatives
he has taken,'' the source said.
These included telephone conversations with Prime Minister John Major and US
President Bill Clinton urging them to impose a ban on buying Nigerian oil, the
country's most important export.
Mandela also called in top local officials of the Shell oil company, which has
key interests in Nigeria, to demand that Royal Dutch/Shell pull out of Nigeria.
Washington has rejected an oil embargo. Britain, meanwhile, has not ruled out
sanctions against Nigeria's military rulers so long as sanctions did not harm
ordinary Nigerians.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
