<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000113</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000113</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Clowning glory caps a career</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975110383</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was cloth cap and morning dress when veteran comedian Norman Wisdom
collected his OBE from the Queen at Buckingham Palace yesterday.
And the 80-year-old entertainer could not resist a characteristic comic walk to
bring a smile to people's faces.
Norman Wisdom, it seems, finds it difficult to be serious.
But life has not always been such fun for him.
``I was in a bad way when I was a kid,'' he said. ``I've been on my own since I
was nine.''
As a teenager, Wisdom slept rough in doorways around Victoria in London.
At 14 he was a cabin boy in Argentina, and soon after joined the Army, serving
in India in a concert party.
``I owe everything to the Army - it gave me self-discipline and the concert
party was my introduction to show business.''
He attributes his good health and vitality to a strict diet and vigorous
exercise, walking and jogging in the country lanes near his home on the Isle of
Man.
q Film director Alan Parker, 51, who last year attacked the Government over
lack of support for the British film industry, received the CBE.
Mr Parker, who directed box office hits including Mississippi Burning, Midnight
Express and The Commitments, began working life as an advertising copywriter.
He is currently working in Argentina on the film Evita starring Madonna.
q Sheila McKechnie, 46, director of the Consumers' Association and former head
of the housing charity Shelter, received the OBE.
</TEXT>
