<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lecturer queries oil firms' safety figures</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110384</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTTISH university lecturer yesterdayalleged that an ``incomplete view'' of
offshore safety had been presented by industry chiefs to remove the problem
from public scrutiny.
He also said a Health and Safety Executive study published earlier this week,
which claimed offshore safety was improving, was misleading.
Oil chiefs have spent about #1500m on safety in the wake of the Piper Alpha
tragedy, and maintain that safety is of paramount importance.
According to figures used by the UK Offshore Operators' Association (UKOOA),
the extraction of oil and gas comes 22nd in a ranking of reported industrial
injury rates.
But Dr Charles Woolfson, an industrial relations lecturer at Glasgow
University, and Dr Matthias Beck, an economics lecturer at St Andrews
University, claim the offshore industry is consistently the second or third
most dangerous industry after mining.
Dr Woolfson and Dr Beck, who say that their views are independent of any
organisation, argue that the picture is very different when rates of fatalities
and serious injuries are assessed.
Dr Woolfson said there had been an average of 89.9 fatalities and serious
injuries in the offshore oil industry since 1985, excluding Piper Alpha, and
400 lives lost in the industry since 1970.
But he said the oil companies' figures, which made the industry appear to be
much safer than it really was, included all reported injuries in the petroleum
sector including onshore management and office workers, as well as those
offshore.
Dr Woolfson said their was still much unease about the way new safety measures
were implemented. Many employees believed safety considerations had been
hijacked by oil companies and that the HSE had been virtually neutered because
of company demands.
He argued any reconstruction of offshore safety which did not have a
legitimised role for trade union-appointed safety representatives amounted to
an ``incomplete safety regime''.
Testimonials taken by Dr Woolfson and Dr Beck from workers on the Brent Charlie
rig suggested they were deeply sceptical about the way HSE regulations were
enforced.
But a UKOOA spokesman last night claimed that Dr Woolfsoon and Dr Beck had been
``very selective'' in their use of statistics.
The report coincided with the industry embarking on an unprecedented move aimed
at improving its public image in the wake of the summer controversy sparked by
Shell's controverial plan to sink its obsolete Brent Spar installation.
In a calculated bid to wrest the initiative away from environmental groups such
as Greepeace, 37 top oil and gas exploration and production companies yesterday
set out an agreed approach for an open discussion on how unwanted offshore
installations should be decommissioned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
