<DOCNO>GH951201-000115</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Palestine calls for closer ties with Scottish `twin'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110385</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE senior Palestinian envoy to the United Kingdom last night called for closer
links between Scotland and the Middle Eastern land.
Mr Afif Safieh, general delegate to the UK and ambassador to the Vatican, was
speaking before a lecture organised by the General Union of Palestine Students
in Glasgow. More than 100 people turned up for the talk.
He said Glasgow and the city of Bethlehem already had close links and a
``dormant'' twinning arrangement was due to be ``revitalised''. The Israeli
security and military authorities are due to withdraw from Bethlehem in three
weeks.
Mr Safieh said the two cities had been linked for about three years and a
closer relationship could benefit both Scotland and Palestine.
He said Scotland could reap the economic rewards of helping Palestine to
rebuild after decades of conflict.
Mr Safieh said: ``I hope for a reactivation of links between Glasgow and
Bethlehem on all fronts, from the City Chambers to the universities, churches,
trade union movement and all other relevant institutions. I want the links to
be strategic and long-term and to the mutual benefit of both countries.''
He said tourism would become a key industry in Palestine, particularly in
Bethlehem during the year 2000.
Mr Safieh added: ``Palestine will be flooded with pilgrims and tourists and a
lot of investment is needed. After years of stagnation we have to engineer the
economic take-off of Palestine and tourism is going to be a major component of
that.
``There is room for co-ordination between Glasgow and Bethlehem and I would
welcome any delegation from Scotland to see the opportunities for themselves.''
Mr Safieh reassured Scotland's Jewish community that the peace process would be
pushed forward.
He made no official comment of the current wrangles over bringing the Lockerbie
bombing suspects to justice and the question of Scottish self-government. But,
stressing he was speaking on a personal level, he said the deadlock over a
trial for the Libyan Lockerbie suspects may be broken by setting up a Scottish
court, under the auspices of the British embassy in The Hague.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Surgeon in bid to save ailing leader British doctor says Papandreou still has chance</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Athens, Thursday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110386</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TOP doctor flown in from Britain to help treat ailing Greek Prime Minister
Andreas Papandreou, hooked up to life-support systems, tonight said he still
had a fighting chance.
``There is a chance of the Prime Minister recovering,'' said Sir Magdi Yacoub,
the British surgeon who performed open heart surgery on Papandreou in 1988 and
who was called in to see him.
Professor Yacoub told reporters that Papandreou's recovery would not be
``immediate or in the very near future'', but doctors were hopeful.
Yacoub, who is based at Harefield Hospital, Middlesex, was flown to Greece by
the Prime Minister's personal plane accompanied by Harefield anaesthetist Dr
Gavin Wright and a renal expert.
Yacoub gave Papandreou a triple heart by-pass in 1988.
He was the last in a series of foreign specialists flown in to see Papandreou,
76, who was admitted to the Onassis Heart Centre 10 days ago suffering from
pneumonia.
The country's first socialist leader has been kept alive by a respirator to
help his breathing and a dialysis machine supporting his kidneys.
The latest medical bulletin, issued this evening, said his condition was
unchanged and he was still on life-support machines.
``The situation of the Prime Minister's health has not changed in the last six
hours. He had dialysis, which he tolerated well and his breathing is still
being supported by a respirator,'' said a statement.
Earlier, hospital spokes-man Gregory Skalkeas said Papandreou's heart was
working properly and that there was still hope he would recover.
``The premier can't breathe on his own,'' Skalkeas said. ``His heart is working
properly and he is responding to the treatment for his lungs and kidneys. This
tells us there is hope that the premier will recover.''
Hundreds of supporters have camped outside the hospital for days. Today is the
feast of St Andrew's Day when Papandreou celebrates his name day - equivalent
to a birthday in Greece - and many brought flowers and sweets to the hospital
steps.
Senior socialist politicians have kept silent in public on the question of
choosing a successor to the man who founded the Panhellenic Socialist Movement
(Pasok) in 1974.
However party sources said wheeling and dealing was intense and it would
probably boil down to a contest between Defence Minister Gerassimos Arsenis and
former Industry Minister Costas Simitis.
Both have solid pockets of support in the 170-member socialist parliamentary
group, which will pick the replacement for Papandreou if he can no longer carry
out his duties.
It was later announced that Interior Minister and Papandreou confidant Akis
Tsohatzopoulos would stand in for the premier at the EU summit in Madrid in two
weeks' time.
DUBAI: King Fahd of Saudi Arabia, ruler of the world's richest oil producer,
was in hospital in Riyadh for check-ups today. The court made the announcement
but did not reveal whether the 73-year-old king was ill.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000117</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000117</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dawn of new barbarism</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By Peter McDougall</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110387</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Peter McDougall does not look like a likely candidate for a random assault. Nor
does his well-built son Willie. Yet before midnight last Saturday, on a busy
suburban Glasgow thoroughfare, they were suddenly attacked for no other reason
than that they were `there'. Violence runs through some of the playwright's
best-known work. It was there in the Prix Italia-winning Just Another Saturday
and in his adaptation of the Jimmy Boyle autobiography A Sense Of Freedom. But
it is never used gratuitously. Here the writer, who abhors violence, reflects
on brutality at large today
VIOLENCE is endemic today and it's not just a Glasgow problem. It's a national
problem. Urban towns now have their no-go areas as well.
The terrifying thing about it for an ordinary person is that it is so arbitrary
in the way it comes about. It's almost like you're waiting your turn. When's
your number going to come up. There is something inevitable about it.
You're not talking about gangsters or gang wars . . . people saying `OK let's
go and fight against them'. You are no longer talking about the classic idea
that violence is some kind of phenomenon that is restricted to the working
class . . . hard men that work down the pits . . . have a fight on a Saturday
night . . . and go back to their work first thing on a Monday morning. You are
talking about people from a different planet.
Young people have been spiritually bankrupted. They are totally
disenfranchised. There is nothing for them to do at all. Arnold Schwarzenegger
couldn't frighten these kids.
The only other time I experienced the same sort of problem was during the
Edinburgh Festival a few years back. The only difference was there was more
warning.
[McDougall and his girlfriend were followed down the Grassmarket by jeering
youths who eventually launched a frenzied attack. They escaped into a pub.
McDougall suffered minor injuries.]
I'm sure it basically stemmed from the same hopelessness that breeds a complete
lack of concern for anyone else. A woman was involved. It didn't make the
slightest difference. It was the same kind of crazed people.
You can intellectualise all you want about social and moral disintegration -
but the fact is that there have always been bad bastards about. They are not
going to go away. They are on the increase. The reason for that is sociological
and political. The increase in random, motiveless attacks is forcing us to
confront the problem. It is chilling.
To take pleasure out of hurting somebody seems perverse. I cannae understand
it. But to them it's become the norm. One of the great mistakes we constantly
make is that we judge them on our moral standards without realising that their
whole culture is without morals. We constantly judge things on how we'd react
ourselves . . . on what we would do in a particular situation. Then you realise
it's a hopeless task because they are not like us. They don't feel the same way
at all.
If you read a tabloid leader after an old lady has been beaten-up they say
things like, `I hope those cowards wake-up in the morning and feel bad'. They
don't feel bad. That idea of a `coward' is as old-fashioned as the British
Empire. These guys would attack a dozen policemen. One wee guy would attack a
dozen policemen.
A pal of mine who is a huge guy and as hard as they come told me he's been
attacked three times recently. You'd have to be mad to attack him. From our
perspective you would never attack him. But the new breed of thugs don't think
like that. They come from a different culture. A branch of society which has
been totally spurned.
You're not talking about an underclass. You are talking about kids that have
been brutalised to the degree that they don't know the difference between right
and wrong. Conscience doesn't exist anymore. It's the new barbarism. The real
legacy of Thatcherism - psychopathy.
They say there hasn't been a war for 50 years. The truth is World War Three has
been going on and nobody's twigged it. The disenfranchised and underprivileged
might as well be living in an occupied country.
I lived in New York for a bit 10 years ago when there was a backlash against
muggers. It could happen here soon. Maybe a year from now somebody'll break
into a car. People won't just phone the police, they'll run out and beat the
guy to death. And they'll get off with it because the guy was breaking into a
car and he's got a criminal record.
Drink comes into it. When you watch a series like Redcaps on the telly every
single violent incident is drink-related. If people feel completely and utterly
hopeless one of the ways of getting over it is through drinking or using drugs.
Everyone knows that drinking makes people aggressive. Drinking and violence go
together. But there was a time when even guys that drank would leave civilians
alone. They wouldnae attack somebody in the street. They might say daft things
to them but they would never attack somebody who was obviously a civilian and
didnae belong to their culture.
That's changed completely. Anybody's fair game. Including old women of 85 and
86. Every second week there's a photograph in the paper of their bruised faces.
It's no' enough to terrorise an old woman into telling them where her money is.
They've got to leave their mark. It's barbaric.
With Howard as the so-called Home Secretary, they are talking through their
arse. Nothing touches them. Nothing reaches them. They know nothing about
anything. It's that terrifying inability to project themselves into any
environment other than their own.
They can't see anything. At least a writer has actually got to project himself
into something in order to actually write about it. Howard's supposed to be in
charge of various things, like the prison service and making changes to
sentences, but he can only think about it intellectually. He has no real
understanding of what's involved.
There should be more polis on the beat. Squad cars used to be great. You could
phone one and, if your're lucky, it might get there in time to prevent anything
happening. There doesn't seem to be the kind of presence any more . . .
`There's a copper on the corner. Watch what your daein.'
</TEXT>
