<HEADLINE>Allies hamper inquiry</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>EXCLUSIVE By IAN BRUCE Defence Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110388</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Serb war crimes hidden
THE United States, Germany and France are withholding vital evidence of Serb
atrocities in Bosnia from the international commission they helped set up last
year to prosecute war criminals in the former Yugoslavia.
Nato sources claim that key satellite, telecommunications and photographic
intelligence which could implicate individuals such as Bosnian Serb military
commander Ratko Mladic in the massacre of Muslim civilians is being suppressed
deliberately to help keep the peace process on track.
Two days ago, the UN confirmed that 5500 Muslim former inhabitants and
defenders of the ``safe haven'' of Srebrenica, which fell to the advancing
Serbs in July, are missing amid growing evidence of mass executions.
Now Judge Richard Goldstone, the war crimes' commission's chief prosecutor, has
written to all three governments to complain about lack of co-operation and
express disappointment about ``the timeliness and quality of information''
supplied.
A copy of one of the letters, addressed to the legal adviser at the US Embassy
in The Hague, has come into The Herald's possession. In it, Judge Goldstone
speaks of ``serious problems'' in the flow of evidence, citing delays of
between two and 11 months.
Much of what has been released, particularly by the Americans, has been
``open-source'' material, available to the media, although sometimes not
directly to the commission. The publication of photographs of alleged mass
grave sites near Srebrenica in the summer is one example.
Sources say that the United Kingdom, America's principal intelligence partner,
has been cut out of the information loop on Bosnia since September last year,
when Britain accused the CIA of interfering on the side of the Sarajevo
government.
France was also excluded from the US information flow, but continued to collect
its own intelligence by intercepting telecommunications and through its own
military in Bosnia.
The French told General Bernard Janvier, the United Nations Protection Force
commander in Bosnia, that the Serbs planned a massive assault on the remaining
three safe havens - Srebrenica, Zepa and Gorazde - several weeks in advance of
this.
However, it was made clear to him that his briefing was purely on the basis of
his seniority within the French military hierarchy, and not as UNPROFOR
commander. The UN headquarters in Zagreb maintains it had no advance warning of
the Serb onslaught in July.
Two months earlier, General Janvier asked a closed session of the UN Security
Council to be relieved of responsibility for protection of the besieged
enclaves. Between July 5, when the attack opened, and July 11, when Serb forces
smashed their way into Srebrenica, he also denied five separate requests by the
local Dutch UNPROFOR commander for Nato air strikes.
The Germans, too, allegedly had a major role to play.
The German intelligence service, the BND, had access to about 90% of US
intelligence data, but also operated its own listening post in the Austrian
Alps north of Slovenia - ostensibly run by the Austrian Army.
US-German co-operation reached the stage last year that a joint BND/CIA/
National Security Agency surveillance centre was opened secretly in Augsburg in
southern Germany to deal with developments in former Yugoslavia.
A number of Nato sources are convinced that the US-BND teams intercepted
telephone conversations between the Serb Army chief of staff, General Momcilo
Perisic and General Ratko Mladic, before the attack, and during the massacre of
civilians which followed.
In addition, the Americans are understood to have both satellite and video
footage of some of the atrocities from their unmanned Predator reconnaissance
drones beamed to their base on the Dalmatian island of Drac.
Dole backs troops.................12
</TEXT>
