<HEADLINE>Sharp blames council changes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110389</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STRATHCLYDE Chief Constable Leslie Sharp spelled out yesterday for the first
time why he is leaving the force early.
Attending his last meeting of the region police and fire committee, he told
members: ``I do not agree with the changes in local government which have come
about in respect of the way they affect the police.''
He also spoke about changes in conditions of service and related pay for police
officers. The whole situation, he said, appeared to be a ``dangerous path''.
If Strathclyde region had remained in being, the authority might have
``squeezed a few more years'' out of him. As it was, he would be leaving at the
end of the year, allowing the new chief constable, Mr John Orr, three months to
``get his feet under the table''.
Recalling his period of service with Strathclyde as ``the happiest
four-and-a-half years of my service'', he said the results achieved had
exceeded anything by any other force in the country since the war.
``We have walked a tightrope together amazingly,'' he told members. ``Progress
has been staggering. People threw at me the appalling crime situation and the
appalling lack of policing in some areas. We have made progress beyond my
wildest dreams. Strathclyde has become a shining beacon in terms of law and
order.''
Mr Sharp declined to amplify his remarks after the committee meeting, but
Deputy Chief Constable James Richardson spoke of the chief's outstanding
qualities of leadership, and the fresh approach he took to policing.
q Some rural areas in the West of Scotland face ``unacceptable delays'' in
response to emergencies, with increased risk to life and property, says
Strathclyde Firemaster John Jameson.
Acknowledging criticism of ``failure to respond'' by some units, Mr Jameson
said in an intermediate report by HM Inspectorate of Fire Services that
changing patterns of work were causing severe problems.
``In areas such as those mentioned by the inspectorate, we use retained
personnel, with pagers. Increasingly, people move out of a village to find
work. We have problems recruiting suitable people locally.
``We also find employers, and some local authorities, can't or won't release
people to attend call-outs. When there was a train crash at Largs recently, a
man was sacked when he turned out and was late for work.
``If we cannot cope properly with changing work patterns and tight constraints,
we would have to consider more full-time people - with implications for finance
for the new unitary authorities.''
</TEXT>
