<HEADLINE>Authority of toll collector  is disputed Lawyers query Skye Bridge document EXCLUSIVE By DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110390</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE operators of the Skye Bridge may not have the legal right to collect tolls
even though more than 36,000 motorists have paid since the bridge opened on
October 16.
Under the New Roads and Street Works Act 1991, the Secretary of State's right
is unquestionable, but opposition MPs will call on the Government to prove that
right has been competently transferred to Skye Bridge Ltd. There is legal
opinion the matter can only be resolved in a court of law.
The uncertainty arises from the phrasing of the legal document in which the
Secretary of State assigned his rights. Mr Forsyth assigned the rights to a
company which no longer exists.
The possible difficulty with this Assignation Statement came to light when toll
opponent Robbie the Pict, formerly Mr Brian Robertson, attempted to cross the
bridge.
When asked for his #4.30 toll, Robbie had requested the toll collector to show
``. . . his assignation order or whatever documents he believed both identified
him and his employees as lawfully empowered by a warrant issued by the
Secretary of State to collect tolls on this road.''
The Toll Order was produced first which did not satisfy Robbie. ``The document
failed to identify either him or his company as a `Special Roads Authority'.''
An Assignation Statement was eventually faxed from the Scottish Office, but it
did not satisfy either.
The Herald also obtained a copy of the Assignation Statement from the Scottish
Office. In Section Two, under Identity of the Concessionaire (Regulation 3
(a)), it states:
``It is proposed that the Concessionaire will be Skye Bridge Tolls Limited,
incorporated under the Companies Acts and having their registered office at
Miller House, 18 South Groathill Avenue, Edinburgh and their permitted
successors and assignees in accordance with the Concession Agreement.''
Skye Bridge Tolls Ltd was the company originally set up by bridge builders
Miller/Dywidag and their financiers, the Bank of America, but it was replaced
more than two years ago by Skye Bridge Ltd. What is not clear from the
Assignation Statement is whether: it was ever more than ``proposed'' that Skye
Bridge Tolls Ltd should be assigned the toll rights; and if so whether they
were ever properly transferred to Skye Bridge Ltd as permitted successors and
assignees.
A Scottish Office spokesman said this week that all rights and responsibilities
had been passed on to Skye Bridge Ltd which now had the clear legal right to
charge tolls.
But Professor Neil MacCormick, who holds the chair of Public Law and is Provost
of the Law and Social Science Faculty Group at Edinburgh University, said
yesterday these were matters of fact in law which could only be put beyond
question in a court of law.
``The use of language such as `it is proposed' suggests they may have confused
intention for accomplished fact, and the whole thing is clouded by obscurity,''
Professor MacCormick said.
Edinburgh solicitor Mr David Brittain, who is researching the position of the
toll bridge in civil law, agreed: ``There may be other papers and documents,
but as far as I can see what we have here is nothing more than a proposal and
not a proper assignation. Clearly the Secretary of State has the right to
charge tolls, but there is nothing in this document to say Skye Bridge Ltd have
that right.''
Robbie himself is clear: ``Where the operation involves both detaining the
public and demanding monies, the identification of the legitimately warranted
party should be `ad littera', meeting at least the same standards of accuracy
as required in the registration of trademarks.''
Labour's Highlands and Islands spokesman, Mr John McFall, said last night: ``I
will certainly be tabling questions. Given the controversy that continues to
attend the bridge and its imposition, any doubt over the legal position must be
examined.''
Ross, Cromarty and Skye MP Charles Kennedy said: ``I will be writing to Michael
Forsyth saying that here we have a heaven-sent opportunity to test his new
arrangements for the Scottish Grand Committee and that we should invite the
Lord Advocate along so we can question him on this issue.''
</TEXT>
