<HEADLINE>Students and workers cause turmoil French cities in a jam as strikes bite</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From PAUL TAYLOR Paris, Thursday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110391</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WIDENING public transport strikes and demonstrations plunged French cities into
vast traffic jams as action against planned welfare cuts, now in its seventh
day, spread to post, electricity, and gas services.
At least 100,000 railwaymen, public employees, and students demonstrated in a
dozen cities, according to police estimates. Some demanded the resignation of
conservative Prime Minister Alain Juppe.
However, despite the most serious labour unrest since 1986, government
spokesman Alain Lamassoure said the Cabinet would stick to unpopular plans to
reform the social security system.
With 325 miles of traffic jams in the Paris region alone, many workers spent
hours trying to reach their workplace.
The Paris Metro and suburban trains were completely shut for the first day
since the strike began. National rail services were at a standstill for a
seventh straight day except for six trains to London and three to Brussels.
Trade unions decided to extend both the rail and Metro strikes at least until
tomorrow night. Transport Minister Bernard Pons is due to meet rail union
leaders tomorrow afternoon.
The mounting disruption hit industry and took its toll on the franc.
Dealers said the markets were beginning to question Juppe's ability to hold the
line on deficit cuts vital if French is to join a single European currency in
1999.
Gilles de Robien, the leader of the house in parliament, said President Jacques
Chirac might call a referendum or an early general election if the labour
unrest worsened.
The CNPF employers' federation urged the centre-right government to stick to
its austerity plans, but said the strikes were having a serious impact on
companies and must be ended soon.
Officials said the government appeared to be playing for time, counting on
public opinion turning against the strikes and exhaustion setting in before the
Christmas holidays.
The state power utility EDF-GDF said it made a few isolated electricity cuts to
industry owing to a 24-hour stoppage by staff protesting against European Union
plans to open the electricity sector to competition.
Rail and electricity workers marched in Paris, Marseilles, Lyons, Toulouse,
Nantes, Rennes, Brest, Grenoble, and Bordeaux.
Students staged a new day of action, with marches around France to protest
against overcrowding and underfunding.
Three policemen were injured in clashes with masked youths in the western city
of Nantes. There was also a brief clash between youths and riot police who
fired a few tear gas grenades as a 10,000-strong student demonstration marched
through Paris.
The strikes widened to postal services, hitting 50 out of 139 sorting centres,
and to provincial public transport. And road haulage unions urged members to
take action.
There were first signs of action spreading to state-owned France Telecom, where
the communist-led CGT union said 30 out of 1000 centres were on strike. The CGT
also said it had called stoppages at carmaker Renault from early next week. -
Reuter.
</TEXT>
