<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tories rally against tax</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110392</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Office Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton joined Fife Conservatives
to take part in a demonstration in St Andrews yesterday against the proposed
plans for a Scottish parliament.
Around 30 protesters, including the party's North-East Fife prospective
parliamentary candidate, Mr Adam Bruce, marched through the town.
At a rally, Lord James said that a ``tartan tax'' would discriminate against
everyone in Scotland.
He added: ``It is extremely important that we make the people of Scotland aware
how much the tartan tax will cost them.
``This is a tax that is contrary to Scottish interests, that would be damaging
to her economy, and that would drive away inward investment.''
Mr Bruce said the tax would ``impoverish the people of North-East Fife and
drive away jobs''.
</TEXT>
