<DOCNO>GH951201-000123</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000123</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Poker chip on the peace talks table</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Margaret Vaughan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110393</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN the Prevention of Terrorism Act was introduced in 1974 it was in the wake
of the Birmingham bombings. Days after rescuers were seen picking through
rubble for bits of bodies in a shattered pub, the Labour Government rushed
through the emergency powers.
The then Home Secretary Roy Jenkins described it as a draconian and oppressive
law introduced in response to a civil crisis. He viewed it as a vital measure
to empower police.
What it meant was that they could detain terrorist suspects for up to seven
days and to place exclusion orders on individuals thought to have connections
with proscribed organisations. It became, along with the Emergency Provisions
Act, which enshrined the non-jury Diplock Courts, the twin pillar of Britain's
anti-terrorist legislation.
It was always intended to be a temporary measure with the provisions of both
Acts subject to annual review. Now, some 21 years later, with a ceasefire
holding, it remains in force.
Yesterday's ruling by the European Court of Justice that the operation of the
exclusion orders contained in the Act breaches EU laws brought a swift response
from the Home Secretary.
He concludes that the court did not say the PTA was wrong, merely that
adjustments should be made to procedures for issuing exclusion orders. And
this, on Mr Howard's interpretation, means that suspected terrorists will have
to be held in custody while an independent assessment is made of an order. At
present those issued with an order are generally put on the first flight out of
Britain, or remain at liberty in Northern Ireland.
The legal challenge was mounted by a former Republican activist, John
Gallagher, who was excluded from Britain as a suspected terrorist. Ruling in
his favour, the court sitting in Luxembourg declared that the operation of
procedures for exclusion orders was a breach of freedom of movement, guaranteed
by the Treaty of Rome. A similiar case, brought by Sinn Fein leader Gerry
Adams, was withdrawn earlier this year, after he was finally allowed into
Britain.
In the summer, six days before the first anniversary of the IRA ceasefire,
Northern Ireland Secretary Sir Patrick Mayhew, renewing the emergency law and
order provisions for the Province, promised an early independent review of the
Prevention of Terrorism Act.
But it would be set up only once a ``lasting peace'' was established he
insisted. Since the ceasefire, he told MPs, there had been 131 punishment
beatings, 62 attributed to loyalists and 69 to republicans.
The Government was ``not going to drop its guard prematurely''. It was an echo
of the Home Secretary's stance in March when he defended the decision to renew
the Act for a further 12 months, saying the Government was not prepared to do
anything which would expose people to unnecessary risk.
However, he announced the lifting of a further 16 exclusion orders that bar
people in Northern Ireland from coming to the mainland.
Figures released two years ago showed that of those held under the terms of the
PTA, 3% were charged with terror offences, 5% with other offences, and 4% were
excluded or deported. Around 90% of those detained under the Act are released
without charge.
Critics argue that while it may once have been an effective means of gaining
information on the activities of others, it played straight into the hands of
the IRA. It was seen as a recruiting sergeant for the terrorism organisations,
who could say to those detained that there is no justice under British laws.
This, it was argued, had a resonance with people, making them fearful of giving
information to the police in case they were held for interrogation. A study by
academics from the School of Law at King's College, London, published earlier
this year, Terrorism And The Rule of Law, found that, from the perspective of
the police, the PTA was not strictly needed.
The authorities no longer haul suspects in to be interrogated, the authors
said. The emphasis now is on intelligence, careful surveillance, and forensic
proof. Suspects are apprehended red-handed rather than pulled in on instinct.
The authors also claim that the law has moved on, with the introduction of an
Act in 1989 which transforms the power of the police in Northern Ireland,
giving them far more ordinary power with which to counter serious crime,
including serious terrorist crime.
At the time the PTA was first enacted it was against a background of a common
law on police powers that was uncertain, ambiguous, and often illogically
restrictive. With ordinary law now allowing wide powers of search and arrest
and authorising four-day detention without charge, the PTA was being deployed
more because it is known than because it is needed, they said.
There were indications early this year from Home Office sources that Michael
Howard was considering suspending the exclusion powers while the ceasefire
held. Nothing happened. It may well be therefore that the Act, in all its
constituent parts, is being viewed as one of the poker chips in the peace talks.
</TEXT>
