<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Royal train firm set for sale to Americans</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110394</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE company which moves the Royal Train - and runs Royal Mail trains and many
football specials - is set to be sold to an American firm, according to the
Labour Party last night.
Rail Express Systems, a British Rail subsidiary, is due to become one of the
first train operating companies to be privatised, a British Railways Board
spokesman confirmed.
But he would not confirm the report by Labour transport spokesman Brian Wilson
that the only company involved in the negotiations is Wisconsin Railways, a
major US freight train operator.
``It is a further Tory humiliation for Britain that we need Americans to own
and operate the engines which pull the Royal Train, the Royal Mail and football
specials,'' Mr Wilson said.
A Labour Party spokesman said they had been passed a copy of a letter from Mr
Charles Belcher, managing director of Rail Express Systems, telling staff that
a management buy-out team was ``not the preferred bidder'' for the firm.
That left the Wisconsin company as the only potential buyer still under
consideration, the Labour spokesman said.
The BR spokesman said he could confirm that the letter, dated November 24, was
``genuine''.
Rail Express Systems did not own the Royal Train, he said. As the only train
operating company licensed for the entire network, it was responsible for
arranging its movements when needed, and sometimes for providing the
locomotives.
The Royal Train carriages would continue to belong to Railtrack, which was
currently publicly owned, the BRB spokesman said.
The plan to sell Rail Express Systems was announced in January, when the
Government invited ``expressions of interest''.
The company was said then to have 720 staff, 161 diesel and electric
locomotives, 133 travelling Post Office carriages and 400 general purpose rail
vans.
Labour's Brian Wilson called for the RES sale to be put on hold until the full
implications had been examined.
``This has been a successful operation in which a great deal of taxpayers'
money has been invested,'' he said.
``Britain is the country which gave railways to the world. Now the world is
being handed our railways. What sense or logic is there in this whole process?''
A Buckingham Palace spokesman said it had no comment on the reported sell-off,
as rail privatisation was a matter for the Department of Transport.
A department spokesman said: ``It has been uppermost in the minds of both BR
and the department that the utmost importance is attached to ensuring that the
change of ownership will have no prejudicial effect on the safety, security or
the efficient operation of the Royal Train - or any other trains operated by
RES.''
The sale was expected to go ahead before the end of the year, but he could give
no details of prospective buyers, he said.
</TEXT>
