<DOCNO>GH951201-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>UVF ready for action, court told</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110396</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LOYALIST para-military force was keeping itself in a state of readiness in
the event of the end of the ceasefire in Northern Ireland, a court heard
yesterday.
A senior Royal Ulster Constabulary intelligence officer told the High Court in
Glasgow that the Ulster Volunteer Force was still gathering arms, although it
had not used them.
Detective Inspector Paul Hamlyn, 38, said: ``Intelligence would indicate they
are still going about their business, although there's no violence whatsoever.''
Mr Hamlyn was giving evidence on the seventh day of the trial of six men who
deny conspiracy, gun-running and drug trafficking on behalf of the UVF.
They include Mr Lindsay Robb, from Lurgan, a Progressive Unionist Party
politician, who met Ulster Minister Michael Ancram for peace talks in June.
The court has heard that one of the accused, Mr John Johnston, 49, organised
dances and raffles in his home town area of Falkirk, to raise money for the
Loyalist Prisoners' Welfare Association.
Mr Hamlyn said the LPWA was not a registered charity; it looked after the needs
of imprisoned members of the UVF and their families, providing money, food
parcels and clothing or whatever was needed. Each battalion was responsible for
collecting its own money, and a certain proportion was sent to brigade
headquarters.
He admitted he did not know whether any of the cash it raised went towards
buying arms.
Earlier yesterday the court heard Mr Robb's girlfriend, Ms Margaret Glen, 33,
give evidence that he was with her on the evening of June 22 at her home in
Airdrie.
The prosecution have alleged that Mr Robb was in a pub in Laurieston that night
and took a gun out of his bag and placed it under a man's knee.
Mr John Johnston, 49, Mr Francis Hives, 45, of Liverpool, Mr William McArthur,
41, of Bonnybridge, Mr David White, 29, of Airdrie, Mr Alexander Davidson, 23
and Mr Lindsay Robb, 28, both from Lurgan, deny conspiring to further by
criminal means the aims of the UVF.
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
