<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000127</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000127</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scotland faces  record demands on Aids resources</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON DANIELS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110397</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE number of new Aids and HIV cases diagnosed by the end of the year in
Scotland will be higher than in any other year since the infection first came
to prominence in the 1980s, an expert has predicted.
The warning came on the eve of World Aids Day and has major implications for
health care authorities, support services and charities.
Dr David Goldberg, deputy director of the Scottish centre for infection and
environmental health based at Glasgow's Ruchill Hospital, said yesterday that
up to the end of September 114 new Aids cases had been registered. He said to
date the highest annual number of cases had totalled 124.
He predicted that the number of newly diagnosed HIV cases would total around
200, the highest since 1987.
However, he said these figures did not mean the number of infections were
rising but that those infected during the 1980s had now become ill. ``The
demand on health care with respect to HIV and Aids will now be greater than
ever.''
Dr Goldberg said analysis of the latest figures and a number of academic
studies painted a varied picture of Aids and HIV infection in Scotland. He said
that while half of Scotland's 2338 people with HIV were drug users there had
been a marked decline in new infections since the mid-1980s.
He attributed this to the success of needle exchange schemes and methadone
programmes. The doctor said the spread of the infections in the heterosexual
population had stabilised.
But he said of most concern was the continuing rise in new infections among the
gay population.
His comments came as the Scottish Health Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton
warned against complacency. The Minister said the purpose of World Aids Day,
organised by the World Health Organisation and the National Aids Trust, was to
draw attention to the problem.
``Complacency in any sector of the community is a real threat in the fight
against Aids and HIV.''
A number of events are being held across the UK today including a vigil in
Edinburgh.
EXCLUSIVE
</TEXT>
