<DOCNO>GH951201-000129</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000129</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish courts put more behind bars</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RON MacKENNA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110399</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE hard-line reputation of Scotland's criminal courts has been upheld by the
latest government figures showing record numbers of people being imprisoned.
Almost 16,000 people were given custodial sentences after conviction in 1994, a
5% increase on previous levels and, according to the Scottish Office, the
highest figure recorded.
The trend was heavily criticised yesterday by the Labour Party and pressure
groups.
Critics are alarmed by the way young men dominate the figures, culled from the
Statistical Bulletin. One in four males aged 17 in 1989 had been convicted of a
crime in the six-year period up to 1994.
However, the increased use of prison is set against the backdrop of a falling
caseload for courts. The number of court cases fell by 3%.
The Scottish figures confirm statistics produced by the Council of Europe which
show that Scotland's judges jail a higher percentage of the population than
their counterparts in most western European countries.
Labour's home affairs spokesman, Mr John McFall, said: ``We have to ask why we
are top of the league in imprisoning our people, and particularly so many of
our young population.
``One quarter of young men have a conviction. What kind of society are we
fostering? This, after 17 years of Conservative government, is a condemnation
of their approach.
``We need a change in attitude. The answer is not to throw people in jail. What
is prison for? We do imprison people who deserve to be in prison, but should
not be filling jails just for the sake of it.''
Ms Carole Ewart, of the Scottish Council for Civil Liberties, said custodial
sentences were not the answer in many cases. ``Our view is that too many people
are sent to prison and it doesn't work,'' she said.
The rise in the percentage of custodial sentences is, according to the
bulletin, partly because of the increased use of prison sentences for crimes of
dishonesty.
Release of the spirit -- 18
</TEXT>
