<DOCNO>GH951201-000130</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Professor calls for ban on all beef offals</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110400</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LEADING brain disease expert has warned that ``mad cow disease'' could be
transmitting to humans.
Neuropathologist Professor Sir Bernard Tomlinson says there is growing evidence
that the human equivalent of the disease can be caught from infected beef
products.
His warning comes after reports that at least three farmers and three teenagers
have been struck down by Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (CJD).
Sir Bernard outlines his fears in an interview with BBC Radio 4 lunchtime
consumer programme You and Yours which is due to be broadcast just after noon
today.
He calls for a ban on all beef offals.
Sir Bernard, who headed an inquiry into the future of London hospitals, says he
no longer eats meat pies or beef liver and ``at the moment'' would not eat a
burger ``under any circumstances''.
Sir Bernard says: ``The involvement of farmers and the involvement of young
people have made me look again at the whole problem and change my mind to the
feeling that we might now have an association.
``I don't think it's stronger than that with BSE but it is now possible that
BSE is transmitting to humans.''
He adds: ``There's clearly an economic price to pay but . . . until we know the
answer, until we can say quite positively there really is no evidence now that
BSE transfers to humans, until we can say that, I believe we've got to pay that
price and all offal should be kept from public consumption.''
The Government continues to stress that there is no proven link between BSE and
CJD and it says the numbers of cases of BSE are falling year on year.
But the You and Yours' report says cattle most likely to die from BSE were born
in 1987 - when their feed was most toxic.
There are fears that young people may now be at risk because the burgers they
ate in the late 1980s were the most highly contaminated.
The Ministry of Agriculture Fisheries and Food (Maff) has recently clamped down
on slaughterhouses in an effort to ensure that certain offals already banned do
not leak into the food chain.
Earlier this week Maff further strengthened controls by banning cattle
backbones, used in meat pies and sausages, from the food chain.
</TEXT>
