<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000131</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000131</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Blair promises a vote on tax</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN Political Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110401</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR leader Tony Blair last night stepped into the ``tartan tax'' debate by
emphasising that a Scottish parliament's tax-raising powers would only be used
with the approval of the electorate.
His intervention, designed to distract from Scottish Secretary Michael
Forsyth's St Andrew's Day address, included a personal pledge to defend the
Union.
He also rejected the additional powers for the Scottish Grand Committee
announced by Mr Forsyth on Wednesday, which include the right to call
non-Scottish Ministers to account, for failing to close the democratic deficit.
In a policy speech that suggested Labour's unease at the implications of the
parliament's right to increase income tax by up to 3p, Mr Blair said: ``There
is a very big difference between having tax-raising powers, and raising tax.''
Under Labour's proposals, a Scottish parliament could vary the standard rate of
tax by 3p up or down. Mr Forsyth has attacked the power as a ``tartan tax''.
Mr Blair said the amount by which the parliament could raise or lower tax
amounted to less than 5% of Scotland's budget. ``The important point is that it
is for the people to elect the parliament and the parliament to decide whether
taxes should rise or fall, and justify its decision.
``There is a very big difference between having tax-raising powers, and raising
tax. The Westminster Parliament can levy tax but parties proposing matters
connected with taxes have to be elected on their programme; and governments
that raise taxes face the electorate.
``That is an exercise in democracy.''
Rejecting Tory claims that devolution would lead to independence for Scotland,
Mr Blair insisted: ``Let me absolutely clear about one thing. I would never
agree to anything which threatened to break up the United Kingdom. I believe in
the United Kingdom.''
``Scotland is vital part of it in every way - economically, socially,
politically, historically. To us devolution is essential if the unity of
Britain is to be maintained and strengthened.
``The real threat to the Union comes from a government that will not face up to
the clearly stated desires of the people of Scotland - desires that are well
understood by the rest of Britain - to have a greater say over the way Scotland
is run.''
He said: ``For 16 years the government have been telling us that there is
nothing wrong with the way Scotland is governed from Westminster. For 16 years
they have said the Scottish people were wrong to want more control over their
own affairs,'' he said.
``Now the Government have acknowledged that it is they who were wrong. They
admit that the way Scotland is governed from London is inadequate and needs to
change. But while they have finally admitted the problem they have failed to
face up to the solution.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000132</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000132</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Caring Cup for Cruse charity</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110402</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BEREAVEMENT counsellors from the Cruse charity in Glasgow are this year's
winners of the Caring Cup awarded annually by the Evening Times and Strathclyde
region. In addition to the handsome trophy, the charity, based in Wellington
Street, will receive #1000 to help in its work assisting young and old come to
terms with loss.
Formed to offer financial advice to widows and children, Cruse opened its
Glasgow branch in the early 1970s. Its trained volunteers deal with a
bewildering assortment of personal tragedies helping people come to terms with
grief.
However, adults don't have a monopoly on such emotions and one of the most
difficult and sensitive areas the counsellors have tackled over the past four
years is helping bereaved children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000133</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000133</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>GOVERNMENT Tories count cost of new  Parliament</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110403</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Tories turned up the heat on the tax-raising powers of the proposed
Scottish Parliament yesterday by claiming that #12m would go straight into the
pockets of its MPs and support staff.
Seeking to steal the St Andrew's Day thunder of the Scottish Constitutional
Convention, the party wheeled into place in front of the old Royal High School
building in Edinburgh a mobile advertising hoarding stating that the tartan tax
would go not towards schools or hospitals but to politicians.
The Tories broke down the direct running cost of the proposed Parliament into
the salaries, office allowances and overnight expense allowances of 129 MSPs,
salaries for promoted posts, the cost of researchers and severance pay for
those voted out of office.
Mr Forsyth said this would come out at more than #12m and he said that, with
the cost of building the new parliament in its first year, this would rise to a
total of #42.5m - the cost of a large general hospital.
However, Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson countered: ``Even on his
figures, which we believe are inflated, this is about one-third of the money
wasted by the Government on the HCI private hospital, and only about 2% of the
money wasted on an unwanted reorganisation of local government.''
The Conservative leaflet stated that someone on #8320 would pay #2.77 per week
in extra ``tartan tax'' if the full 3p power was implemented; on a #14,400
income this would rise to #6.33; at #22,080 the tax would be #10.70; and an
earner on #76,000 would pay an extra #41.81 weekly.''
After showing off the advertising trailers for the cameras, Scottish Tory
chairman Sir Michael Hirst told a press conference that the proposed tartan tax
would be a ``complicated, costly, administrative nightmare'' and he was
confident that opposition to Home Rule would grow as this dawned on the
electorate.
Of the running costs of the Parliament, the president of the Scottish
Conservative and Unionist Association, Mr David McLetchie, said he did not
believe the people of Scotland would be prepared to sacrifice vital services to
pay for more politicians and bureaucrats.
Mr Forsyth made clear that he was going to wage a relentless onslaught on the
tax-raising power proposed for the Scottish Constitutional Convention's scheme
for a Parliament, and throughout yesterday he treated the proposed 3p power as
if its implementation in full was inevitable.
``What did the Scots do to deserve the imposition of a tax on devolution that
even Labour says will not be levied on Wales?'' he asked. ``The tartan tax is
the most outrageous proposal to come from any political party in a generation.''
He said the planned tax was highly regressive and added: ``We aim to win this
argument. I aim to ensure that the people of Scotland do not sleepwalk into
separatism.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000134</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000134</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Marriage should be for life, says Mackay as peers split on divorce</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110404</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government is facing a battle over its divorce law reforms, after divisions
were exposed last night in the Lords on the Family Law Bill.
The legislation for England and Wales is backed by the bishops but opposed by a
cross-party group of ``pro-family'' peers. It ends the so-called ``quickie''
divorce, introduces ``no-fault'' divorces and imposes a 12-month cooling off
period after the start of divorce proceedings.
The measure also revives, in amended form, the Government's proposals to
strengthen protection for victims of domestic violence.
Leading criticism of the divorce reforms in last night's second reading debate,
Tory former Lords Leader Baroness Young gave notice that strenuous efforts
would be made to change the legislation in the committee stage.
She told the House: ``I shall be putting down amendments which I hope will have
the effect of trying to buttress marriage because that's what we ought to be
talking about - not just picking up the pieces, which is what I think this Bill
does.''
Lady Young added she hoped many improvements could be made to the Bill in the
Lords before it went to the Commons.
She claimed that by removing fault from divorce, the state was ``actively
discouraging any concept of lifelong commitment in marriage'' and undermining
the legal basis of marriage by ``making the contract meaningless''.
Opening the debate, Lord Chancellor Lord Mackay of Clashfern declared his
belief that marriage should be for life.
``I personally would not wish to see people divorced at all,'' Lord Mackay
said. ``I believe that marriage should be for life. This is an ideal, I
believe, which most couples who marry strive for.
``It is this ideal which provides the most stable and secure background for the
birth and development of children.
``I would prefer that spouses remain united until God separated them by death.''
However, Lord Mackay continued: ``I have to recognise that marriages do break
down and the civil legislator must take account of this fact and provide the
best framework of law to do this.''
Most peers in the debate were overwhelmingly in favour of the divorce reforms
in principle, but some voiced particular concern that measures should be taken
to buttress marriage.
Former Chief Rabbi Lord Jakobovits said that with some 150,000 divorces a year,
marriage was now a ``national disaster area'' to which the Government should
respond with the same energy devoted to the Aids epidemic when it first struck.
He protested: ``This Bill, by its emphasis on easing divorce rather than on
strengthening marriage, seems to accept the massive break-up of marriages as if
it were inescapable.''
Lord Marsh (Ind.) predicted a hard-fought committee stage for the Bill in the
Lords on the basis of the ``depth of differences'' voiced by peers on the issue
of divorce.
Lord Mackay emphasised his willingness to consider amendments to the Bill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000135</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000135</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Economists scotch tax fears</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEORGE HUME</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110405</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PROFESSOR of economics has accused Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth of
scaremongering over the ``tartan tax'' proposed for a Scottish parliament.
The doomsday scenario that Mr Forsyth claims would follow the imposition of a
3p-in-the-pound increase in income tax is, says Professor Douglas Mair, of
Heriot-Watt University, ``quite deliberate and political''.
The professor, who has spent five years studying the long-term effect that a
tartan tax would have on the Scottish economy said yesterday: ``Mr Forsyth has
a degree in economics and he ought to know better. He is simply
scare-mongering.''
Nor does he give comfort to the opposing camp who see the proposed extra tax
levy - to a maximum of 3p - as being without flaw.
Says Professor Mair, who has produced his study in conjunction with Dr Tony
Laramie, of Merrimack College in Massachusetts: ``It is misleading, even
mischievous, to claim that the introduction of the tartan tax will have
exclusively harmful or beneficial effects on the Scottish economy.''
Professor Mair and Dr Laramie stress that the so-called tartan tax is not a
black-and-white issue.
They concede that their proposal to move away from conventional means of
managing the economy will not eliminate business cycles.
But extreme swings from boom to bust and back again would, they say, be
flattened out, helping to stabilise the economy.
Professor Mair claims that their researches into the effect of a tartan tax
have been ``exhaustive and rigorous'', that their proposal is ``well thought
through'', and that they have produced a revolutionary new approach to the
study of the effects of taxes.
Working on the basis of the so-called ``worst case scenario'' - that a Scottish
parliament would raise the standard rate of income tax in Scotland by the full
3p - they argue that the level of taxation on its own does not affect the level
of national income. Two things, they say, change the level of national income -
change in the distribution of income brought about by tax increases and the
impact of the tax change on investment.
An increase in the standard rate of income tax in Scotland and the effect
brought about through a change in the distribution of income would have two
sets of effects which largely offset each other, they argue.
There would be a fall in the aggregate level of consumption as a result of the
fall in after-tax incomes. However, because there would have been a
corresponding increase in the spending of the Scottish parliament, a balanced
budget would offset the fall in consumption ``and may even bring about a net
increase in national income in Scotland''.
Professor Mair said yesterday: ``We calculate that if the long run trend of
investment in Scotland was zero then the introduction of the tartan tax would
have the effect of slowing down the rate of growth in investment during the
upswing of the business cycle but accelerate it during the downswing of the
cycle.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000136</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000136</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>TV licence fee to be increased</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110406</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TELEVISION licence fees will rise from next April by #3.50 to #90 for colour
and by #1.50 to #30 for black and white, National Heritage Minister Iain Sproat
announced last night.
He said in a Commons written reply: ``Licence fee increases are based on the
annual Retail Price Index figure as at the previous September. Application of
the RPI figure of 3.9% for the year to September 1995 to the current unrounded
licence fees produces new rounded totals of #90 for a colour licence and #30
for a black and white licence.''
After a review in 1993, the Government decided that, for the remaining three
years of the current BBC Charter, changes in the licence fee should continue to
be set at the inflation level.
Before deciding the level of the licence fee from April 1997, the Government
will review the RPI formula. The continued use of the licence fee to fund the
BBC will be reviewed before the end of 2001.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000137</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000137</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>ANALYSIS Forsyth has a fight on his hands</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MALCOLM DICKSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110407</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS summer saw the ``Battle of the Bands'' with popsters Blur and Oasis
fighting out for the number one spot in the charts. While political parallels
are hard to come by outside of a General Election, this year's St Andrew's Day
``Battle of the Parties'' over the future of Scottish government comes close.
We now have a clear picture of the constitutional stalls being laid out by all
the major political parties in Scotland.
It has been a significant week for Scottish politics. In particular, the
announcements by the Scottish Secretary, Michael Forsyth, on ``strengthening
the Union through real devolution'' have given the first real hints that the
Tories are seriously under pressure over the manner in which Scotland is
governed.
Since Mr Forsyth has found himself in the hot seat in the Scottish Office, he
has launched a number of initiatives aimed at addressing both the Tories' poor
poll ratings and the workings of Scottish decision-making.
However, he finds himself in a difficult position of having to come up with
something new, while for so long the Tories have said all is well. With the
Scottish Constitutional Convention plans now on the table he is in the position
of having to follow the agenda set by the opposition parties rather than
forging his own.
But the plans will have the effect of turning the spotlight even more brightly
on how little impact the elected representatives of Scotland currently have in
Scottish decision-making.
For example, the plans to extend the remit of the Scottish Grand Committee give
the Tories two new problems. Firstly, they will not only have to justify their
position on any Scottish legislation but will also have to justify why certain
Bills will go before the Grand Committee and others will not. Under the glare
of the opposition and the Scottish media, this is an impossible task to achieve
without further criticism being generated.
Secondly, these plans are an own-goal as far the Tory insistence on an answer
to the ``West Lothian Question'' goes. It will allow Scottish MPs to vote on
Scottish legislation while allowing those self-same MPs to vote on equivalent
measures for England and Wales. Mr Forsyth has been pushing the issue of the
West Lothian question in recent months and yet his plans actually pose that
very question themselves.
Opposition responses to these plans have bordered on the derisive. Yet none of
the opposition parties can guarantee having the last laugh in the run up to the
General Election. Both the SNP and Labour together with the Liberal Democrats
have now put detailed plans before the people of Scotland. In 1992, despite the
attention focused on the constitutional issue, details were rather thin on the
ground. The need to be able to argue the constitutional case in detail as well
as in principle will be a guiding feature of the next election campaign.
Mr Salmond desperately needs to take votes from Labour to make any impact, but
his party's support is back into the mid-20% bracket, down from the 30%
achieved in last year's Euro elections. With Labour surging ahead in British
terms it may well be the case that the Scottish electorate's attentions are
focused more on a possible win for Tony Blair rather than being ready for a win
for the SNP.
So far, Mr Forsyth can be judged favourably on his ability to keep a grip on
the Scottish Office's allocation in last Tuesday's Budget. There was
considerable pressure to slice Scottish spending. Yet this is not the stuff of
electoral appeal. Nor is the pressure being put on Scottish local government in
the run up to the introduction of the new councils next April.
The constitutional issue has struck a chord with Mr Forsyth in his attack on
devolution tax raising powers, the so-called ``Tartan Tax''. Yet with the
general trust of voters in the Tories on the economy and tax at a post-war low,
the tax issue is likely to have resonance only in the Scottish business
community.
Michael Forsyth will require all his robustness to continue the battle in
Scotland. But it is difficult to see how he can succeed where his predecessors
have failed. Even a full scale U-turn on devolution would not be enough.
Dr Malcolm Dickson lectures in Politics at Strathclyde University.
</TEXT>
