<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000138</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000138</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Church faces a modern-day dilemma as royalty bridges an old religious divide Kirk has to find stance on `partners'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH BUIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110408</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A VOTE by the Church of England's ruling body on a report which claims that
living in sin is no longer sinful may give fresh impetus to the Church of
Scotland to reach a position on relationships outside marriage, it was claimed
last night.
Mrs Elizabeth Templeton, convener of the Church of Scotland's working party on
marriage for the board of doctrine, said last night that, every time the issue
of relationships outside marriage went through a church's court, it increased
pressure on other churches to take a stand on the issue.
Her comments followed a warning by the Archbishop of Canterbury, Dr George
Carey, that ``cohabitation was no substitution for marriage''. Dr Carey also
called for the Church to be ``uncompromising'' in upholding the values of
marital fidelity.
Until now, the Church of Scotland has drawn back from voting on a report,
prepared for the General Assembly in 1994, which recommended it was time the
Church took seriously the position of people who had decided to participate in
alternative relationships. It provoked very sharp dissent from some members of
the Church and no vote was taken.
That same report has recently been reissued to congregations, Kirk sessions and
presbyteries for their consideration, but no time limit has been set for a
response.
``It will come up when some committee calls for a fixed vote. I think there are
people who would like a vote from both ends of the spectrum, and people who
would like there not to be one, as any decision would be premature or
divisive,'' Mrs Templeton said.
She added that both the United Reform Church and the Methodist Church had
decided that people who were in long-term committed homosexual or heterosexual
relationships were welcome as members.
Father Noel Barry, speaking on behalf of Cardinal Thomas Winning, head of the
Roman Catholic Church in Scotland, said: ``The position of the Roman Catholic
Church is that there is no substitute for marriage in terms of relationships.
Nothing less than marriage would be acceptable.''
In a stormy debate at the Church of England's General Synod yesterday, members
voted to ``take note'' of the report while restating the Church's commitment to
marriage. The Synod also cited the variety of family relationships.
Opening the debate, the Bishop of Liverpool, Dr David Sheppard, threw his
weight behind the report, but warned people to see it in its whole context. He
believed it did not say cohabitation had the same moral value as marriage,
which was ``God's proper and best way''.
Warning against stifling public debate, he said it was important ``to try to
offer a word to those who may be in irregular partnerships''. This was quite
different from encouraging people to have casual relationships.
In stark contrast, Dr Carey said he was ``very disappointed'' with the report,
which did not focus strongly enough on the impact of family life based on a
husband and wife in a permanent, loving relationship.
This ideal had run through the Bible from the story of Adam and Eve to later
stories in the New Testament.
Cohabitation was not and could not be marriage in all but name, he added.
Marriage was a ceremony involving a recognition from wider society. Those who
chose to cohabit on the grounds that their relationship was a private matter
and nothing to do with society were ``frankly deluding themselves''.
Mrs Christine McMullen, from Derby, a member of the working party which drew up
the report, described it as ``gentle, affirming, tolerant and honest''. It
searched for the truth of the family and did not claim to offer the whole truth.
The report said marriage was the best place for children to be reared but did
not despise those who had different arrangements. Mrs McMullen added it gave
meaning to life in a largely meaningless world.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000139</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000139</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tory fury at ruling by European Court on anti-terror law</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110409</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOME Secretary Michael Howard denied yesterday that his ability to exclude
suspected terrorists from Britain had been undermined by a ruling of the
European Court of Justice.
Ruling in favour of former republican activist John Gallagher, who was excluded
from Britain as a suspected terrorist, the Court stated that the operation of
the Prevention of Terrorism Act was in breach of freedom of movement guaranteed
by the Treaty of Rome.
The ruling opens the door to possible compensation claims from other Irish
citizens kept out of the UK under the Home Secretary's special powers.
As angry Conservative MPs bitterly attacked the ruling, Mr Howard said that did
not affect the substance of his power to continue issuing banning orders but
only the procedures which had to be followed in operating it.
Mr Howard said: ``As far as I can see, the only likely effect of it is that
those who are subject to it are likely to be detained in custody in consequence
instead of being allowed to leave the country while an exclusion order is being
considered.''
He said he was confident he would successfully resist any claim for
compensation that was made.
However, former Home Office Minister Charles Wardle (Bexhill and Battle - Con.)
said the European Court had ``made a mockery'' of the exclusion order decisions
and wondered what the court would do with Britain's internal frontier controls.
Mr Howard told him the government remained determined to retain frontier
controls.
Sir Ivan Lawrence (Burton - Con.), chairman of the Home Affairs Select
Committee, said life was becoming impossible for Ministers, whose every
decision was becoming subject to judicial review and urged that consideration
be given to reducing the opportunities for this.
Sir Teddy Taylor (Southend East - Con.), who said it was ``a terribly serious
issue'', demanded to know if it was true the Government would have to give
compensation from taxpayers' funds to those excluded from Britain on grounds of
national security.
He asked how the Government explained the decision after the assurances given
during the passage of the Maastricht Act that security was a matter entirely
for the British Government.
Mr Howard said be very much regretted the court decision but it did not go to
the substance of his powers.
Liberal Democrat lawyer Alex Carlile (Montgomery) accused the critics of
``babbling,'' and said the decision did not undermine the PTA provisions ``in
any significant way.''
Mr John Greenway (Ryedale - Con.) claimed that the sovereignty of the Commons
was at risk, but Mr Howard said that while he would be concerned if that was
the case the judgment simply made a limited criticism of some of the procedures
and said these could be updated ``without any difficulty.''
Ealier, Sir Teddy Taylor said outside the Commons: ``This is one of the most
frightening decisions we've ever heard.
``It seems appalling that the non-elected European Court is telling the British
Government not only how to operate on terrorism, but how not to.''
He added: ``At some stage, the Government is going to have to tell this court
to take a running jump.''
The Home Office said it would study the details of the ruling but had no
intention of scrapping the Act.
``We shall consider very carefully the implications of this judgment. But it is
clear that it does not question the power to make exclusion orders - it
addresses only the procedures involved in making them,'' a spokesman said.
``The power to exclude remains an important weapon in our counter-terrorist
armoury. We don't propose to surrender that weapon until it is completely safe
to do so.''
The court's ruling said the Prevention of Terrorism Act was subject to a 1964
EU directive which stated that national authorities cannot, except in
emergencies, issue exclusion orders to foreign nationals ``before a competent
authority has given its opinion''.
The ``competent authority'' can be appointed by the government, as long as it
has ``absolute independence'' and is not subject to ``any control'' from the
government, says the directive.
That provision is not honoured by the Prevention of Terrorism Act, the
Luxembourg judges ruled.
``Member states are entitled to make exclusion orders. This case has been about
the procedures and process of doing so,'' a court official said.
Donegal-born Gallagher, 35, was arrested in London in September 1991 and served
with an exclusion order. He was deported to Ireland three days later.
After he was expelled Gallagher wrote to the Home Office insisting on a
personal interview with someone nominated by the Home Secretary.
The interview took place in the British Embassy in Dublin in December 1991, but
the nominee did not identify himself and provided no information about the
grounds for Gallagher's exclusion. Gallagher then took his case to the Court of
Appeal, which referred it to Luxembourg for a ruling.
Poker chip 15
</TEXT>
