<DOCNO>GH951201-000140</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000140</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Major defends girl's deportation</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110410</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister defended the immigration service in the Commons yesterday
against allegations that it had deported a sick three-year-old girl with her
mother.
Mr Major said during Question Time that immigration cases were ``examined with
compassion'' and that the child must have been deported because her mother was
an illegal immigrant.
The issue was raised by Labour MP Janner (Leicester West). He told the House
about one of his constituents, British-born three-year-old Jasmine Sorabjee. Mr
Janner said she was ill and claimed the Home Office had deported her and her
mother Scheherazade Sorabjee, a Kenyan Asian, to Kenya.
Mrs Sorabjee's plight arises from Britain's refusal to afford protected
immigration status to parents of its own citizens who are still minors, in
contrast to other EU members.
Mr Janner asked the Prime Minister: ``Is this not a cruel and disgraceful
decision, totally devoid of compassion, and showing the absolutely disgraceful
way this Government is abusing immigration rules?''
To howls of protest from the Labour benches, Mr Major said: ``There are very
strict ways these matters are examined, they are examined with compassion,
without any shadow of doubt and the person removed from this country, although
I have no details of the particular case, would have been the parent who
presumably was an illegal immigrant.''
</TEXT>
