<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000141</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000141</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Research shows higher incidence in central belt Alzheimer's study finds mining link</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110411</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAJOR research programme into pre-senile Alzheimer's Disease has found that
it is more prevalent in Glasgow, North Lanarkshire and Edinburgh than other
areas of Scotland, and that having a father who was a coal miner or who was an
older father increases the risk.
The research by Professor Lawrence Whalley and colleagues at Aberdeen
University involved the only national sample in the world, which was also the
biggest sample so far. It involved 450 Alzheimer patients between 1974 and 1988
and 1784 early dementia cases.
One of the key findings is that, in Scotland, the distribution of Alzheimer's
Disease is not random.
``There are pockets of high incidence,'' Professor Whalley said yesterday.
``They are in North Lanarkshire and the major conurbations of Edinburgh and
Glasgow.
``We have tested these pockets and they are real pockets and are not just
caused by a variation in diagnosis which would account for a higher than
expected incidence.
``We then tried to explain them and looked at what we knew about the people in
these areas.''
The researchers were looking at whether increased parental age was a factor
because it has been previously established that virtually everyone with Down's
Syndrome gets Alzheimer's Disease before the age of 40, and Down's Syndrome is
associated with increased maternal age.
Because of Scotland's history in public health, the researchers were able to
consult comprehensive records of disease and they were also able to check
marriage records.
``We found that there was increased parental age, but it was their fathers who
were increased in age, and it was only their sons who were affected,'' he said.
``This is very important because there are other diseases which show this
particular phenomena in medicine.
``It is always assumed that, although women should be wary about having
children as they grow older, men can go on fathering children until they get to
Charlie Chaplin's age. This may not be the case.''
He said that about 10% of the male Alzheimer's patients could be accounted for
by increased paternal age. The association of having a coal miner for a father
was quite unexpected and is not specific for Alzheimer's Disease, just for
dementia.
``When these people were born between 1915 and 1925, about 10% of Scotland's
male working population were coal miners,'' said Professor Whalley.
``These people lived in considerable poverty, often in small villages away from
towns and cities and with very little in the way of alternative employment.''
He said that those pioneering public health medicine in Scotland went out to
these villages and discovered that the miners topped every league table ever
drawn up for diseases, and their children were the same. Infant mortality was
as high as 30%.
Professor Whalley said the coal miners' children subsequently migrated into the
big cities, which probably explains the high incidence of Alzheimer's in
central Scotland.
He said the deficient nutrition of these children during pregnancy and in the
early years of their lives may have affected their ``cerebral reserve'' and
reduced their capacity to cope with even the mildest Alzheimer's. ``The
nutrition and education you receive shape up your brain's adaptive capacity,''
he said.
Professor Whalley added that they knew from the records of the medical officers
of health that these children experienced extreme poverty growing up in the
central belt around the time of the First World War, and they suspect that may
be the link which explains the high incidence of the condition.
Those children who survived the deprivation are more likely to get Alzheimer's
Disease. ``We already know from other studies that children who grow up in
poverty are much more likely to get vascular disease,'' he said.
``The next step is to try to identify the components that could be causing
this. The one we are particularly interested in is nutrition and ageing.''
</TEXT>
