<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000142</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000142</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Number of single  parents levels out</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110412</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE rise in the number of single parent families is slowing in the 1990s while
more people are living alone, a survey published yesterday shows.
Living trends in Britain are revealed in the Office of Population Censuses and
Surveys' general household survey for 1994.
It shows the proportion of families with dependent children headed by single
parents remained at 22% between 1993 and last year.
But the number of people living alone continued to rise and accounted for 27%
of households last year. When the survey was first published in 1971 they made
up just 17%.
The average family size is 2.4 people, which has declined from 2.9 in the early
1970s.
Other key findings include news that the gap between men and women smokers has
narrowed. In 1994 28% of men smoked compared with 26% of women, but 20 years
ago half of all men smoked and just over 40% of women.
As far as alcohol is concerned, one in four men drink more than the recommended
maximum level of 21 units a week while 13% of women knock back more than their
recommended 14 units a week.
The survey was taken by questioning 18,000 people from more than 9700
households across the country between April 1994 and March this year.
It also found that we continue to buy more consumer goods with the greatest
increase from 1993 in the number of CD players from 39% to 47% of families.
The kitchens of 67% of households now have microwave ovens and 19% have a
dishwasher.
Only one in five households are council tenants compared with one in three in
1983.
But renting from the private sector has risen from 7% of households in 1991 to
9% last year.
</TEXT>
