<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Same dull thud and even less passion</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Stuart Trotter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110413</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NOBODY called it a ``wee sleekit, cowrin', timorous beastie'' which, as they
were all Welsh, was perhaps not surprising. But they got close.
Ieuan Win Jones (Ynys Mon - Welsh Nationalist), inhibited by not being allowed
Welsh, called it ``a timid little mouse,'' which showed up English as lacking
the virility of a Scots accent.
Mr Donald Anderson (Swansea East - Lab.) said that, after 17 years' reflection
on devolution, the Government had produced ``the longest recorded gestation
period of a mouse''.
Mr William Hague, Welsh Secretary, was presenting his policy for expanding the
activities of the Welsh Grand Committee following in the footsteps of Mr
Michael Forsyth the day before. ``Major to be quizzed in Bangor'' will be a
headline to match ``Heseltine questioned in Stornoway''.
The proposals went down with the same dull thud as those for Scotland - not
surprising, considering that the MPs giving them the thumbs-down have what they
consider infinitely superior plans of their own for their native lands.
However, the whole affair was much less combative. Mr Forsyth, even when
striving to be ecumenical, cannot it seems avoid stirring up fiery passions in
his opponents.
Mr Hague, though sharp, has a more amiable political personality.
The Opposition parties were prepared to tell him his ideas were no good without
evincing any strong desire to see him twisting in the wind. Rather like Mr
Major, Mr Hague is a politician it is hard to be angry with.
The unkindest cut came from Labour spokesman Rhodri Morgan, who suggested that
the Secretary of State had peaked as a speaker at the age of 16 when, readers
will recall, he transfixed a Tory Party conference with his youthful oratory.
Unlike Mr George Robertson, who fell over himself in denunciatory vigour, Mr
Ron Davies, the Welsh Shadow, admitted the idea was ``novel'', just not much
use.
Mr Alex Carlile, for the Liberal Democrats, contented himself with ``paltry and
miserable,'' and Mrs Ann Clywd (Cynon Valley - Lab.) said it was ``a
meaningless sop''.
A few hastily summoned English Tories asked what sounded like suspiciously
planted questions about how the Welsh would be enthused by seeing more of their
Grand Committee and what a treat it would be for them to be visited by the
likes of Messrs Major and Clarke.
There were calls for ``a real parliament,'' although, perhaps warned by the
experience of their Scottish conferences, nobody called for taxing powers.
According to Mr Alan Williams (Swansea West - Lab.), 99% of the Welsh
population are in the blissful state of not knowing the Welsh Grand Committee
exists. Mr Hague's travelling circus could well cut that to 95%.
This Tory devolution bid, declared Mr Morgan, was as meaningless as King Edward
I making his son the first Prince of Wales. King Edward also made John Balliol
King of Scotland. Presumably, George Robertson, Jim Wallace, and Alex Salmond
can make something of that.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000144</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000144</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>CBI's costs plea</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110414</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S industrial leaders say the ``hard economic facts'' of devolution
should be made available to them.
Mr Andrew Cubie, chairman of the CBI Scotland, warned that businesses would not
tolerate any increase in the cost of government in Scotland if devolution
became a reality.
About 43% of Scotland's Gross Domestic Product (GDP) currently goes to the
Government, according to Mr Cubie, when in fact the CBI believed it should be
under 40%.
``Scottish business can demand that hard economic facts should be made
available to us,'' said Mr Cubie.
``We do not have sufficient economic information to make a judgment on
devolution.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000145</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000145</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Post strike ends</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110415</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE postal strike at Hamilton is over. A return to work was agreed last night
without, apparently, the removal of a line manager whose allegedly aggressive
attitude had angered the strikers.
Instead, both the Royal Mail and the Communication Workers' Union said that
industrial relations at Hamilton would be monitored and a ``climate of trust
and respect'' would be encouraged.
Welcoming the return to work, Royal Mail area manager Steve Cameron said: ``We
are committed to restoring the mail service to our customers as quickly as
possible.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000146</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000146</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Murder choice for McVitie's Prize</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RON MacKENNA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110416</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GLASGOW born author and poet Frank Kuppner has been awarded the McVitie's Prize
for his investigative novel, Something Like Murder.
Mr Kuppner, whose previous publications include A Bad Day for the Sung Dynasty,
picks up a #10,000 cheque to go with the title of Scottish Writer of the Year.
Five shortlisted authors receive #1000. They are: A L Kennedy for So I Am Glad;
Eric Lomax for The Railway Man; Alexander McCall Smith for Heavenly Date and
Other Stories; and Sharman Mac- donald for Plays 1.
A L Kennedy also shared joint first prize with Neil Ascherson, for Black Sea,
in the #2500 Saltire Society book awards announced in Glasgow City Chambers.
Ali Smith's Free Love was named Scottish First Book by the society.
Lorn Macintyre - Page 14
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000147</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000147</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MP may have to quit Labour post in `racism' row</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN Political Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110417</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR Chief Whip Donald Dewar has summoned MP Keith Vaz to explain remarks in
a television interview in which he allegedly questioned the need for a white
man to be given a local council post.
Mr Vaz, 49, is MP for Leicester East and a Front Bench spokesman on inner-city
affairs. Speculation was growing at Westminister last night that he may be
asked to resign his post after Tory MPs seized on the incident at Prime
Minister's Questions.
Tory Party chairman Brian Mawhinney yesterday wrote to Labour leader Tony Blair
demanding that Mr Vaz be sacked ``in support of the view that we both hold that
there can be no excuse for racism in public life.''
According to Dr Mawhinney, Mr Vaz is quoted in an upcoming Dispatches programme
on Channel 4 as saying of a candidate for the post of deputy leader of
Leicester Council ``why should we have a white person?''
A Labour spokesman said no decision would be taken until the matter was
discussed, and Mr Vaz had had the chance to explain himself.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000148</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000148</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The Queen attends Roman Catholic service amid protests</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110418</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Queen made history when she attended a full service in a Roman Catholic
church yesterday.
The Duchess of Kent, a Catholic convert, was also present for the ecumenical
service at Westminster Cathedral.
Minority Protestant demonstrators jeered as the Queen, who is head of the
Church of England, arrived for the 45-minute service.
Led into the cathedral by Cardinal Basil Hume, the Roman Catholic Archbishop of
Westminster, the Queen was greeted by the 1500-strong congregation which broke
into warm and spontaneous applause.
The service was also attended by Dr George Carey, the Archbishop of Canterbury,
and representatives of other Christian faiths - there was no Mass.
Buckingham Palace said it was ``an appropriate decision for the times'' that
the 100th anniversary of Westminster Cathedral should be celebrated at an
ecumenical service with the Queen present.
Cardinal Hume, in his homily, welcomed the Queen.
``In 1982, Your Majesty received Pope John Paul into your London home,'' he
said. ``That was for us the healing of many ancient wounds and we were so
grateful for that.''
The Queen's presence was ``a further affirmation of the place that we Catholics
have in the nation'', added Cardinal Hume.
The Queen sat at the front of the nave on a specially-carved chair made of
rosewood and emblazoned with a mother-of-pearl rose of England and the Cross of
St George.
The congregation and choir sang much of the service in Latin but ended with God
Save the Queen in English.
Outside small groups of protesters, among the 500 to 600-strong crowd, handed
out leaflets and preached impromptu sermons.
Reformed Baptist Michael Hobbis, holding a banner declaring The Just Shall Live
by Faith, said: ``The Queen is breaking her coronation vows and making a
mockery of the martyrs of the Reformation.
``The Archbishop of Canterbury ought not to have advised Her Majesty to attend
Vespers at Westminster Cathedral, and Her Majesty, as keeper of her own
conscience as she will answer before Almighty God, ought not to attend.''
q THE Queen Mother has been advised by doctors to stay in hospital for a few
more days to complete her recovery, Buckingham Palace said yesterday.
She had made ``excellent progress'' following her hip replacement operation two
weeks ago, said a palace spokesman.
It was not possible to give a precise date when the Queen Mother, 95, would
leave the King Edward VII Hospital for Officers in London, he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000149</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000149</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sickness delays `right to die' case</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110419</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S first ``right to die'' case has been delayed by the illness of the
Lord Advocate.
Because of the ``substantial importance'' of the issues involved in the case,
the Lord Advocate, Mr Donald Mackay QC, wishes to appear in person to state the
Crown's position.
At the Court of Session yesterday, Lord Cameron was informed that the Lord
Advocate was unwell and would be unable to appear.
The judge agreed to adjourn the case brought by the Law Hospital NHS Trust
until Mr Mackay can appear in person. No date for a new hearing has yet been
fixed.
Lord Cameron is being asked to declare that doctors can lawfully discontinue
life-saving treatment for 52-year-old Mrs Janet Johnstone.
Mrs Johnstone, from Houldsworth Crescent, Allanton, Lanarkshire, has been in a
coma after taking a drugs overdose in January 1992. She can breathe on her own
but has to be fed through a nasal tube.
Five doctors have confirmed that she is in a persistent vegetative state with
no prospect of recovery and the hospital's application to let her die with
dignity is supported by her immediate family.
In his written defences to the case, the Lord Advocate is arguing that since
the case raises criminal law issues of murder and culpable homicide, the Court
of Session, a civil court, has no jurisdiction to hear it.
A curator appointed to look after Mrs Johnstone's interests is also opposing
the hospital's application.
</TEXT>
