<DOCNO>GH951201-000150</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000150</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stamp prices set to rise as Treasury raids PO till</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110420</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE price of stamps is set to rise by a penny next year - and Post Office
chiefs say the Government is to blame.
Mail bosses, who are also refusing to rule out job cuts, say Treasury Ministers
have dramatically increased the amount they annually claim from the PO.
As a result, hopes that a price freeze imposed in late 1993 could be extended
to at least March had been ``inevitably called into question'', warned PO chief
executive John Roberts.
Labour says the Government's move amounts to a new ``stamp duty'' to make up
for the tax cuts it announced in Tuesday's Budget.
Ministers had set the annual dividend it claims from the Post Office at #178m
for each of the next three financial years.
But that has been increased, as a result of Tuesday's Budget, to nearly #300m
in the first year and more than #300m in the next two years.
Post Office officials said they would now have to hand over nearly #1000m in
the next three years - about as much as they had paid in the last 10.
And that was on top of the #110m a year the organisation pays in tax, added a
spokesman.
The upshot was that the Post Office was being ``squeezed'' and would have to
find ways of raising more cash, said Mr Roberts.
``The Government has its job to do and we have ours. We would be failing in our
duty to the customer if we did not make clear the implications of these
figures,'' he added.
Mr Roberts said customers should brace themselves for a 1p rise on first and
second-class rates in the spring. A first-class stamp is currently 25p and a
second 19p.
Shadow Trade Secretary Margaret Beckett said what the Government had given away
in tax cuts in one hand on Tuesday it was now taking back with another.
``A new Tory stamp tax has been exposed,'' she said. ``They're demanding
another million pounds a day from the Post Office.''
The Union of Communication Workers said the Government's decision could result
in the PO going into the red for the first time in 20 years.
In June, PO bosses announced record pre-tax profits of #472m. It has also shed
about 10,000 jobs in the last four years.
The PO warning comes months after former Trade President Michael Heseltine
failed to privatise the organisation.
Mail bosses wanted privatisation because they said the financial demands made
by Government were making it increasingly difficult to fight off competition
from privatised foreign operations.
Mr Heseltine indicated he would aim to give the organisation more commercial
freedom within Government ownership.
But the increase in Government cash demands would appear to be a complete
reversal of that policy.
</TEXT>
