<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000151</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000151</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chancellor admits extra cash for families does not all come from tax cuts Labour seizes on Clarke `gaffe'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Our Political Staff</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110421</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHANCELLOR Kenneth Clarke last night was caught up in a row with Labour over
claims that the Budget would leave average families #9 a week better off.
He was forced to admit that more than half the extra cash in their pockets next
year would come from pay increases - and not through Budget tax cuts.
In what Labour hailed as a double ``gaffe,'' Mr Clarke also appeared to admit
that Tory policies had done little to increase the income of ordinary families
in the 1990s.
Labour leader Tony Blair challenged the Prime Minister at Commons Questions to
admit that #7 of the claimed #9 a week post-Budget increase in family income
was down to wage rises that would have happened anyway.
``The real Budget figure is just #2 and that's not taking account of extra
costs and charges,'' he said.
Mr Major insisted that it was the Government's ``expectation'' that family
incomes would rise by around #450 a year - or #9 a week - but sidestepped
repeating the claim made by Tory chairman Brian Mawhinney that the increase was
the direct result of the Budget.
In a letter to Mr Blair, the Chancellor drove the point home, but added
significantly: ``This increase is attributable both to tax reductions and
growth in real earnings.
``Budget tax changes will leave such a family #190 a year better off in cash
terms.
``As a result of the growth in the economy which this Government's policies
have secured, earnings growth is expected to bring the overall increase in real
take-home pay up to #450.''
Labour has insisted since the Budget that Tory claims for increased income were
false and party leaders seized on the letter as clear vindication.
Deputy leader John Prescott said: ``The Budget is unravelling hour by hour.
First the Prime Minister is forced to admit the so-called #9 a week Budget is
merely an expectation, now the Chancellor is forced to admit that the bulk of
this #9 is made up of a rosy estimation of wage rises and economic growth.
``The truth is you can't trust their claims for inflation, for growth or for
pay rises. They are incapable of running an economy and they are incapable of
telling the truth about tax.''
Mr Clarke was embroiled in a separate row after appearing to admit that
ordinary families were no better off under Tory rule after being hard hit by
the recession.
``As Chancellor, I have come along with a healing economy and a recovering
economy and we are recovering very well,'' he told Jimmy Young on BBC Radio 2.
``The trouble is the British public don't feel much benefit. Their family
incomes are not any better than they were really.''
However, he insisted that economic recovery was now among the strongest in the
world and said families would ``keep more of what they earn and more of what
they save'' as a result of his tax-cutting financial package on Tuesday.
Shadow Chancellor Gordon Brown said the remarks were proof that Tory policies
had failed ordinary families despite the #9-a-week claim.
``Now we find the Chancellor having to tell the truth that family incomes are
no better than they were,'' he said.
In the Commons, Mr Blair asked Mr Major: ``Will you confirm that of this #9,
almost #7 has nothing to do with the Budget but to do with the Conservatives'
projection of wage increases next year?''
Mr Major said: ``You made a whole series of comments in replying to the Budget
- the vast majority of which were specious, or wrong or misleading.
``If you care to examine them, you will find that those that were not wrong
were misleading and those that were not misleading were wrong.
``What Dr Mawhinney said is that people will be better off next year by #450
and that is our expectation.''
</TEXT>
