<DOCNO>GH951201-000152</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000152</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Curbs on surveillance videos</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110422</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government is to introduce a code of practice to cover the use of material
from closed-circuit television cameras, Home Office Minister of State David
Maclean said yesterday. The move follows concern over a video compilation
called Caught In The Act!, which included shots of a couple having sex in a
lift. The video went on sale earlier this week but was withdrawn after protests.
Mr Maclean told the Commons that a ``key condition'' of Government funding for
any CCTV cameras for security purposes would be a code of practice on ``the
proper use'' of videotapes.
Mr Henry Bellingham (Norfolk North-West - Con.) cited the ``bizarre and
worrying'' recent case where one of his constituents bought 20 police interview
tapes, marked Essex and Cambridgeshire Constabulary, at a car boot sale.
``This contained highly confidential information including an interview of a
schoolmaster who was alleged to have interfered with a choirboy.''
Mr Alun Michael, for the Opposition, said it would be tragic if public
confidence in surveillance cameras was undermined by people selling off
material from the films.
Mr Maclean replied: ``Let us be careful not to hype up these episodes. We do
not want to regulate out sensible use of pictures by hasty measures because of
shoddy, poor quality, over-hyped films. The little that has been released is of
such poor quality that it is worse than Logie Baird's first pictures in 1925.
The public should condemn it by not buying this rubbish.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
