<DOCNO>GH951201-000153</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000153</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>`Chance meeting' that put Adams in the spotlight</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110423</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A STAGE-managed but symbolic handshake between President Clinton and Sinn Fein
president Gerry Adams took place outside a Falls Road cafe yesterday.
The meeting, portrayed as a chance encounter, had clearly been deftly woven
into the President's busy schedule.
American sources indicated the meeting was arranged late last night.
Mr Clinton was driving through the nationalist stronghold when his cavalcade
stopped outside McErleans Bakery.
Mr Adams was inside with other members of his party. He went out on the
pavement and greeted the President with a handshake and the two men chatted
before they went inside.
Shop assistant Kathleen Mooney said: ``He (Mr Clinton) popped in all right - we
weren't expecting him.
``Gerry Adams was having a cup of tea, he was sitting with members of Sinn
Fein. He walked out and then he greeted the President as he got out of the car.
``President Clinton walked in and greeted us. He said he was very happy to be
in Belfast and he chatted to Gerry Adams,'' the assistant added.
Asked what he had told the President, Mr Adams told reporters: ``I gave him a
thousand welcomes.''
This is a traditional greeting in Gaelic - ``Mille Failte''.
Mr Clinton replied: ``Nice to see you. I look forward to seeing you this
evening.''
Afterwards Mr Adams said: ``He is obviously pleased to be here and enthused by
the reception of the people.''
The two men shook hands once before when the Sinn Fein president attended a
White House St Patrick's Day celebration in Washington this year.
Sinn Fein said it understood the President ``felt it was important to touch
base with everyone during his visit to Belfast''.
Immediately afterwards, the Sinn Fein leader went on to attend a lunch with US
Secretary of Commerce Ron Brown and US Education Secretary Dick Riley.
</TEXT>
