<DOCNO>GH951201-000154</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000154</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Choices for Scotland. Day of Destiny: as the Constituitional Convention celebrates the signing of a historic document the SNP and the Tories make the case for something different</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH, Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110424</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S D-Day was how Canon Kenyon Wright described yesterday's public
launch of the Scottish Constitutional Convention's proposals for a Scottish
Parliament.
``The victory is not won. There are hard battles ahead, but we sense that the
decisive turning point has come; the result is no longer in serious doubt,'' he
told a gathering in the Church of Scotland's General Assembly Hall in Edinburgh.
It was billed as a civic and cultural celebration to launch the document
``Scotland's Parliament - Scotland's Right'' to the people of Scotland.
There were speeches, of course, but also musical interludes, with songs in
Gaelic and an exuberant all-female drumming group, and a video showing sports
and arts personalities and members of the public endorsing the devolution
message.
The morning's celebration had begun with the reading of a proclamation at the
Mercat Cross in the High Street.
Acting as crier was Laurie Robertson, one of Edinburgh District Council's city
officers, who was flanked by the convention's co-chairmen, Lord Ewing of
Kirkford and Sir David Steel MP.
The call was to the people of Scotland to come to the Assembly Hall to witness
the signing of the agreed scheme for Scotland's parliament and to celebrate
this ``great step forward'' in establishing the parliament in Edinburgh.
Led by the Lothian and Borders Police Pipe Band, a selection of the great and
the good from Scottish political life (excluding the Tories or the SNP, of
course) the churches, the trade unions and other social groups all marched to
the Assembly Hall.
Once inside - with members of the public also present - there were some party
political points to be scored.
When Scottish Labour leader George Robertson spoke of ``one lot of politicians
who, over a single weekend, had abandoned the ``no change policy'' which had
united them for 16 years'' everyone knew he was talking about the Tories.
Scottish Liberal Democrat Leader Jim Wallace MP called the Scottish Economic
Council, soon to be revamped under the Scottish Secretary's latest proposals,
``Michael's Mouse'', and Jean McFadden, who chairs the new Glasgow City
Council, said Tory plans for strengthening the Scottish Grand Committee would
have done nothing to stop the hated poll tax, whereas a Scottish parliament
would have done so.
Lord Ewing struck a sombre note too when he warned of ``a campaign of fear''
which he forecast would now be unleashed by the convention's enemies about the
consequences of the creation of a devolved Scottish parliament. They would try
to frighten the life out of the people of Scotland ``in the most disgraceful
fashion'' he claimed.
One Tory, in fact, was spotted in the audience - Alan Clark the maverick former
Defence Minister and author of the notorious diaries. He said his mission to
observe was journalistic rather than political.
``I don't think the Prime Minister would have chosen me to report back to
him,'' he chuckled.
Mr Clark, for the record, now says the arguments for change in Scotland are
very hard to resist, but he favours independence, not devolution.
The mood in the Assembly Hall was also one of satisfaction and rejoicing that,
after six years of debate and negotiation, the convention's scheme was now
complete and agreement had been reached between the Labour Party and the
Liberal Democrats on the shape of the new Scottish parliament.
In the Assembly Hall, the sight of George Robertson and Jim Wallace seated
together seemed to give tangible form to that constitutional alliance, and Sir
David Steel paid tribute to their leadership in bringing the long discussions
to a successful conclusion.
Details of the 129-seat body, 56 of whose members would be elected by a form of
proportional representation involving additonal members from party lists, had
already been publicised.
Jim Wallace said that the creation of a fairly-elected parliament ``was the
first and most obvious signal to the Scottish people that what we are trying to
create is something very different from the mock gothic pile on the banks of
the Thames.''
George Robertson said the accord reached between Labour and the Liberal
Democrats over the convention document was evidence of a new era in the
politics of Scotland. ``Not just words or ringing phrases. Not just hopes and
optimism.''
He went on ``Instead we present with dignity and integrity a detailed plan
worked on with pain and argument, time and travail, often mind-bending
attention to detail, and built solidly and effectively on consensus and common
sense.''
Speaking on behalf of the Scottish Trades Union Congress, Jane McKay said that
one of the reasons why the parliament would make a difference was because women
would be involved equally with men in the decision-making process.
She referred to the unique agreement between Labour and the Liberal Democrats
which accepted the principle that there should be an equal number of men and
women as members of the parliament.
After all the members had signed the Convention's declaration to the sound of
the pipes it fell to Canon Wright, chairman of the executive commitee, to make
the final speech.
The canon wished he could be young again to be part of the reshaping of
Scotland. Young people, he stressed, had a crucial part to play in creating a
new society.
Later, the Scottish Chambers of Commerce gave an enthusiastic welcome to the
convention's contribution to the devolution debate.
Acting director general Peter Dunn said said he had been struck by the honesty,
sincerity and integrity of those who had presented the proposals .
q WHILE the ceremony was going ahead in Edinburgh, Mr Campbell Christie, the
STUC general secretary, was in Brussels for a simultaneous presentation.
He told a gathering of Scots in the Scotland Europa Centre that the Scottish
parliament would have strong ties with the European Union.
Liberal Democrat Graham Watson, who sits in the European Parliament for an
English seat, said the promised Scottish parliament was the result of six years
of talks and 250 years of struggle. ``This is a great day,'' he said. ``It will
be remembered for ever as a great day for Britain and a historic day for
Scotland.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000155</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000155</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>`The United States will stand by those who take risks for peace in Northern Ireland' Clinton promises prosperity for peace</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From ANNE SIMPSON in Belfast</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110425</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIKE socially energetic newcomers to the neighbourhood, a couple called Clinton
moved into Northern Ireland yesterday to distribute calling cards around the
towns.
And in doing so the American President and First Lady have come closer than
anyone to snapping shut the door on a brutal past.
This was the day when history reasserted itself with a brighter face. A day
when, by simply stating the obvious, the world's most powerful citizen turned
mundanity into magic.
It happened through a peculiarly affecting brand of folksiness and
professionalism, and it happened also because on this occasion all sides were
uncommonly willing to listen, knowing that no other speechmaker could enrich
them with so much economic clout.
A factory on the peace line of Belfast was the first potent symbol of the day.
Here Bill Clinton, burly, shrewd and affable in that good guy American way
delivered his initial keynote address on this extraordinary Irish journey.
In a week when ``fudge'' as much as ``peace'' has been the word of the moment,
here was no fudge but a forceful, unambiguous vision, reminding politicians,
paramilitaries and every partisan throng that no single element had the
monopoly on terror: ``Engaging in honest dialogue is not an act of surrender.
It is an act of strength and commonsense.''
Around the world in most locations the self-evidence of that statement would
sound banal. Here in Mackie's vast, unprepossessing shed it already represented
one small victory in an odyssey of deadlock. If heeded, the message will bring
such unrivalled financial investment to Northern Ireland it will never again be
worth the bigot's while to ignore the benefits of social harmony.
That was the promise. Here are the words: ``We will stand with those who take
risks for peace in Northern Ireland. We will do all we can, through the
International Fund for Ireland and in many other ways, to ease your load. We
are entering an era of possibility unparalleled in all human history. If you
enter that era determined to build a new age of peace, the United States of
America will proudly stand by you.''
In one way that signal might almost be read as the speech of a benign
consul-general inspecting a neglected outpost. And maybe it is true that on the
far horizon all three governments involved in this story see Northern Ireland
as some kind of economic territory under the active but ``neutral'' dominion of
America's software imperialists.
In the end, however distant, only prosperity for all - as President Clinton
envisages it - would create round-table agreement for eventual British
withdrawal.
But if that is hurtling too speculatively into the future, it was still
remarkable that here in Northern Ireland there was an American head of state
bringing together representatives from two warring communities in a manner
British and Irish negotiators have never managed to achieve.
So, from the start it was a day of happy incongruity, beginning with the
President's spontaneous decision to halt his 40 limousine motorcade on the
Shankhill and enter a fruitshop where he announced to the stunned proprietor:
``Hi, I'm Bill Clinton and this is my wife Hillary.''
And while Violet Clarke was recovering, he purchased two apples - one red, one
green. Was that a conscious even-handed gesture? All through the visit the
President's sense of balance and attentiveness to tribal sensitivities has been
impressive, and as each venue yesterday proved such a celebratory occasion, one
set of usual protesters didn't seem to mind that he hadn't bought an orange.
But there was one audible voice of dissent. At Mackie's, originally a
Protestant factory but now with a mixed workforce re-establishing its name as a
world leader in light engineering diversity, Bill Clinton, without naming it
directly, put up a challenge to the British Government: ``You must be willing
to say to those who renounce violence, and who do take their own risks for
peace, that they are entitled to be full participants in the democratic
process. Those who show the courage to break with the past are entitled to
their stake in the future.''
There was little doubt that here was a reference to the paramilitaries, and
Sinn Fein in particular, a suggestion also that there should be no delay in
bringing all parties to the table, whatever the situation on the weapons issue.
And it was at this point that a lone voice cried: ``Never!'', only to be
drummed out by the audience's applause.
There was no easy treatment from the President for the merchants of
destruction: ``Your day is over. Violence has no place at the table of
democracy; no role in the future of this land.''
But if he was careful to praise Messrs Major and Bruton, Messrs Hume and
Trimble, and Sinn Fein's Gerry Adams and the Ulster Democratic Party's Gary
McMichael, there was conspicuously no mention of the Rev Ian Paisley. As for
that elusive handshake between Adams and Bill Clinton, it happened on the Falls
Road when the President stopped off for another spot of shopping, this time in
a bakery. Obviously a man addicted to the habit of American snacking. And there
by design was Adams, proffering an accepted hand and wishing Cead mile failte.
By the time the Clintons had reached Derry the mood in both cities had swelled
into one of rapturous festivity. Derry, by ancient lineage, has always been a
nationalist city, the city of Nobel laureate Seamus Heaney, the city of John
Hume, that man whom the President described as a ``tireless champion of civil
rights, its most eloquent voice of non-violence''. In what will now be called
the second Siege of Derry, tens of thousands crowded every approach to the
Guildhall in the shadow of the town's historical walls.
But despite the size of the welcome there remained something homely and
old-fashioned about it, the outdoor podium and battered municipal leather
chairs draped rather haphazardly with green beize, and the Guildhall Square
strung not with sophisticated laser decorations but Christmas lights which had
the dated look of pre-Troubles about them, as if they had been dragged down
from a dusty attic.
There was something touching about the simplicity of the event which culminated
in the President dedicating the Chair in Peace Studies at the University of
Ulster in memory of the late Tip O'Neill, one of America's outstanding
politicians and distinguished Irish-American. Something inevitable too, in the
choice of the President's favourite sing-along tunes, Phil Coulter's folk
anthem, The Town I Loved So Well.
But when Northern Ireland comes to remember this day it will be principally
because some sort of miracle happened: A tiny child called Catherine Hamill
standing on an improvised stage in a factory, telling the President of America
and all the world that her first daddy died in the Troubles ``and it was the
saddest day of my life, but my Christmas wish is that peace and love in Ireland
will last for ever''.
And when they come to recall Big Bill tomorrow and the day after, and the day
after that, it will be as a man who arrived as a conciliator but one of
forthright vision. A man impatient of overcoats, tough enough to stand in the
bitter wind on wounded ground, preferring to be exposed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000156</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000156</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Concise guide to what is proposed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110426</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH CONSTITUTIONAL CONVENTION:
There will be 129 MPs - 73 elected from constituencies (Orkney and Shetland to
be separate) and the other 56 coming from party lists to ensure as far as
possible equal numbers of men and women and parties having the same percentage
of MPs as they have in the overall vote.
Each elector will be entitled to cast two votes - the first for a constituency
member and the second for a local party or group list of additional members.
The Parliament will take over the powers of the Scottish Office including
those over education, law, health, local government, training, transport,
planning, the environment and industry.
Westminster will be left with defence, foreign affairs, immigration, social
security policy and central economic policies.
The Parliament will be financed by an assigned budget along the present lines
from Westminster and will also have the ability to vary income tax up or down
by 3p in the pound.
It will meet in Edinburgh but with committee meetings throughout the rest of
Scotland so that the public can see it in action.
It will have a fixed term of four years with full-time MPs meeting during
normal working hours to avoid the kind of anti-social late-night sittings of
Westminster.
SCOTTISH NATIONAL PARTY:
The Queen and her successors to remain Head of State, but Chancellor of
Scotland, the elected presiding officer of the Scottish Parliament, will act in
this capacity in her absence. Role of monarchy to be redefined and limited.
Bill of Rights, incorporating provisions of European Human Rights Convention,
to guarantee fundamamental liberties including rights to housing, health,
education, ethnic minorities, freedom of speech and freedom of the press.
Extends to areas like language (official status for Gaelic alongside English)
and access to hills and mountains. All to be enforceable by law.
Single chamber of 200 MPs elected by proportional representation. Means to
defer contentious legislation and seek referendum or review by consultative
body. Scottish Prime Minister and Cabinet to run administration. Autonomy of
local government enshrined in constitution and elections on PR basis.
Guarantees for judiciary's independence from executive. Separate commission to
make appointments. Scottish courts final arbiters in all civil and criminal
matters, subject to appeals under European and international law.
Promotion of an Association of States of the British Isles, to include
England, Wales, Northern Ireland and Irish Republic to maintain existing
relationships and act together in areas of common interest. Continuing
membership of European Union, and adoption of Social Chapter. Scotland to
become 186th member of the United Nations.
THE GOVERNMENT:
The Scottish Grand Committee, which comprises all 72 Scottish MPs, will meet
more regularly throughout Scotland and will be attended by senior Ministers up
to the level of Premier.
Important legislation may, however, be steered past the committee, mainly by
appending Scottish changes on to UK legislation.
In any event, the Scottish Grand Committee in taking the second and third
readings of Bills will vote only technically - which means it will only record
the fact that it has held the debates. No actual vote accepting or rejecting
the Bill will be permitted.
The role and remit of the Scottish Economic Council will be extended, as
suggested by the STUC, but full details are still to come.
Powers stripped from local government will be handed back - of a 52-item
``shopping list'' proposed by the Convention of Scottish Local Authorities
around half are likely to be agreed - mainly minor powers.
The key request of an end to capping powers on council spending has been
turned down.
Councils will now be given their whole budget in bigger tranches which leave
them to decide how to divide up their cake, rather than the past practice of
the Scottish Office specifying how the money will be targeted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000157</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000157</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>My first daddy died in the troubles . . . My Christmas wish is that peace and love will last forever</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110427</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO children from opposite sides of Belfast's ``peace line'' made a poignant
and simple plea for a lasting peace yesterday.
President Clinton was visibly moved when the primary school children, a
Catholic girl and a Protestant boy, held hands to welcome him to Mackies
engineering factory in west Belfast.
Catherine Hamill, nine, told Mr Clinton that her first daddy had been killed
during the Troubles and that she wanted peace. ``My Christmas wish is that
peace and love will last in Ireland for ever,'' she said.
David Sterrett, 10, said that peace meant he could play in the park without
worrying about getting shot.
The children were selected to meet Mr Clinton after winning a ``Letter to the
President'' competition in a local newspaper. Their words stayed with the
President and he referred back to them time and again during his keynote speech.
The children read extracts from their letters to Mr Clinton before an audience
of hundreds of invited guests.
``My name is Catherine Hamill. My daddy works as an assistant at Stewarts
Warehouse. I live in Belfast. I love where I live.
``My first daddy died in the Troubles. It was the saddest day of my life. I
still think of him. Now it is nice and peaceful. I like having peace and quiet
for a change, instead of people shooting and killing.
``My Christmas wish is that peace and love will last in Ireland forever. Please
have a safe journey back to America. I hope you enjoyed your visit to Ireland.''
Catherine, from Forfar Street, on the nationalist side of the peace line, was
less than two years old when her father was killed.
Patrick Hamill was outside the house in which his daughter still lives when a
loyalist Ulster Freedom Fighters gunman shot him on September 8, 1987, during a
period of vicious tit-for-tat killings.
Catherine attends St John's Primary School, close to her home, and her letter
was selected from those of 40 children at the school.
David Sterrett, from Clovelly Street, off the Springfield Road, who attends
Springfield Primary, told the President he lived in a mixed area of Catholics
and Protestants.
``We play football and races together. I want to thank you for coming to
Northern Ireland to help the peace process.
``I think the peace is great, because there is no shooting or bombing. It means
I can play in the park without worrying about getting shot.'' When Mr Clinton
began his own plea for a lasting peace he said: ``This is one of those
occasions when I really feel that all that needs to be said has already been
said.''
He said a big part of peace was children growing up safely, learning and
growing together.
Children played a big part in his visit to Belfast. Several hundred welcomed
him at Mackies.
One school beside the M2 motorway into the city gathered all its children in
ranks in the playground to wave as the motorcade sped by.
Catherine Hamill sat in her home last night, proudly watching television news
reruns of her big moment with the President.
She said Mr Clinton had told her that he was very proud of her for reading out
her letter.
``It was so exciting. I just kept thinking `Keep calm Catherine, keep calm',''
she said. ``My mum was so proud, so she was.''
She clutched her letter on which President Clinton had written a personal note:
``Catherine, this is a lovely statement. Thank you for joining me. Bill
Clinton.''
Her mother, Laura, who was in the audience at Mackies, said she cried as she
watched her daughter reading the letter.
``It was unbelievable. It was amazing when the President came out and sat
beside her.''
The letters from Catherine and David were the most moving part of his visit to
Ulster, the President said last night.
Speaking in Londonderry before returning to Belfast, he said: ``A lot of moving
things happened today. But the most moving thing was the two children who stood
and introduced me at the Mackies plant.
``They represented all those children who have written to me about what peace
means to them.''
</TEXT>
