<HEADLINE>Overnight stay at Europa proves a symbol of peace</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110429</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE giant strides made towards peace was symbolised last night by the President
and his entourage staying at the Europa, one of the world's most bombed hotels.
The hotel's deputy general manager, Mr Doug Heady, a New Yorker, has catered
for a President before: he worked at the Hyatt Regency in San Francisco when
Ronald Reagan stayed there in 1984.
He called it ``a lesson in controlled chaos''.
The hotel was a regular target for the IRA during its years of waging economic
warfare. It was bombed 36 times in 25 years.
Home from home to the world's press throughout the bad times, it was the
Europa's proud boast that it never closed, despite the unrelenting terrorist
attacks.
In 1981, then manager Harper Brown was awarded an OBE for his efforts for
keeping the hotel open. The most recent attack was a 1000lb bomb in May 1993.
It cost an estimated #1.75m to put the damage right.
Despite the present peace, a huge security operation was mounted yesterday.
Almost 3000 members of the RUC and more than 100 American Secret Service agents
flung a tight safety cordon around the President wherever he went.
The agents were given special permission by Chief Constable Sir Hugh Annesley
to carry firearms.
Months of planning went into ``Operation Venice'' with US agents constantly
travelling to Belfast for talks with the RUC.
Tensions were heightened on Wednesday night when there were two bomb alerts in
Belfast, one 200 yards down the road from the Europa.
Army bomb disposal experts were called out and the devices, described as
``crude'' by the RUC, were made safe.
Police divers were sent down drains and sewers anywhere near there the
President was to visit and manhole covers were sealed.
Northern Ireland's International airport was ringed by police hours before Air
Force One landed. Sniffer dogs searched every inch of the airfield and its
terminal. Parts of the building were closed and travellers closely checked out.
RUC marksmen were positioned on rooftops.
</TEXT>
