<HEADLINE>Panel in global warming alert</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>From TIM BROWN Madrid, Thursday</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110430</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCIENTISTS warned today of widespread drought, floods, and other extreme
weather conditions in the coming century if steps are not taken to counter
global warming.
For the first time experts from 100 countries from the UN Inter-Governmental
Panel on Climatic Change confirmed that humans were responsible for the change
in climate and warned that the average temperature of the planet could increase
by between 1C and 3.5C over the next century.
Drought would increase, but also there would be more floods and other weather
extremes, said Bert Bolin, the conference president, at the end of the
three-day meeting in the Spanish capital, Madrid.
He added: ``There is now a discernible human influence in the climatic change
which before had only been indicated.''
The experts urged governments to bring in tough controls to cut down on the
emission of gases such as carbon dioxide, nitric oxide, and methane.
A move by oil-producing states, led by Saudi Arabia and Kuwait, to introduce a
footnote that the finding was only preliminary was dropped.
</TEXT>
