<DOCNO>GH951201-000161</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000161</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>An end to the old boys' club raises women's hopes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SUE INNES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110431</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE increased role for women was described by Isobel Lindsay, of the Campaign
for a Scottish Parliament, as ``the most revolutionary thing that has happened
in Scottish and British politics since women got the vote''.
The result of ``equal representation of men and women'' for a Scottish
Parliament would change Scotland from having one of the lowest levels of women
as elected representatives to one of the highest in Europe.
Such decisive change is possible because it is a new parliament. ``The simple
fact that you are starting off with no `incumbency factor', no bums already on
seats means equality becomes not just theoretically desirable but practically
possible,'' Ms Lindsay said.
For many people active in the constitutional debate gender equality has now
come to symbolise a better form of politics; a principle seen as wildly radical
at first has come to express ``the good society''.
It is, observes writer Tom Nairn, ``an emblem of the kind of country and the
style of nationalism people really want''.
Creating ``the first legislature of modern times to fully acknowledge the
equality of genders'' has, he thinks , stirred something very fundamental to
the Scottish sense of democracy.
Canon Kenyon Wright, convener of the Constitutional Convention, described the
electoral contract, when it was introduced, as ``the most important thing for
the future of Scotland''.
Although some male politicians have complained that this will ruin their
careers, debate has been notably less polarised than around all-women
short-lists in the Labour Party.
From the beginning this has been about much more than numbers. Most believe
that bringing more women in will have consequences for the style of government,
creating a more issue-based and consensual legislature.
The issue came alive in 1989 with the Women's Claim of Right and the idea from
the STUC's women's committee of one man and one woman for every parliamentary
seat.
The relative strength of the women's movement in Scotland and its willingness
to engage with party politics has been critical, particularly the role played
by a network of feminist groups and women from the trade unions.
The means to equality finally arrived at the unique electoral contract which
was signed by George Robertson and Jim Wallace last Thursday. It is not a
statutory agreement but it is workable: Scottish Liberal Democrat Marilyn
McLaren insists it is ``politically binding'' and Isobel Lindsay emphasises
that it will be incorporated into party rules.
Both parties agreed to field equal numbers of women and men candidates for both
winnable and marginal seats, but each will achieve that in different ways.
Labour is likely to use a modified version of all-women shortlists adapted to
paired constituencies, though they will continue to campaign for a statutory
50/50 in the parliament. The Lib Dems will use the additional member ``top up''
to ensure equal numbers, a departure from their policy in England and Wales of
encouragement but non-intervention.
In practice it is likely to deliver close to gender equality, rather than a
perfect 50/50. The SNP and the Tories - though not part of the convention -
also look likely to field more women candidates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
