<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jaffna `to fall in days'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110432</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Colombo, Thursday
THE Sri Lankan army had captured more than half of Jaffna town and would bring
the entire rebel stronghold under its control in a ``couple of days'', a
military spokesman said.
Brigadier Sarath Munasinghe said: ``Give us a couple more days, this Jaffna
town will be entirely ours. There's no doubt about that.''
Munasinghe told a news conference in Colombo that the troops had less than half
of the northern citadel of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) to take.
``As of Wednesday, we had captured more than half of Jaffna town,'' he added.
He said the military still had to take control of the town centre where the
rebels were resisting.
Munasinghe said rebels trapped inside the town were heard ``screaming for
ammunition, help, and medical help''.
Rebel radio today reported heavy fighting around the suburbs of Jaffna, saying
the Tigers had slowed the army's advance.
Meanwhile, the government this week offered a two-week amnesty to the thousands
of men who have deserted the military in the past five years as the separatist
war intensified.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
