<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000163</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000163</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Parties have crosses to bear for St Andrew's Day</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBBIE DINWOODIE Scottish Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110433</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was St Andrew's Day Jim, but not as we know it.
Unlike the Irish, who make a ridiculous song and dance of their national day to
the extent of dying their beer green, the Scots normally keep quiet about their
saint's day.
Yesterday was much the same as usual, except among a certain type of person
(the political/journalistic animal) and a certain place (Edinburgh). While the
rest of the country carried on its usual practice of ignoring the day, the
capital was hit by a wave of something nastier than influenza. Indeed, one good
sneeze yesterday and the entire chattering class would have been infected.
A city officer from the district council read a proclamation from the Mercat
Cross and the only people present were a bevvy of journalists, a sneer of
politicians, and a gaggle of Japanese tourists. Perhaps the city fathers should
have given him a bigger bell, or even better, the organisers might have staged
a damned good hanging.
By then, the likely recipient of this hanging had already stolen the media
thunder by holding the first photo-opportunity and press conference of the day.
The photo was an odd one, stunted in front of the old Royal High School
building. However hostile the intent, it was hard to escape the impression that
using the proposed Parliament building as a backdrop was sending out the wrong
subliminal message.
At the press conference there was the same nervous edge. Does anyone really
believe that Canon Kenyon Wright is somehow a dangerous and sinister figure,
comparable to Stalin? And yet Michael Forsyth went out of his way to point out
that as a former head of CND in Scotland the Canon had been seen off, without
which ``the people of Eastern Europe would still be in chains''.
Over at the Assembly Hall of the Church of Scotland the Canon cut a distinctly
less sinister figure, cracking some splendid jokes about the uncomfortable
seating and delivering bits of his speech in French and German. ``You'll be
glad to know I canny manage the other nine languages,'' he assured us.
A friend had told him that he would never get a consensus but if he did succeed
political opponents would sit up and take notice. ``We did. They have,'' he
said. He also had the best metaphor of the day, saying of Michael Forsyth's
proposals: ``This is the State's attempt at a cosmetic smile, to be crudely
painted on for any intelligent Scot to be taken in.''
The standing ovation, when it came, was unstaged, slow to build, and as far
from the stunted adulation of party conferences as it is possible to imagine.
Kenyon Wright spoke afterwards of simultaneous pleasure and embarrassment at
the moment.
Having said that, one of the other churchmen who spoke seemed to have stumbled
into the wrong meeting. Congregational minister the Rev Robert Waters startled
some by announcing: ``In the long-run, I guess Scotland will become an
independent nation once again.''
Meanwhile, the meeting at which he should have announced this was taking place
a few hundred yards away at Edinburgh City Chambers. The SNP launched its own
constitutional vision - actually a coddled together report of various old
policy reports and conference decisions, but who can blame them for not wanting
to miss the show?
You could tell this was the nationalist event. It was held in the European
Room, there wasn't a bit of tartan in sight (even SNP Lord Provost Norman Irons
eschewed the kilt for the day), there was no bagpipes, not even a wee bit of
shortbread. Monsieur Salmond, who was about to jet across to Bruxelles, was in
full Euro-mode, the only giveaway being MacDiarmid's little white rose of
Scotland pinned to his lapel.
By the time the day's constitutional roadshow moved on to Glasgow last night
everyone was getting weary. Michael Forsyth held a press conference to repeat
everything he had said early in the morning. Former Tory MPAlan Clark, doing a
St Andrew's Day colour piece for a Sunday newspaper, was wearing the glazed
look of a man entering the first state of post traumatic stress syndrome, and
Michael Forsyth was explaining once more the close affinity between an
Episcopalian churchman and Joseph Stalin.
As the BBC reported that his Dick Stewart Memorial lecture was already wowing
them at Strathclyde University, the Scottish Secretary was still stuck in a
traffic jam.
The principal, Professor John Arbuthnott, explained that Mr Forsyth was
educated at Arbroath and St Andrews. ``At this time of the year we look to wise
men from the East bearing gifts,'' he explained. Mr Forsyth, having mugged
local authorities of their powers for years, dipped into his poacher's pocket
and committed the offence of political reset.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000164</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000164</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Former premier offered arms job</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110434</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FORMER Prime Minister and an Army Chief-of-Staff have been named as members
of the international body being set up to oversee the controversial arms
decommissioning element of the Northern Ireland peace process.
The appointments of one-time Finnish premier Harri Holkeri and General John de
Chastelain, Canadian Army chief, were confirmed by the British and Irish
governments last night.
The nominations were agreed, subject to both men accepting the posts, as part
of the agreement struck in Downing Street late on Tuesday night by Prime
Minister John Major and his Irish counterpart John Bruton in a bid to break the
long-running peace process deadlock.
General de Chastelain, 58, has been Canadian Defence Chief of Staff since 1989,
except for a period of a year from 1993, when he was his country's ambassador
in Washington.
Mr Holkeri, also 58, was Prime Minister of Finland between 1987 and 1991.
The international body is being chaired by former United States Senator George
Mitchell, a senior aide of President Bill Clinton.
The full make-up of the group, and the status of the three appointees, is being
seen as an indication of the crucial importance being attached to the body in
London, Dublin and Washington.
The international body has been set up by the two governments to conduct ``an
independent assessment'' of the arms decommissioning issue.
They hope it will resolve the still-in-contention stipulation by Britain that
the IRA has to move towards decommissioning its weapons ahead of Sinn Fein's
entry into all-party talks on the future of Northern Ireland.
While the body undertakes its work, with a report expected by the middle of
January, preparatory talks are to go on involving the political parties in
Northern Ireland.
That twin-track approach is planned to pave the way to all-inclusive
discussions, possibly by the end of February.
The Prime Minister has made it clear the international body will be advisory.
It will consult ``all relevant parties'' on the arms issue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951201-000165</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951201-000165</DOCID>
<DATE>951201</DATE>
<HEADLINE>President tipped to make his a stout</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975110435</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE better-known pleasures of Ireland are on Bill Clinton's schedule today as
he takes time off to sample the Guinness in a typical Dublin pub.
Regulars at Cassidy's Wine and Tea merchants' premises in Camden Street have
been told to stand by their pints late in the afternoon.
American security men called at the 105-year-old city centre bar - recognised
as one of Dublin's finest by those in the know - at least six times before
declaring it suitable for a presidential visit, listed as ``an unscheduled
event'' on the official itinerary.
The pub fits the Clinton bill in several ways as Cassidy was reputedly the name
of the President's mother's family.
If he downs a pint of stout, Mr Clinton will follow the example of Ronald
Reagan, who stopped for a drink in his ancestral home village of Ballyporeen,
County Tipperary, in 1984.
His visit will be the fourth to Ireland by a US head of state.
The most celebrated was by John Kennedy, months before his 1963 assassination.
Richard Nixon was in the country in 1974.
Dublin will get its best chance to see the present US leader when he addresses
a rally outside the city's Trinity College university.
Minutes earlier he will receive the freedom of Dublin, and afterwards a Clinton
walk-about is likely.
More than 3000 Irish police and troops - as well as about 100 American agents -
will be on duty.
An Irish police spokesman said: ``There is no particular menace to President
Clinton here, but every possible security measure is being implemented.''
Mr Clinton's busy schedule includes a call on President Mary Robinson at her
official residence in Dublin's Phoenix Park, talks with Irish Prime Minister
John Bruton, an address to a joint session of the Dail and Senate houses of
parliament and a dinner   hosted by the Irish Government at Dublin Castle.
</TEXT>
